ople of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American Christian Zionists]]\n[[Category:Biden family]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Delaware]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:County council members and commissioners in Delaware]]\n[[Category:Delaware Democrats]]\n[[Category:Delaware Fightin' Blue Hens football players]]\n[[Category:Delaware Independents]]\n[[Category:Delaware lawyers]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party (United States) vice presidential nominees]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party United States senators]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party Vice Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Castle County, Delaware politicians]]\n[[Category:Obama administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:People from Claymont, Delaware]]\n[[Category:People from Wilmington, Delaware]]\n[[Category:People involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Scranton, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Public defenders]]\n[[Category:Real property lawyers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of St. George's Order of Victory]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Liberty (Ukraine)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana, 1st Class]]\n[[Category:Syracuse University College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:United States senators from Delaware]]\n[[Category:University of Delaware alumni]]\n[[Category:Vice Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Widener University faculty]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Hilal-i-Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Chairmen of the Senate Committee on Foreign Relations]]\n", "name_user": "SPECIFICO", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAllegations of inappropriate physical contact and sexual assault", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Biden"}
{"title_page": "Large-scale social restrictions", "text_new": "{{Current}}\n'''Large-scale social restrictions''' ([[Indonesian language|Indonesian]]: ''Pembatasan Sosial Berskala Besar'' or '''PSBB''') are currently in place in [[Indonesia]] in response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Indonesia|coronavirus pandemic]]. The restrictions are implemented by local governments with the approval of the [[Ministry of Health (Indonesia)|Ministry of Health]], and includes measures such as closing public spaces, restricting public transport, to limiting travel to and from the restricted region.\n\nAs of 15 April 2020, the restrictions has been approved or are in place for the entirety of [[Greater Jakarta]].\n==Background==\nThe first case of [[COVID-19]] was confirmed in Indonesia on 2 March 2020, with two residents of [[Depok]], [[West Java]] testing positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=BREAKING: Jokowi announces Indonesia\u2019s first two confirmed COVID-19 cases |url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/02/breaking-jokowi-announces-indonesias-first-two-confirmed-covid-19-cases.html |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Jakarta Post |date=2 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> By 15 March, with 117 confirmed cases, President [[Joko Widodo]] had called for Indonesians to exercise [[social distancing]] measures, with some regional leaders in [[Jakarta]], [[Banten]] and West Java already closing down schools and public places.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jokowi calls for \u2018social distancing\u2019 to stem virus spread |url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/15/jokowi-calls-for-social-distancing-to-stem-virus-spread.html |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Jakarta Post |date=15 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In a statement the following day, he stated that he was not going for lockdowns, and lightly criticized regional leaders which did implement lockdowns.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jokowi: Indonesia Tidak Perlu Lockdown |url=https://www.kompas.tv/article/71535/jokowi-indonesia-tidak-perlu-lockdown |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=KOMPAS.tv |date=16 March 2020 |language=id}}</ref> By 27 March, [[Dedy Yon Supriyono]], mayor of the city of [[Tegal (city)|Tegal]], [[Central Java]] had announced that the city would be implementing a local lockdown measure, closing off multiple access points to and from the city, the first locality to do so in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jadi Kota Pertama di Indonesia, Tegal Lockdown Selama 4 Bulan |url=https://jateng.suara.com/read/2020/03/26/212323/jadi-kota-pertama-di-indonesia-tegal-lockdown-selama-4-bulan |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Suara Jateng |date=26 March 2020 |language=id}}</ref>\n==Legal basis==\nOn 31 March 2020, Jokowi signed into law Government Regulation 21/2020, which regulated large-scale social restrictions, allowing regional governments to restrict the movement of people and goods in and out of their respective localities provided they had received permission from the relevant ministry (in this case the [[Ministry of Health (Indonesia)|Ministry of Health]], under [[Terawan Agus Putranto]]). The law also defined a \"minimal\" restriction as including school and work holidays, limitations on physical worship, and limitations on public gatherings. At the same time, Presidential Decision 11/2020 was also signed, declaring a national disaster. Both laws were based on the Law No. 6 of 2018 on Medical Quarantines, which had provisions for PSBB.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kebijakan PSBB Harus Mendapat \u2018Restu\u2019 Pemerintah Pusat |url=https://www.hukumonline.com/berita/baca/lt5e847795ecc2f/kebijakan-psbb-harus-mendapat-restu-pemerintah-pusat/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=hukumonline.com |date=1 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pembatasan Sosial Berskala Besar Berhak Batasi Orang Keluar Masuk Suatu Daerah |url=https://nasional.kompas.com/read/2020/04/01/11054771/pembatasan-sosial-berskala-besar-berhak-batasi-orang-keluar-masuk-suatu |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=KOMPAS.com |date=1 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=PP Nomor 21 Tahun 2020 |url=https://jdih.setkab.go.id/PUUdoc/176085/PP_Nomor_21_Tahun_2020.pdf |publisher=[[Government of Indonesia]] |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref>\n==By area==\nAs of 15 April 2020, PSBB has been only formally approved or implemented in areas included within [[Greater Jakarta]].\n===Jakarta===\n[[Governor of Jakarta]] [[Anies Baswedan]] applied for a PSBB implementation in the capital on 4 April 2020, the first region to formally do so, and the request was approved on 6 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Disetujui Menkes, PSBB DKI Jakarta Mulai Berlaku Selasa 7 April 2020 |url=https://nasional.kompas.com/read/2020/04/07/11582841/disetujui-menkes-psbb-dki-jakarta-mulai-berlaku-selasa-7-april-2020?page=all |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=KOMPAS.com |date=7 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref> The lockdown measure came into place on 10 April, and was initially intended to remain in place for 14 days. Jakarta's PSBB restricted [[Motorcycle taxi|motorcycle taxis]] from carrying passengers, banned eating in at restaurants (though allowed takeaways), made it obligatory for hotels to accept people who are self-isolating, and required sporting activities to be done within the vicinity of one's own home.<ref>{{cite news |title=Yang Perlu Diketahui dari PSBB Jakarta yang Berlaku Hari Ini |url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4971980/yang-perlu-diketahui-dari-psbb-jakarta-yang-berlaku-hari-ini |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=detiknews |date=10 April 2020 |language=id-ID}}</ref> Schools, entertainment sites, and some other locations were closed down, while public transport was limited to operating at 50 percent capacity.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ikhsanudin |first1=Arief |title=Lengkap, Ini Panduan Resmi Aktivitas Warga Saat PSBB di Jakarta |url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4976368/lengkap-ini-panduan-resmi-aktivitas-warga-saat-psbb-di-jakarta |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=detiknews |date=14 April 2020 |language=id-ID}}</ref> Only those fulfilling \"basic needs\" and those working in certain sectors are allowed to leave their houses, and they would be required to wear face masks.<ref>{{cite news |title=Selama PSBB di Jakarta, Warga Wajib Pakai Masker Saat Keluar Rumah |url=https://megapolitan.kompas.com/read/2020/04/09/22562861/selama-psbb-di-jakarta-warga-wajib-pakai-masker-saat-keluar-rumah |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=KOMPAS.com |date=9 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref>\n\nTo enforce these measures, the [[Greater Jakarta Metropolitan Regional Police]] set up checkpoints on main roads and bus terminals, numbering 33 initially.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jakarta Tambah Titik Pengawasan PSBB, Bogor Siapkan 10 Titik |url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200413144817-20-493063/jakarta-tambah-titik-pengawasan-psbb-bogor-siapkan-10-titik |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=CNN Indonesia |date=13 April 2020 |language=id-ID}}</ref> Due to the economic impact of the lockdown, the provincial government established a program to deliver basic supplies including food, medical masks, and soap to poorer residents of the city impacted by the lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dinsos Minta Warga DKI Tak Dapat Bansos Lapor RW |url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200413161546-20-493102/dinsos-minta-warga-dki-tak-dapat-bansos-lapor-rw |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=CNN Indonesia |date=13 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref>\n===Banten===\nPSBB for the Greater Tangerang area (i.e. [[Tangerang|Tangerang City]], [[South Tangerang]] and [[Tangerang Regency]]) was approved by the Ministry of Health on 12 April.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Adyatama |first1=Egi |title=Terawan Jelaskan Alasan Setujui Status PSBB Banten |url=https://nasional.tempo.co/read/1330785/terawan-jelaskan-alasan-setujui-status-psbb-banten/full&view=ok |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Tempo |date=12 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref> The restrictions, set to come into effect on 18 April, would permit factories to continue running, though they were required to exercise social distancing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sejumlah Aturan Jelang Penerapan PSBB di Kota Tangerang |url=https://megapolitan.kompas.com/read/2020/04/14/08585291/sejumlah-aturan-jelang-penerapan-psbb-di-kota-tangerang?page=all |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=KOMPAS.com |date=14 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref> \n===West Java===\n[[West Java]] Governor [[Ridwan Kamil]] issued PSBB orders for [[Bogor]], [[Bogor Regency]], [[Depok]], [[Bekasi]] and [[Bekasi Regency]], initially in effect between 15 and 28 April 2020, extendable if the virus continued to spread. Similar to Jakarta's, the measures restricted work except for certain vital sectors, limited study and worship activities (except studies related to healthcare research), and restricted passenger counts in all vehicles, including public transport and private cars.<ref>{{cite news |title=Isi Peraturan PSBB Bogor, Depok & Bekasi yang Diteken Ridwan Kamil |url=https://tirto.id/isi-peraturan-psbb-bogor-depok-bekasi-yang-diteken-ridwan-kamil-eMZB |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=tirto.id |date=13 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{COVID-19}}\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Containment efforts related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Country subdivisions lockdowns]] <!-- Because it's a lot of subdivisions locked down separately, not a national decision -->\n[[Category:History of Indonesia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Current}}\n'''Large-scale social restrictions''' ([[Indonesian language|Indonesian]]: ''Pembatasan Sosial Berskala Besar'' or '''PSBB''') are currently in place in [[Indonesia]] in response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Indonesia|coronavirus pandemic]]. The restrictions are implemented by local governments with the approval of the [[Ministry of Health (Indonesia)|Ministry of Health]], and includes measures such as closing public spaces, restricting public transport, to limiting travel to and from the restricted region.\n\nAs of 15 April 2020, the restrictions has been approved or are in place for the entirety of [[Greater Jakarta]].\n==Background==\nThe first case of [[COVID-19]] was confirmed in Indonesia on 2 March 2020, with two residents of [[Depok]], [[West Java]] testing positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=BREAKING: Jokowi announces Indonesia\u2019s first two confirmed COVID-19 cases |url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/02/breaking-jokowi-announces-indonesias-first-two-confirmed-covid-19-cases.html |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Jakarta Post |date=2 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> By 15 March, with 117 confirmed cases, President [[Joko Widodo]] had called for Indonesians to exercise [[social distancing]] measures, with some regional leaders in [[Jakarta]], [[Banten]] and West Java already closing down schools and public places.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jokowi calls for \u2018social distancing\u2019 to stem virus spread |url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/15/jokowi-calls-for-social-distancing-to-stem-virus-spread.html |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Jakarta Post |date=15 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In a statement the following day, he stated that he was not going for lockdowns, and lightly criticized regional leaders which did implement lockdowns.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jokowi: Indonesia Tidak Perlu Lockdown |url=https://www.kompas.tv/article/71535/jokowi-indonesia-tidak-perlu-lockdown |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=KOMPAS.tv |date=16 March 2020 |language=id}}</ref> By 27 March, [[Dedy Yon Supriyono]], mayor of the city of [[Tegal (city)|Tegal]], [[Central Java]] had announced that the city would be implementing a local lockdown measure, closing off multiple access points to and from the city, the first locality to do so in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jadi Kota Pertama di Indonesia, Tegal Lockdown Selama 4 Bulan |url=https://jateng.suara.com/read/2020/03/26/212323/jadi-kota-pertama-di-indonesia-tegal-lockdown-selama-4-bulan |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Suara Jateng |date=26 March 2020 |language=id}}</ref>\n==Legal basis==\nOn 31 March 2020, Jokowi signed into law Government Regulation 21/2020, which regulated large-scale social restrictions, allowing regional governments to restrict the movement of people and goods in and out of their respective localities provided they had received permission from the relevant ministry (in this case the [[Ministry of Health (Indonesia)|Ministry of Health]], under [[Terawan Agus Putranto]]). The law also defined a \"minimal\" restriction as including school and work holidays, limitations on physical worship, and limitations on public gatherings. At the same time, Presidential Decision 11/2020 was also signed, declaring a national disaster. Both laws were based on the Law No. 6 of 2018 on Medical Quarantines, which had provisions for PSBB.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kebijakan PSBB Harus Mendapat \u2018Restu\u2019 Pemerintah Pusat |url=https://www.hukumonline.com/berita/baca/lt5e847795ecc2f/kebijakan-psbb-harus-mendapat-restu-pemerintah-pusat/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=hukumonline.com |date=1 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pembatasan Sosial Berskala Besar Berhak Batasi Orang Keluar Masuk Suatu Daerah |url=https://nasional.kompas.com/read/2020/04/01/11054771/pembatasan-sosial-berskala-besar-berhak-batasi-orang-keluar-masuk-suatu |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=KOMPAS.com |date=1 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=PP Nomor 21 Tahun 2020 |url=https://jdih.setkab.go.id/PUUdoc/176085/PP_Nomor_21_Tahun_2020.pdf |publisher=[[Government of Indonesia]] |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref>\n==By area==\n{{Expand list|date=April 2020}}\nAs of 15 April 2020, PSBB has been only formally approved or implemented in areas included within [[Greater Jakarta]].\n===Jakarta===\n[[Governor of Jakarta]] [[Anies Baswedan]] applied for a PSBB implementation in the capital on 4 April 2020, the first region to formally do so, and the request was approved on 6 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Disetujui Menkes, PSBB DKI Jakarta Mulai Berlaku Selasa 7 April 2020 |url=https://nasional.kompas.com/read/2020/04/07/11582841/disetujui-menkes-psbb-dki-jakarta-mulai-berlaku-selasa-7-april-2020?page=all |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=KOMPAS.com |date=7 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref> The lockdown measure came into place on 10 April, and was initially intended to remain in place for 14 days. Jakarta's PSBB restricted [[Motorcycle taxi|motorcycle taxis]] from carrying passengers, banned eating in at restaurants (though allowed takeaways), made it obligatory for hotels to accept people who are self-isolating, and required sporting activities to be done within the vicinity of one's own home.<ref>{{cite news |title=Yang Perlu Diketahui dari PSBB Jakarta yang Berlaku Hari Ini |url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4971980/yang-perlu-diketahui-dari-psbb-jakarta-yang-berlaku-hari-ini |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=detiknews |date=10 April 2020 |language=id-ID}}</ref> Schools, entertainment sites, and some other locations were closed down, while public transport was limited to operating at 50 percent capacity.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ikhsanudin |first1=Arief |title=Lengkap, Ini Panduan Resmi Aktivitas Warga Saat PSBB di Jakarta |url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4976368/lengkap-ini-panduan-resmi-aktivitas-warga-saat-psbb-di-jakarta |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=detiknews |date=14 April 2020 |language=id-ID}}</ref> Only those fulfilling \"basic needs\" and those working in certain sectors are allowed to leave their houses, and they would be required to wear face masks.<ref>{{cite news |title=Selama PSBB di Jakarta, Warga Wajib Pakai Masker Saat Keluar Rumah |url=https://megapolitan.kompas.com/read/2020/04/09/22562861/selama-psbb-di-jakarta-warga-wajib-pakai-masker-saat-keluar-rumah |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=KOMPAS.com |date=9 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref>\n\nTo enforce these measures, the [[Greater Jakarta Metropolitan Regional Police]] set up checkpoints on main roads and bus terminals, numbering 33 initially.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jakarta Tambah Titik Pengawasan PSBB, Bogor Siapkan 10 Titik |url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200413144817-20-493063/jakarta-tambah-titik-pengawasan-psbb-bogor-siapkan-10-titik |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=CNN Indonesia |date=13 April 2020 |language=id-ID}}</ref> Due to the economic impact of the lockdown, the provincial government established a program to deliver basic supplies including food, medical masks, and soap to poorer residents of the city impacted by the lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dinsos Minta Warga DKI Tak Dapat Bansos Lapor RW |url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200413161546-20-493102/dinsos-minta-warga-dki-tak-dapat-bansos-lapor-rw |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=CNN Indonesia |date=13 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref>\n===Banten===\nPSBB for the Greater Tangerang area (i.e. [[Tangerang|Tangerang City]], [[South Tangerang]] and [[Tangerang Regency]]) was approved by the Ministry of Health on 12 April.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Adyatama |first1=Egi |title=Terawan Jelaskan Alasan Setujui Status PSBB Banten |url=https://nasional.tempo.co/read/1330785/terawan-jelaskan-alasan-setujui-status-psbb-banten/full&view=ok |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Tempo |date=12 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref> The restrictions, set to come into effect on 18 April, would permit factories to continue running, though they were required to exercise social distancing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sejumlah Aturan Jelang Penerapan PSBB di Kota Tangerang |url=https://megapolitan.kompas.com/read/2020/04/14/08585291/sejumlah-aturan-jelang-penerapan-psbb-di-kota-tangerang?page=all |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=KOMPAS.com |date=14 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref> \n===West Java===\n[[West Java]] Governor [[Ridwan Kamil]] issued PSBB orders for [[Bogor]], [[Bogor Regency]], [[Depok]], [[Bekasi]] and [[Bekasi Regency]], initially in effect between 15 and 28 April 2020, extendable if the virus continued to spread. Similar to Jakarta's, the measures restricted work except for certain vital sectors, limited study and worship activities (except studies related to healthcare research), and restricted passenger counts in all vehicles, including public transport and private cars.<ref>{{cite news |title=Isi Peraturan PSBB Bogor, Depok & Bekasi yang Diteken Ridwan Kamil |url=https://tirto.id/isi-peraturan-psbb-bogor-depok-bekasi-yang-diteken-ridwan-kamil-eMZB |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=tirto.id |date=13 April 2020 |language=id}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{COVID-19}}\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Containment efforts related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Country subdivisions lockdowns]] <!-- Because it's a lot of subdivisions locked down separately, not a national decision -->\n[[Category:History of Indonesia]]\n", "name_user": "Juxlos", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBy area", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Large-scale_social_restrictions"}
{"title_page": "Jacques Blamont", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|French astrophysicist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                    = Jacques Blamont\n| image                   = Jacques_Blamont,_2015_(cropped).jpg\n| imagesize               =\n| caption                 =\n|birth_name=Jacques Emile Blamont\n| birth_date              = 13 October 1926\n| birth_place             = [[Paris]], [[French Third Republic|France]]\n| death_date              = {{death date and age|2020|4|13|1926|10|13|df=y}}\n| death_place             = [[Ch\u00e2tillon, Hauts-de-Seine|Ch\u00e2tillon]], France\n| restingplace            =\n| restingplacecoordinates =\n| othername               =\n| occupation              = [[Astrophysicist]]\n| yearsactive             = 1948\u20132020\n| known for               = Aerospace programmes\n| spouse                  =\n| domesticpartner         =\n| children                =\n| parents                 =\n| website                 =\n| awards                  = [[Padma Shri]]<br>[[Commander of the Legion of Honour]]<br>[[National Order of Merit (France)|Grand Officer of the National Order of Merit]]<br>[[Ordre des Palmes Acad\u00e9miques|Commander of the Academic Palms]]<br>[[National Order of Merit (France)|Grand Cross of the National Order of Merit]]<br>Rovel H. Prize<br>[[Aim\u00e9 Cotton]] Prize<br>Leon Grelaud Prize<br>[[CNES]] Vermeil Medal<br>Prize Doisteau Paul - \u00c9mile Blutet<br>[[President of France|President's]] Silver Medal<br>[[Daniel and Florence Guggenheim Foundation|Daniel and Florence Guggenheim]] Award<br>[[NASA]] Exceptional Scientific Achievement Medal<br>[[USSR Academy of Sciences]] Gagarin Medal<br>[[International Academy of Astronautics|IAA]] Guggenheim Medal<br>[[Soviet Order of Friendship of Peoples]]<br>[[International Academy of Astronautics|IAA]] [[Theodore von Karman Medal]]<br>[[Indian Space Research Organization|ISRO]] [[Vikram Sarabhai]] Medal<br>[[Guiana Space Center]] Gold Medal<br>Spie prize<br>French Roberval Prize<br>[[International Society for Optical Engineering|ISOE]] George N. Goddard Award<br>[[NASA]] Distinguished Service Medal<br>COSPAR Space Science Award\n}}\n'''Jacques Emile Blamont''' ({{IPA-fr|\u0292ak bla.m\u0254\u0303|}}; 13 October 1926&nbsp;\u2013 13 April 2020) was a French [[astrophysicist]]<ref name=\"Interview de Jacques Blamont\">{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6VUpicNBMzg | title=Interview de Jacques Blamont | publisher=Thinkerview | work=[[YouTube]] video | date=30 January 2013 | accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Interview\">{{cite web | url=http://www.automatesintelligents.com/interviews/2004/oct/blamont.html | title=Interview with Jacques Blamont | publisher=Jean-Paul Baquiast and Christophe Jacquemin | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref> author and the founder scientific and technical director of [[CNES|National Centre for Space Studies]] (CNES-Centre national d'\u00e9tudes spatiales), known to have contributed to the development of [[V\u00e9ronique (rocket)|Veronique]], the first rocket launched by France in 1957.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\">{{cite web | url=http://www.academie-sciences.fr/academie/membre/BlamontJ_bio0909.pdf | title=Royal Academy of Sciences profile | publisher=Royal Academy of Sciences | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"Planetary Society\">{{cite web | url=http://www.planetary.org/connect/our-experts/profiles/jacques-blamont.html | title=Planetary Society | publisher=Planetary Society | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref> He was an elected fellow of the [[French Academy of Technologies]]<ref name=\"NATF Fellow\">{{cite web | url=http://www.academie-technologies.fr/en/directories/B | title=NATF Fellow | publisher=NATF | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref> and a professor emeritus of the [[Pierre and Marie Curie University]] (University of Paris VI).<ref name=\"Diploweb\">{{cite web | url=http://www.diploweb.com/_Jacques-BLAMONT_.html | title=Diploweb | publisher=Diploweb | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nBlamont was a recipient of several national honours such as [[Commander of the Legion of Honour]], the third highest French civilian honour, [[National Order of Merit (France)|Grand Officer of the National Order of Merit]], the second highest French civilian honour, [[Ordre des Palmes Acad\u00e9miques|Commander of the Academic Palms]], [[National Order of Merit (France)|Grand Cross of the National Order of Merit]], the highest French civilian honour, [[President of France|President's]] Silver Medal, [[Soviet Order of Friendship of Peoples]] and [[Padma Shri]], the fourth highest Indian civilian award.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=114952 |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Padma Awards |date=2015 |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6VrWjEuo3?url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=114952 |archivedate=26 January 2015 }}</ref>\n\nBlamont died on 13 April 2020 in [[Ch\u00e2tillon, Hauts-de-Seine]], aged 93.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/disparitions/article/2020/04/14/l-astrophysicien-jacques-blamont-un-des-peres-de-l-aventure-spatiale-francaise-est-mort_6036491_3382.html |last=Augereau |first=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois |title=L\u2019astrophysicien, Jacques Blamont, un des p\u00e8res de l\u2019aventure spatiale fran\u00e7aise, est mort |date=14 April 2020 |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=[[Le Monde]]}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nJacques Blamont was born in Paris in France on 13 October 1926<ref name=\"NATF Profile\">{{cite web | url=http://www.academie-technologies.fr/en/members/152-jacques-blamont | title=NATF Profile | publisher=NATF | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Rise of the West\">{{cite web | url=http://www.riseofthewest.net/thinkers/blamont01.htm | title=Rise of the West | publisher=Rise of the West | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> and did his studies at the [[\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure]]<ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /> where he came in contact with the [[Nobel laureate]], [[Alfred Kastler]], who was serving the institution as a professorial chair.<ref name=\"Kastler\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nobel-winners.com/Physics/alfred_kastler.html | title=Kastler | publisher=Nobelwinners.com | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> He graduated from [[\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure]] in 1948<ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> and continued his studies at the [[National Centre for Scientific Research]] (CNRS) as an associate of physical sciences.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /> In 1952, he reunited with Alfred Kastler in research on ''atomic coherence phenomenon'' and secured his doctoral degree (Doctor of Science) under his guidance in 1956.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /><ref name=\"Rise of the West\" />\n\nBlamont continued at [[CNRS]] for a year more as a research fellow<ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /> and joined the Aeronomy Service of the institution in 1957 where he became the deputy director in 1958.<ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /> In 1961, he was promoted as the director, a post he held till 1985.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /><ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /> He worked in many capacities during his stay with CNES, as a Scientific and Technical Director (1962-1972), as Top Scientific Advisor (1972-1982) and as an advisor to the President of CNES<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> from 1982.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /><ref name=\"American Philosophical Society\">{{cite web | url=http://www.amphilsoc.org/memhist/search?creator=Blamont&title=&subject=&subdiv=&mem=&year=&year-max=&dead=&keyword=&smode=advanced | title=American Philosophical Society | publisher=American Philosophical Society | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> During this period, he served the [[Pierre and Marie Curie University]] as a professor without chair from 1957 to 1961, as a full professor from 1962 to 1996 and as a professor emeritus from there on.<ref name=\"Planetary Society\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /><ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /><ref name=\"American Philosophical Society\" /><ref name=\"Academy reference\">{{cite web | url=http://www.academie-sciences.fr/academie/membre/Blamont_Jacques.htm | title=Academy reference | publisher=Academy of Sciences | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402150505/http://www.academie-sciences.fr/academie/membre/Blamont_Jacques.htm | archive-date=2 April 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> He also worked as a research director at [[\u00c9cole Militaire]] (Joint Defence College).<ref name=\"NATF Profile\" />\n\nHe was made the first [[Vikram Sarabhai]] professor at the [[Physical Research Laboratory]] in 1977,<ref name=\"Vikram Professor\" >{{cite web | url=https://www.prl.res.in/prl-eng/vikram_professor | title=Vikram Professor | publisher=Physical Research Laboratory |date=2020 |accessdate=13 April 2020 }}</ref> a visiting professor at the [[California Institute of Technology]] in 1985 and a distinguished visiting scientist at [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]] during 1980\u20132001.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /> He was a member of [[International Academy of Astronautics]] (1969),<ref name=\"International Academy of Astronautics\">{{cite web | url=http://iaaweb.org/content/view/234/362/ | title=International Academy of Astronautics | publisher=International Academy of Astronautics | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> [[Indian National Science Academy]] (1978),<ref name=\"INSA\">{{cite web | url=http://www.insaindia.org/detailforeign.php?id=9 | title=INSA | publisher=Indian National Science Academy | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402170014/http://www.insaindia.org/detailforeign.php?id=9 | archive-date=2 April 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> [[National Academy of Sciences, USA]] (1980),<ref name=\"National Academy of Sciences\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nasonline.org/member-directory/?q=&site=nas_members&client=nas_members&proxystylesheet=nas_members&output=xml_no_dtd&filter=0&GSAhost=search.nationalacademies.org&unitsite=nas_members&unitname=NAS+Member+Directory&theme=gray&requestencoding=utf-8&s=&access=p&entqr=3&getfields=member_institution.member_section.member_secondary.member_fullname.member_lastname.member_firstname.member_date_of_birth.member_date_of_death.member_photopath&ie=UTF-8&ip=144.171.1.33&num=15&oe=UTF-8&requiredfields=(member_alphaname:B)&sort=meta:feedsort::ED&ud=1&ulang=&entqrm=0&wc=200&wc_mc=1&jsonp=jsonp1425711080546&start=120 | title=National Academy of Sciences | publisher=National Academy of Sciences, USA | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> Air and Space Academy (1983),<ref name=\"Air and Space Academy\">{{cite web | url=http://www.academie-air-espace.com/mship/newlist.php?pageNum_results=2&totalRows_results=333 | title=Air and Space Academy | publisher=Air and Space Academy | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> [[Academia Europaea]] (1989),<ref name=\"Academia Europaea\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ae-info.org/ae/User/Blamont_Jacques | title=Academia Europaea | publisher=Academia Europaea | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> Academy of Technology (2000), [[French Academy of Sciences]]<ref name=\"Academy membership\">{{cite web | url=http://www.academie-sciences.fr/academie/membre/section_su.htm | title=Academy membership | publisher=Academy of Sciences | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302075311/http://www.academie-sciences.fr/academie/membre/section_su.htm | archive-date=2 March 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> and the [[American Philosophical Society]]<ref name=\"American Philosophical Society\" />(2002).<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> He was also a member of the advisory council of the Planetary Society.<ref name=\"Planetary Society\" />\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Phobos Marte.jpg|left|thumb|150px|Phobos]]\n[[File:Vega-mission.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Vega mission]]\n[[File:Helkivad \u00f6\u00f6pilved Kuresoo kohal.jpg|thumb|150px|Noctilucent clouds]]\nBlamont was one of the pioneers of French space programme<ref name=\"Diploweb\" /><ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /> and his efforts were reported in the establishment of [[CNES]], the French Space Agency, in 1962.<ref name=\"Planetary Society\" /><ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> He was known to have contributed to the launch of the first French rocket, [[V\u00e9ronique (rocket)|V\u00e9ronique]],<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> in 1957.<ref name=\"Planetary Society\" /> He was one of the founders of Service d\u2019a\u00e9ronomie du CNRS, (Aeronomy Service of [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique]]) and was its director from 1958 to 1985.<ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> He participated, as a member of the steering groups,<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> in several global space missions such as the [[Voyager program|Voyager]] and [[Pioneer Venus project|Pioneer-Venus]] of [[NASA]] and [[Vega mission]] of the [[Soviet Union]] to [[Venus]] and [[Halley's Comet]] and acted as the chief investigator of the [[Phobos program]] of the USSR.<ref name=\"Planetary Society\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /><ref name=\"American Philosophical Society\" /> He assisted [[Vikram Sarabhai]]<ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> in the establishment of the Indian National Committee for Space Research (INCOSPAR) which later grew to become the present day [[Indian Space Research Organization]] (ISRO)<ref name=\"The Saga of Indian Science Since Independence: In a Nutshell\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=g7crHmSeI5kC&pg=PA39#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=The Saga of Indian Science Since Independence: In a Nutshell | publisher=Universities Press | author=Chandana Chakrabarti, Pushpa M. Bhargava | year=2003 | pages=248 | isbn=9788173714351}}</ref> and played a part in providing the payload for the first two Indian rocket launches in 1963 and 1964.<ref name=\"Diploweb\" />\n\nBlamont was credited with the discovery of [[turbopause]] in 1959, the [[interstellar wind]] in 1970, the [[Stellar structure|hydrogen envelope]] of comets in 1971 and the polar [[noctilucent clouds]] in 1973.<ref name=\"Diploweb\" /><ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> He was known to have made the measurement of the temperature of the neutral atmosphere from 100 to 500&nbsp;km, the dynamic parameters of the [[Mesopause|mesopause region]], and [[Einstein's general relativity]] [[redshift]] on the Sun for the first time.<ref name=\"Diploweb\" /><ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /><ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> He was the head of the group which introduced scientific ballooning and [[Lidar]] technology for atmospheric probing in Europe.<ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> The image compression device developed by Blamont<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> is in use with various space agencies for planetary missions around the Moon, Mars and [[Titan (moon)|Titan]].<ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> He also contributed to the establishment of a shooting range, in [[Guiana Space Centre|Kourou, French Guyana]].<ref name=\"NATF Profile\" />\n\nBlamont, besides writing several articles on science, authored four books,<ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /><ref name=\"American Philosophical Society\" /><ref name=\"CNES Bibliography\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cnes.fr/web/CNES-fr/4304-jacques-blamont-le-chiffre-et-le-songe.php | title=CNES Bibliography | publisher=CNES | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> viz. ''V\u00e9nus d\u00e9voil\u00e9e, Voyage autour d'une plan\u00e8te'' (Venus Unveiled \u2013 1987),<ref name=\"V\u00e9nus d\u00e9voil\u00e9e. Voyage autour d'une plan\u00e8te\">{{cite book | title=V\u00e9nus d\u00e9voil\u00e9e. Voyage autour d'une plan\u00e8te | publisher=Broch\u00e9 | author=Jacques Blamont | year=1987 | pages=367 | isbn=978-2020096430}}</ref> ''Le Chiffre et le Songe, Histoire politique de la d\u00e9couverte'' (The Digit and the \u2013 1993),<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /><ref name=\"Le Chiffre et le Songe, Histoire politique de la d\u00e9couverte\">{{cite book | title=Le Chiffre et le Songe, Histoire politique de la d\u00e9couverte | publisher=Reli\u00e9 | author=Jacques Blamont | year=1993 | pages=941 | isbn=978-2738101938}}</ref> ''Le Lion et le Moucheron, Histoire des Marrances de Toulouse'' (The Lion and the Midge \u2013 2000)<ref name=\"Le Lion et le Moucheron, Histoire des Marrances de Toulouse\">{{cite book | title=Le Lion et le Moucheron, Histoire des Marrances de Toulouse | publisher=Le Grand Livre Du Mois | author=Jacques Blamont | year=2000 | isbn=978-2702853054}}</ref> and ''Introduction au Si\u00e8cle des Menaces'' (Introduction to the Age of Menaces \u2013 2004).<ref name=\"Introduction au Si\u00e8cle des Menaces\">{{cite book | title=Introduction au Si\u00e8cle des Menaces | publisher=Broch\u00e9 | author=Jacques Blamont | year=2004 | pages=560 | isbn=978-2738114099}}</ref><ref name=\"Introduction to the century threats\">{{cite web | url=http://www.automatesintelligents.com/biblionet/2004/sep/blamont.html | title=Introduction to the century threats | publisher=Automates Intelligents | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> He also mentored 80 research scholars in their doctoral research.<ref name=\"NATF Profile\" />\n\n==Awards and recognition==\nJacques Blamont received three of the highest French civilian honours, [[Commander of the Legion of Honour]], [[National Order of Merit (France)|Grand Officer of the National Order of Merit]] and [[National Order of Merit (France)|Grand Cross of the National Order of Merit]] apart from the honour of the [[Ordre des Palmes Acad\u00e9miques|Commander of the Order of Academic Palms]] and the Silver Medal from the [[President of the french republic|President of the French Republic]] in 1967.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /> He received the [[Soviet Order of Friendship of Peoples]] from the erstwhile [[Soviet Union]] in 1989<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /> and the [[Government of India]] awarded him the fourth highest Indian civilian award of [[Padma Shri]] in 2015.<ref name=\"Padma Awards\" /> He was a winner of NASA awards twice, [[NASA]] Exceptional Scientific Achievement Medal in 1972<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> and [[NASA]] Distinguished Service Medal in 2000<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> and the [[French Academy of Sciences]] honoured him two times, Leon Grelaud Prize in 1960 and Doisteau Paul - \u00c9mile Blutet Prize in 1967.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /> The [[Academy of Sciences of the USSR]] and the [[Indian Space Research Organization]] awarded him the [[Yuri Gagarin]] Medal in 1985<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> and the [[Vikram Sarabhai]] Medal in 1994 respectively.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> He won three awards from the [[International Academy of Astronautics]], Daniel and Florence Guggenheim Award in 1967, Guggenheim Medal in 1986 and Von Karman Award in 1989.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> He was also a recipient of Rovel H. Prize from the Faculty of Paris in 1957, Aim\u00e9 Cotton prize of the French Physical Society in 1960, [[CNES]] Vermeil medal in 1967, Spie prize,<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> French Roberval Prize in 1993,<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> Gold Medal of the Guiana Space Center in 1995, George N. Goddard Award from the [[International Society for Optical Engineering]] in 1997, [[Committee on Space Research]] (COSPAR) Space Science Award in 2004 <ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" />\nand [[Prix International d'Astronautique]] (International Astronautics Prize), formerly known as [[Prix REP-Hirsch]] in 2019.\n\n==Award gallery==\n<gallery>\nPadma Shri India IIIe Klasse.jpg|[[Padma Shri|Padma Shri India]]\nChevalier l\u00e9gion d'honneur 2.png|[[Commander of the Legion of Honour]]\nM\u00e9rite national officier FRANCE.jpg|[[National Order of Merit (France)|Grand Officer of the National Order of Merit]]\nCommandeur de l'Ordre des Palmes Acad\u00e9miques avers.jpg|[[Ordre des Palmes Acad\u00e9miques|Commander of the Academic Palms]]\nGrand-Croix de l'Ordre National du Merite.jpg|[[National Order of Merit (France)|Grand Cross of the National Order of Merit]]\nOrden De La Amistad De Los Pueblos.png|[[Order of Friendship of Peoples|Soviet Order of Friendship of Peoples]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|India|France|Science}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | url=https://www.odilejacob.fr/catalogue/sciences/astronomie-astrophysique-cosmologie/venus-devoilee_9782020096430.php | title=V\u00e9nus d\u00e9voil\u00e9e. Voyage autour d'une plan\u00e8te | publisher=Odile Jacob | author=Jacques Blamont | year=1987 | pages=367 | isbn=978-2020096430}}\n* {{cite book | url=https://www.odilejacob.fr/catalogue/sciences-humaines/epistemologie-histoire-des-sciences/chiffre-et-le-songe_9782738143105.php | title=Le Chiffre et le Songe. Histoire politique de la d\u00e9couverte | publisher=Odile Jacob | author=Jacques Blamont | year=1993 | pages=941 | isbn=978-2738101938}}\n* {{cite book | url=https://www.odilejacob.fr/catalogue/histoire-et-geopolitique/histoire/lion-et-le-moucheron_9782738107770.php | title=Le Lion et le Moucheron. Histoire des Marrances de Toulouse | publisher=Le Grand Livre du Mois | author=Jacques Blamont | year=2000 | isbn=978-2702853054}}\n* {{cite book | url=https://www.odilejacob.fr/catalogue/sciences/introduction-au-siecle-des-menaces_9782738114099.php | title=Introduction au Si\u00e8cle des Menaces | publisher=Odile Jacob | author=Jacques Blamont | year=2004 | pages=560 | isbn=978-2738114099}}\n* {{cite book | url=https://www.odilejacob.fr/catalogue/histoire-et-geopolitique/geopolitique-et-strategie/-leve-toi-et-marche-_9782738122407.php | title=\" L\u00e8ve-toi et marche \". Propositions pour un futur de l'humanit\u00e9 | publisher=Odile Jacob | author=Jacques Blamont | year=2009 | pages=336 | isbn=978-2738122407}}\n* {{cite web | url=http://www.automatesintelligents.com/biblionet/2004/sep/blamont.html | title=Introduction to the Century Threats - Review| publisher=Automates Intelligents | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}\n* {{cite book | url=http://www.cnrseditions.fr/sciences/7689-reseaux-.html?search_query=reseau&results=126 | title=R\u00e9seaux ! Le pari de l'intelligence collective | publisher=CNRS \u00c9ditions | author=Jacques Blamont | year=2018 | pages=336 | isbn=978-2738122407}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6VUpicNBMzg | title=Interview de Jacques Blamont | publisher=Thinkerview | work=[[YouTube]] video | date=30 January 2013 | accessdate=6 March 2015}}\n* {{cite web | url=http://www.automatesintelligents.com/interviews/2004/oct/blamont.html | title=Interview with Jacques Blamont | publisher=Jean-Paul Baquiast and Christophe Jacquemin | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blamont, Jacques}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:French astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:French science writers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in science & engineering]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Friendship of Peoples]]\n[[Category:Members of the French Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Foreign Fellows of the Indian National Science Academy]]\n[[Category:Foreign associates of the National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:20th-century French physicists]]\n[[Category:21st-century French physicists]]\n[[Category:20th-century French male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century French male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century French non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century French non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:French male non-fiction writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|French astrophysicist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                    = Jacques Blamont\n| image                   = Jacques_Blamont,_2015_(cropped).jpg\n| imagesize               =\n| caption                 =\n|birth_name=Jacques Emile Blamont\n| birth_date              = 13 October 1926\n| birth_place             = [[Paris]], [[French Third Republic|France]]\n| death_date              = {{death date and age|2020|4|13|1926|10|13|df=y}}\n| death_place             = [[Ch\u00e2tillon, Hauts-de-Seine|Ch\u00e2tillon]], France\n| restingplace            =\n| restingplacecoordinates =\n| othername               =\n| occupation              = [[Astrophysicist]]\n| yearsactive             = 1948\u20132020\n| known for               = Aerospace programmes\n| spouse                  =\n| domesticpartner         =\n| children                =\n| parents                 =\n| website                 =\n| awards                  = [[Padma Shri]]<br>[[Commander of the Legion of Honour]]<br>[[National Order of Merit (France)|Grand Officer of the National Order of Merit]]<br>[[Ordre des Palmes Acad\u00e9miques|Commander of the Academic Palms]]<br>[[National Order of Merit (France)|Grand Cross of the National Order of Merit]]<br>Rovel H. Prize<br>[[Aim\u00e9 Cotton]] Prize<br>Leon Grelaud Prize<br>[[CNES]] Vermeil Medal<br>Prize Doisteau Paul - \u00c9mile Blutet<br>[[President of France|President's]] Silver Medal<br>[[Daniel and Florence Guggenheim Foundation|Daniel and Florence Guggenheim]] Award<br>[[NASA]] Exceptional Scientific Achievement Medal<br>[[USSR Academy of Sciences]] Gagarin Medal<br>[[International Academy of Astronautics|IAA]] Guggenheim Medal<br>[[Soviet Order of Friendship of Peoples]]<br>[[International Academy of Astronautics|IAA]] [[Theodore von Karman Medal]]<br>[[Indian Space Research Organization|ISRO]] [[Vikram Sarabhai]] Medal<br>[[Guiana Space Center]] Gold Medal<br>Spie prize<br>French Roberval Prize<br>[[International Society for Optical Engineering|ISOE]] George N. Goddard Award<br>[[NASA]] Distinguished Service Medal<br>COSPAR Space Science Award\n}}\n'''Jacques Emile Blamont''' ({{IPA-fr|\u0292ak bla.m\u0254\u0303|}}; 13 October 1926&nbsp;\u2013 13 April 2020) was a French [[astrophysicist]]<ref name=\"Interview de Jacques Blamont\">{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6VUpicNBMzg | title=Interview de Jacques Blamont | publisher=Thinkerview | work=[[YouTube]] video | date=30 January 2013 | accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Interview\">{{cite web | url=http://www.automatesintelligents.com/interviews/2004/oct/blamont.html | title=Interview with Jacques Blamont | publisher=Jean-Paul Baquiast and Christophe Jacquemin | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref> author and the founder scientific and technical director of [[CNES|National Centre for Space Studies]] (CNES-Centre national d'\u00e9tudes spatiales), known to have contributed to the development of [[V\u00e9ronique (rocket)|Veronique]], the first rocket launched by France in 1957.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\">{{cite web | url=http://www.academie-sciences.fr/academie/membre/BlamontJ_bio0909.pdf | title=Royal Academy of Sciences profile | publisher=Royal Academy of Sciences | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"Planetary Society\">{{cite web | url=http://www.planetary.org/connect/our-experts/profiles/jacques-blamont.html | title=Planetary Society | publisher=Planetary Society | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref> He was an elected fellow of the [[French Academy of Technologies]]<ref name=\"NATF Fellow\">{{cite web | url=http://www.academie-technologies.fr/en/directories/B | title=NATF Fellow | publisher=NATF | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref> and a professor emeritus of the [[Pierre and Marie Curie University]] (University of Paris VI).<ref name=\"Diploweb\">{{cite web | url=http://www.diploweb.com/_Jacques-BLAMONT_.html | title=Diploweb | publisher=Diploweb | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nBlamont was a recipient of several national honours such as [[Commander of the Legion of Honour]], the third highest French civilian honour, [[National Order of Merit (France)|Grand Officer of the National Order of Merit]], the second highest French civilian honour, [[Ordre des Palmes Acad\u00e9miques|Commander of the Academic Palms]], [[National Order of Merit (France)|Grand Cross of the National Order of Merit]], the highest French civilian honour, [[President of France|President's]] Silver Medal, [[Soviet Order of Friendship of Peoples]] and [[Padma Shri]], the fourth highest Indian civilian award.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=114952 |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Padma Awards |date=2015 |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6VrWjEuo3?url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=114952 |archivedate=26 January 2015 }}</ref>\n\nBlamont died on 13 April 2020 in [[Ch\u00e2tillon, Hauts-de-Seine]], aged 93.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/disparitions/article/2020/04/14/l-astrophysicien-jacques-blamont-un-des-peres-de-l-aventure-spatiale-francaise-est-mort_6036491_3382.html |last=Augereau |first=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois |title=L\u2019astrophysicien, Jacques Blamont, un des p\u00e8res de l\u2019aventure spatiale fran\u00e7aise, est mort |date=14 April 2020 |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=[[Le Monde]]}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nJacques Blamont was born in Paris in France on 13 October 1926<ref name=\"NATF Profile\">{{cite web | url=http://www.academie-technologies.fr/en/members/152-jacques-blamont | title=NATF Profile | publisher=NATF | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Rise of the West\">{{cite web | url=http://www.riseofthewest.net/thinkers/blamont01.htm | title=Rise of the West | publisher=Rise of the West | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> and did his studies at the [[\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure]]<ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /> where he came in contact with the [[Nobel laureate]], [[Alfred Kastler]], who was serving the institution as a professorial chair.<ref name=\"Kastler\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nobel-winners.com/Physics/alfred_kastler.html | title=Kastler | publisher=Nobelwinners.com | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> He graduated from [[\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure]] in 1948<ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> and continued his studies at the [[National Centre for Scientific Research]] (CNRS) as an associate of physical sciences.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /> In 1952, he reunited with Alfred Kastler in research on ''atomic coherence phenomenon'' and secured his doctoral degree (Doctor of Science) under his guidance in 1956.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /><ref name=\"Rise of the West\" />\n\nBlamont continued at [[CNRS]] for a year more as a research fellow<ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /> and joined the Aeronomy Service of the institution in 1957 where he became the deputy director in 1958.<ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /> In 1961, he was promoted as the director, a post he held till 1985.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /><ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /> He worked in many capacities during his stay with CNES, as a Scientific and Technical Director (1962-1972), as Top Scientific Advisor (1972-1982) and as an advisor to the President of CNES<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> from 1982.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /><ref name=\"American Philosophical Society\">{{cite web | url=http://www.amphilsoc.org/memhist/search?creator=Blamont&title=&subject=&subdiv=&mem=&year=&year-max=&dead=&keyword=&smode=advanced | title=American Philosophical Society | publisher=American Philosophical Society | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> During this period, he served the [[Pierre and Marie Curie University]] as a professor without chair from 1957 to 1961, as a full professor from 1962 to 1996 and as a professor emeritus from there on.<ref name=\"Planetary Society\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /><ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /><ref name=\"American Philosophical Society\" /><ref name=\"Academy reference\">{{cite web | url=http://www.academie-sciences.fr/academie/membre/Blamont_Jacques.htm | title=Academy reference | publisher=Academy of Sciences | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402150505/http://www.academie-sciences.fr/academie/membre/Blamont_Jacques.htm | archive-date=2 April 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> He also worked as a research director at [[\u00c9cole Militaire]] (Joint Defence College).<ref name=\"NATF Profile\" />\n\nHe was made the first [[Vikram Sarabhai]] professor at the [[Physical Research Laboratory]] in 1977<ref name=\"Vikram Professor\" >{{cite web | url=https://www.prl.res.in/prl-eng/vikram_professor | title=Vikram Professor | publisher=Physical Research Laboratory |date=2020 |accessdate=13 April 2020 }}</ref>, a visiting professor at the [[California Institute of Technology]] in 1985 and a distinguished visiting scientist at [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]] during 1980-2001.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /> He was a member of [[International Academy of Astronautics]] (1969),<ref name=\"International Academy of Astronautics\">{{cite web | url=http://iaaweb.org/content/view/234/362/ | title=International Academy of Astronautics | publisher=International Academy of Astronautics | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> [[Indian National Science Academy]] (1978),<ref name=\"INSA\">{{cite web | url=http://www.insaindia.org/detailforeign.php?id=9 | title=INSA | publisher=Indian National Science Academy | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402170014/http://www.insaindia.org/detailforeign.php?id=9 | archive-date=2 April 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> [[National Academy of Sciences, USA]] (1980),<ref name=\"National Academy of Sciences\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nasonline.org/member-directory/?q=&site=nas_members&client=nas_members&proxystylesheet=nas_members&output=xml_no_dtd&filter=0&GSAhost=search.nationalacademies.org&unitsite=nas_members&unitname=NAS+Member+Directory&theme=gray&requestencoding=utf-8&s=&access=p&entqr=3&getfields=member_institution.member_section.member_secondary.member_fullname.member_lastname.member_firstname.member_date_of_birth.member_date_of_death.member_photopath&ie=UTF-8&ip=144.171.1.33&num=15&oe=UTF-8&requiredfields=(member_alphaname:B)&sort=meta:feedsort::ED&ud=1&ulang=&entqrm=0&wc=200&wc_mc=1&jsonp=jsonp1425711080546&start=120 | title=National Academy of Sciences | publisher=National Academy of Sciences, USA | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> Air and Space Academy (1983),<ref name=\"Air and Space Academy\">{{cite web | url=http://www.academie-air-espace.com/mship/newlist.php?pageNum_results=2&totalRows_results=333 | title=Air and Space Academy | publisher=Air and Space Academy | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> [[Academia Europaea]] (1989),<ref name=\"Academia Europaea\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ae-info.org/ae/User/Blamont_Jacques | title=Academia Europaea | publisher=Academia Europaea | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> Academy of Technology (2000), [[French Academy of Sciences]]<ref name=\"Academy membership\">{{cite web | url=http://www.academie-sciences.fr/academie/membre/section_su.htm | title=Academy membership | publisher=Academy of Sciences | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302075311/http://www.academie-sciences.fr/academie/membre/section_su.htm | archive-date=2 March 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> and the [[American Philosophical Society]]<ref name=\"American Philosophical Society\" />(2002).<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> He was also a member of the advisory council of the Planetary Society.<ref name=\"Planetary Society\" />\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Phobos Marte.jpg|left|thumb|150px|Phobos]]\n[[File:Vega-mission.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Vega mission]]\n[[File:Helkivad \u00f6\u00f6pilved Kuresoo kohal.jpg|thumb|150px|Noctilucent clouds]]\nBlamont was one of the pioneers of French space programme<ref name=\"Diploweb\" /><ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /> and his efforts were reported in the establishment of [[CNES]], the French Space Agency, in 1962.<ref name=\"Planetary Society\" /><ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> He was known to have contributed to the launch of the first French rocket, [[V\u00e9ronique (rocket)|V\u00e9ronique]],<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> in 1957.<ref name=\"Planetary Society\" /> He was one of the founders of Service d\u2019a\u00e9ronomie du CNRS, (Aeronomy Service of [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique]]) and was its director from 1958 to 1985.<ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> He participated, as a member of the steering groups,<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> in several global space missions such as the [[Voyager program|Voyager]] and [[Pioneer Venus project|Pioneer-Venus]] of [[NASA]] and [[Vega mission]] of the [[Soviet Union]] to [[Venus]] and [[Halley's Comet]] and acted as the chief investigator of the [[Phobos program]] of the USSR.<ref name=\"Planetary Society\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /><ref name=\"American Philosophical Society\" /> He assisted [[Vikram Sarabhai]]<ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> in the establishment of the Indian National Committee for Space Research (INCOSPAR) which later grew to become the present day [[Indian Space Research Organization]] (ISRO)<ref name=\"The Saga of Indian Science Since Independence: In a Nutshell\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=g7crHmSeI5kC&pg=PA39#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=The Saga of Indian Science Since Independence: In a Nutshell | publisher=Universities Press | author=Chandana Chakrabarti, Pushpa M. Bhargava | year=2003 | pages=248 | isbn=9788173714351}}</ref> and played a part in providing the payload for the first two Indian rocket launches in 1963 and 1964.<ref name=\"Diploweb\" />\n\nBlamont was credited with the discovery of [[turbopause]] in 1959, the [[interstellar wind]] in 1970, the [[Stellar structure|hydrogen envelope]] of comets in 1971 and the polar [[noctilucent clouds]] in 1973.<ref name=\"Diploweb\" /><ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> He was known to have made the measurement of the temperature of the neutral atmosphere from 100 to 500&nbsp;km, the dynamic parameters of the [[Mesopause|mesopause region]], and [[Einstein's general relativity]] [[redshift]] on the Sun for the first time.<ref name=\"Diploweb\" /><ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /><ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> He was the head of the group which introduced scientific ballooning and [[Lidar]] technology for atmospheric probing in Europe.<ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> The image compression device developed by Blamont<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> is in use with various space agencies for planetary missions around the Moon, Mars and [[Titan (moon)|Titan]].<ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> He also contributed to the establishment of a shooting range, in [[Guiana Space Centre|Kourou, French Guyana]].<ref name=\"NATF Profile\" />\n\nBlamont, besides writing several articles on science, authored four books,<ref name=\"NATF Profile\" /><ref name=\"American Philosophical Society\" /><ref name=\"CNES Bibliography\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cnes.fr/web/CNES-fr/4304-jacques-blamont-le-chiffre-et-le-songe.php | title=CNES Bibliography | publisher=CNES | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> viz. ''V\u00e9nus d\u00e9voil\u00e9e, Voyage autour d'une plan\u00e8te'' (Venus Unveiled \u2013 1987),<ref name=\"V\u00e9nus d\u00e9voil\u00e9e. Voyage autour d'une plan\u00e8te\">{{cite book | title=V\u00e9nus d\u00e9voil\u00e9e. Voyage autour d'une plan\u00e8te | publisher=Broch\u00e9 | author=Jacques Blamont | year=1987 | pages=367 | isbn=978-2020096430}}</ref> ''Le Chiffre et le Songe, Histoire politique de la d\u00e9couverte'' (The Digit and the \u2013 1993),<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /><ref name=\"Le Chiffre et le Songe, Histoire politique de la d\u00e9couverte\">{{cite book | title=Le Chiffre et le Songe, Histoire politique de la d\u00e9couverte | publisher=Reli\u00e9 | author=Jacques Blamont | year=1993 | pages=941 | isbn=978-2738101938}}</ref> ''Le Lion et le Moucheron, Histoire des Marrances de Toulouse'' (The Lion and the Midge \u2013 2000)<ref name=\"Le Lion et le Moucheron, Histoire des Marrances de Toulouse\">{{cite book | title=Le Lion et le Moucheron, Histoire des Marrances de Toulouse | publisher=Le Grand Livre Du Mois | author=Jacques Blamont | year=2000 | isbn=978-2702853054}}</ref> and ''Introduction au Si\u00e8cle des Menaces'' (Introduction to the Age of Menaces \u2013 2004).<ref name=\"Introduction au Si\u00e8cle des Menaces\">{{cite book | title=Introduction au Si\u00e8cle des Menaces | publisher=Broch\u00e9 | author=Jacques Blamont | year=2004 | pages=560 | isbn=978-2738114099}}</ref><ref name=\"Introduction to the century threats\">{{cite web | url=http://www.automatesintelligents.com/biblionet/2004/sep/blamont.html | title=Introduction to the century threats | publisher=Automates Intelligents | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> He also mentored 80 research scholars in their doctoral research.<ref name=\"NATF Profile\" />\n\n==Awards and recognition==\nJacques Blamont received three of the highest French civilian honours, [[Commander of the Legion of Honour]], [[National Order of Merit (France)|Grand Officer of the National Order of Merit]] and [[National Order of Merit (France)|Grand Cross of the National Order of Merit]] apart from the honour of the [[Ordre des Palmes Acad\u00e9miques|Commander of the Order of Academic Palms]] and the Silver Medal from the [[President of the french republic|President of the French Republic]] in 1967.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /> He received the [[Soviet Order of Friendship of Peoples]] from the erstwhile [[Soviet Union]] in 1989<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /> and the [[Government of India]] awarded him the fourth highest Indian civilian award of [[Padma Shri]] in 2015.<ref name=\"Padma Awards\" /> He was a winner of NASA awards twice, [[NASA]] Exceptional Scientific Achievement Medal in 1972<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> and [[NASA]] Distinguished Service Medal in 2000<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> and the [[French Academy of Sciences]] honoured him two times, Leon Grelaud Prize in 1960 and Doisteau Paul - \u00c9mile Blutet Prize in 1967.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /> The [[Academy of Sciences of the USSR]] and the [[Indian Space Research Organization]] awarded him the [[Yuri Gagarin]] Medal in 1985<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> and the [[Vikram Sarabhai]] Medal in 1994 respectively.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> He won three awards from the [[International Academy of Astronautics]], Daniel and Florence Guggenheim Award in 1967, Guggenheim Medal in 1986 and Von Karman Award in 1989.<ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" /> He was also a recipient of Rovel H. Prize from the Faculty of Paris in 1957, Aim\u00e9 Cotton prize of the French Physical Society in 1960, [[CNES]] Vermeil medal in 1967, Spie prize,<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> French Roberval Prize in 1993,<ref name=\"Rise of the West\" /> Gold Medal of the Guiana Space Center in 1995, George N. Goddard Award from the [[International Society for Optical Engineering]] in 1997, [[Committee on Space Research]] (COSPAR) Space Science Award in 2004 <ref name=\"Royal Academy of Sciences profile\" /><ref name=\"Diploweb\" />\nand [[Prix International d'Astronautique]] (International Astronautics Prize), formerly known as [[Prix REP-Hirsch]] in 2019.\n\n==Award gallery==\n<gallery>\nPadma Shri India IIIe Klasse.jpg|[[Padma Shri|Padma Shri India]]\nChevalier l\u00e9gion d'honneur 2.png|[[Commander of the Legion of Honour]]\nM\u00e9rite national officier FRANCE.jpg|[[National Order of Merit (France)|Grand Officer of the National Order of Merit]]\nCommandeur de l'Ordre des Palmes Acad\u00e9miques avers.jpg|[[Ordre des Palmes Acad\u00e9miques|Commander of the Academic Palms]]\nGrand-Croix de l'Ordre National du Merite.jpg|[[National Order of Merit (France)|Grand Cross of the National Order of Merit]]\nOrden De La Amistad De Los Pueblos.png|[[Order of Friendship of Peoples|Soviet Order of Friendship of Peoples]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[CNES]], the National Centre for Space Studies\n* [[French Academy of Sciences]]\n* [[French Academy of Technologies]]\n* [[Indian Space Research Organization]]\n* [[Pierre and Marie Curie University]]\n* [[V\u00e9ronique (rocket)|Veronique]]\n{{portal|India|France|Science}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | url=https://www.odilejacob.fr/catalogue/sciences/astronomie-astrophysique-cosmologie/venus-devoilee_9782020096430.php | title=V\u00e9nus d\u00e9voil\u00e9e. Voyage autour d'une plan\u00e8te | publisher=Odile Jacob | author=Jacques Blamont | year=1987 | pages=367 | isbn=978-2020096430}}\n* {{cite book | url=https://www.odilejacob.fr/catalogue/sciences-humaines/epistemologie-histoire-des-sciences/chiffre-et-le-songe_9782738143105.php | title=Le Chiffre et le Songe. Histoire politique de la d\u00e9couverte | publisher=Odile Jacob | author=Jacques Blamont | year=1993 | pages=941 | isbn=978-2738101938}}\n* {{cite book | url=https://www.odilejacob.fr/catalogue/histoire-et-geopolitique/histoire/lion-et-le-moucheron_9782738107770.php | title=Le Lion et le Moucheron. Histoire des Marrances de Toulouse | publisher=Le Grand Livre du Mois | author=Jacques Blamont | year=2000 | isbn=978-2702853054}}\n* {{cite book | url=https://www.odilejacob.fr/catalogue/sciences/introduction-au-siecle-des-menaces_9782738114099.php | title=Introduction au Si\u00e8cle des Menaces | publisher=Odile Jacob | author=Jacques Blamont | year=2004 | pages=560 | isbn=978-2738114099}}\n* {{cite book | url=https://www.odilejacob.fr/catalogue/histoire-et-geopolitique/geopolitique-et-strategie/-leve-toi-et-marche-_9782738122407.php | title=\" L\u00e8ve-toi et marche \". Propositions pour un futur de l'humanit\u00e9 | publisher=Odile Jacob | author=Jacques Blamont | year=2009 | pages=336 | isbn=978-2738122407}}\n* {{cite web | url=http://www.automatesintelligents.com/biblionet/2004/sep/blamont.html | title=Introduction to the Century Threats - Review| publisher=Automates Intelligents | date=2015 | accessdate=7 March 2015}}\n* {{cite book | url=http://www.cnrseditions.fr/sciences/7689-reseaux-.html?search_query=reseau&results=126 | title=R\u00e9seaux ! Le pari de l'intelligence collective | publisher=CNRS \u00c9ditions | author=Jacques Blamont | year=2018 | pages=336 | isbn=978-2738122407}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6VUpicNBMzg | title=Interview de Jacques Blamont | publisher=Thinkerview | work=[[YouTube]] video | date=30 January 2013 | accessdate=6 March 2015}}\n* {{cite web | url=http://www.automatesintelligents.com/interviews/2004/oct/blamont.html | title=Interview with Jacques Blamont | publisher=Jean-Paul Baquiast and Christophe Jacquemin | date=2015 | accessdate=6 March 2015}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blamont, Jacques}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:French astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:French science writers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in science & engineering]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Friendship of Peoples]]\n[[Category:Members of the French Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Foreign Fellows of the Indian National Science Academy]]\n[[Category:Foreign associates of the National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:20th-century French physicists]]\n[[Category:21st-century French physicists]]\n[[Category:20th-century French male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century French male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century French non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century French non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:French male non-fiction writers]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1980-2001 \u2192 1980\u20132001", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacques_Blamont"}
{"title_page": "Last Week Tonight with John Oliver", "text_new": "{{short description|American late-night talk show}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = Last Week Tonight {{nowrap|with John Oliver}}\n| show_name_2        = Last Week Tonight\n| image              = Last Week Tonight.svg\n| image_alt          = Black and red text on a white background reading \"Last Week Tonight with John Oliver\".\n| caption            =\n| genre              = {{plainlist|\n* [[Comedy]]\n* [[News satire]]\n* [[Political satire]]\n* [[Talk show]]\n}}\n| creator            = [[John Oliver]]\n| writer             = <!-- Per infobox template rules, writer(s) should not be included if series has 5+ writers -->\n| director           = {{plainlist|\n* Joe Perota\n* Christopher Werner\n* Jim Hoskinson\n* Paul Pennolino\n* Bruce Leddy\n}}\n| presenter          = John Oliver\n| starring           =\n| narrated           = [[David Kaye (voice actor)|David Kaye]]\n| opentheme          = \"Go\" by [[Valley Lodge (band)|Valley Lodge]]<ref>{{cite tweet|user=LastWeekTonight|number=476822910494310400|date=June 11, 2014|title=By the way, our theme song \"Go\" is performed by the excellent rock band @ValleyLodge!}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dave Hill|title=Valley Lodge's \"Go\" Is the Theme Song for \"Last Week Tonight with John Oliver\" on HBO|url=http://davehillonline.com/blog/2014/04/valley-lodges-go-is-the-theme-song-for-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-on-hbo/|publisher=DaveHillOnline.com|date=April 29, 2014|accessdate=April 2, 2016|author-link=Dave Hill (comedian)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401105027/http://davehillonline.com/blog/2014/04/valley-lodges-go-is-the-theme-song-for-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-on-hbo/|archive-date=April 1, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| country            = United States\n| language           = English\n| num_seasons        = 7\n| num_episodes       = 187\n| list_episodes      = List of Last Week Tonight with John Oliver episodes\n| executive_producer = {{plainlist|\n* John Oliver\n* [[Tim Carvell]]\n* Liz Stanton\n* James Taylor\n* [[Jon Thoday]]\n}}\n| location           = [[CBS Broadcast Center]]<br />New York, New York\n| runtime            = 30\u201340 minutes<ref>{{cite tweet|user=LastWeekTonight|number=927269314025140225|date=November 5, 2017|title=You got an extra hour of sleep this morning, so you should be well-rested for tonight's 40-minute episode that starts at 11:15.}}</ref>\n| company            = {{plainlist|\n* Avalon Television\n* Partially Important Productions\n}}\n| distributor        = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| network            = [[HBO]]\n| picture_format     = [[1080i]] ([[16:9]] [[HDTV]])\n| audio_format       = [[Dolby Surround]]\n| first_aired        = {{Start date|2014|4|27}}\n| last_aired         = present\n| website            = http://www.hbo.com/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver\n}}\n'''''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver''''' (often abridged as '''''Last Week Tonight''''') is an American [[late-night talk show|late-night talk]] and [[news satire]] television program hosted by comedian [[John Oliver]].<ref name=\"order\">{{cite news |last=Patten |first=Dominic |date=February 12, 2014 |title=HBO Sets Name & Date For John Oliver Debut |url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/02/hbo-sets-name-date-for-john-oliver-debut/ |url-status=live |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140214111313/http://www.deadline.com/2014/02/hbo-sets-name-date-for-john-oliver-debut/ |archivedate=February 14, 2014 |accessdate=February 12, 2014}}</ref> The half-hour-long show premiered on Sunday, April 27, 2014, on [[HBO]].<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Connell|first=Michael|title=John Oliver's HBO Series Gets Name, April Premiere|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/john-olivers-hbo-series-gets-679764|accessdate=March 10, 2014|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=February 12, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140324102357/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/john-olivers-hbo-series-gets-679764|archive-date=March 24, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Last Week Tonight'' shares some similarities with [[Comedy Central]]'s ''[[The Daily Show]]'' (where Oliver was previously [[List of The Daily Show correspondents|featured as a correspondent]] and fill-in host), as it takes a satirical look at news, politics and current events, but on a weekly basis.<ref name=\"order\"/>\n\nOliver has stated that he has \"full [[artistic freedom|creative freedom]], including free rein to [[Criticisms of corporations|criticize corporations]]\". His initial contract with HBO was for two years with an option for extension.<ref name=\"freedom\">{{cite news|last=Guthrie|first=Marisa|title=John Oliver on the Luxurious 'Freedom' of HBO, His Complicated Relationship With NYC|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-luxurious-freedom-hbo-696165|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=April 19, 2014|date=April 16, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418232827/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-luxurious-freedom-hbo-696165|archive-date=April 18, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2017, HBO announced that the show had been renewed for three additional seasons of 30 episodes each, keeping the show on the air through 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/12/arts/television/john-oliver-hbo-contract.html |title=John Oliver Extends HBO Contract Through 2020 |last=Koblin |first=John |work=The New York Times |date=September 12, 2017 |accessdate=September 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912182739/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/12/arts/television/john-oliver-hbo-contract.html |archive-date=September 12, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The show's seventh season, the last season promised by the 2017 renewal announcement, premiered on February 16, 2020.<ref name=\"S6\">{{cite news |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title='Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' Gets Season 6 Premiere Date On HBO |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-season-6-premiere-date-hbo-1202528068/ |accessdate=January 2, 2019 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=January 2, 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102235844/https://deadline.com/2019/01/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-season-6-premiere-date-hbo-1202528068/ |archive-date=January 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nOliver described his preparations for the show to an interviewer for ''[[The Atlantic#The Wire|The Wire]]'': \"... I basically have to watch everything. The only thing I kind of watch for pleasure is [[Fareed Zakaria GPS|Fareed Zakaria's show]] on Sundays ... That and ''[[60 Minutes]]'' I watch for pleasure, or maybe ''[[Frontline (American TV program)|Frontline]]'' ... I have a TV on in my office all the time and I'll generally flick around on that from [[CNN]], [[Fox News|Fox]], [[MSNBC]], [[Bloomberg Television|Bloomberg]], [[CNBC]], [[Al Jazeera America|Al Jazeera]] ... I'm watching with a certain thing in mind and that is how to see a story told badly.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thewire.com/entertainment/2014/05/john-oliver-what-i-read/361405/ |author= Zuckerman, Esther |date= May 1, 2014 |title= John Oliver: What I Read |work= The Wire |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140504083727/http://www.thewire.com/entertainment/2014/05/john-oliver-what-i-read/361405/ |archive-date= May 4, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nHe said to another interviewer that he is concerned about dealing with [[news values|old news]]:\n\n<blockquote>If something happens on a Monday, realistically all the meat is going to be picked off that bone by the time it gets to us&nbsp;\u2014 there's probably barely a point in doing it ... I think we'll be attracted to some extent by stories that are off the grid ... Our show may end up skewing more international in terms of stories.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://unfetteredequality.com/2014/08/13/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-changing-journalism-for-the-better |title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver: Changing journalism for the better |last=Hoxie |first=Angie |date=August 13, 2014 |accessdate=February 18, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218055110/http://unfetteredequality.com/2014/08/13/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-changing-journalism-for-the-better/ |archive-date=February 18, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n[[Tim Carvell]], executive producer of ''Last Week Tonight'', explained in an interview how the cast and crew deal with a half hour of Oliver speaking without any [[Television advertisement|commercial]] breaks.<ref name=\"usnews\">{{cite web |url= https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/04/22/5-things-to-know-about-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver |author= Sneed, Tierney |date= April 22, 2014 |title= Why ''Last Week Tonight'' Will Not Just Be ''The Daily Show'' on Sundays |work= [[U.S. News & World Report]] |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140504081746/http://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/04/22/5-things-to-know-about-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver |archive-date= May 4, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Structural considerations are leading to changes in the content in the show that will inherently make it different from ''The Daily Show'' ... We realized early on, you don't necessarily want to hear anybody talk to you for a half an hour straight&nbsp;\u2013 even John, who is very charming&nbsp;\u2013 so we are constructing these little, produced comedy elements that will serve the function of commercial breaks throughout the show, which will let us get out of the studio, get us away from John's voice and break the show up a bit.}}\n\nCarvell also revealed that HBO gave them freedom in choosing guests for the show, advising them not to feel obligated to feature celebrities.<ref name=\"usnews\" /> When asked by an interviewer about \"[[correspondent]]s\" such as those featured on ''The Daily Show'', Oliver replied, \"we're not going to be a parody news show, so no people pretending to be journalists.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/blogs/tv-news/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-interview-two-days-later-222215388.html|last=Furlong|first=Maggie|title='Last Week Tonight,' Two Days Later: John Oliver on His First Show, Dream Guests, and Old White Racists|website=Yahoo!|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=May 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619185957/https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/blogs/tv-news/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-interview-two-days-later-222215388.html|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the fifth episode of season 7, Oliver stated that the studio and the show's offices were shut down after employees tested positive for [[COVID-19]] and that the show would go on temporary hiatus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/films-tv-delayed-coronavirus-canceled-1203532033/|title=All the Shows and Movies Shut Down or Delayed Because of Coronavirus|publisher=Variety|date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The show returned on March&nbsp;29, filmed from Oliver's home, to cover the coronavirus and the response to it.<ref>https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/john-oliver-coronavirus-last-week-tonight-march-29.html</ref>\n\n==Format==\n{{more citations needed section|date=August 2015}}\nThe format is similar to ''[[The Daily Show]]'', with Oliver sitting at a desk in front of a backdrop of a skyline containing buildings from around the world, often relating to the current topic. Unlike ''The Daily Show'', Oliver tends to explore one concept in depth but retains the appearance of commercial breaks to intercut larger topics with smaller segments that are not necessarily related to the topic at hand. The show is taped in front of a [[studio audience]], and HBO offers a limited number of free tickets to attend each week's ''Last Week Tonight'' taping. As of March 15, 2020, the show is being filmed with no live audience at an unspecified studio location due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].\n\nThe show's theme starts off every episode containing images relating to it or the world at large with satirical captions written in [[dog Latin]]. Each episode covers a small handful of shorter segments, and then one main segment. While the short segments almost always relate to recent news, the episode's main segment usually covers in length and detail a political issue, even if that issue did not have news media attention during the preceding week. On occasion, the short segments are omitted and the main segment takes up the entirety of the episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2016/2/14/10989154/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-season-3|last=Framke|first=Caroline|title=John Oliver on making Last Week Tonight and why he won't focus on the 2016 election|website=Vox|date=February 14, 2016|accessdate=March 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320052802/http://www.vox.com/2016/2/14/10989154/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-season-3|archive-date=March 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOliver injects humor into his presentation, including satirical [[analogies]], and allusions to popular culture and celebrities. The show includes a panel in the upper-left corner that frequently displays a photo or graphic for that accompanies subject at hand, which aids in the humor. A full-screen graphic will show and play a video clip (such as excerpts from news show or documentaries) when Oliver is citing it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2014/07/why-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-is-the-next-generation-of-late-night-23696/|title=Why 'Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' is The Next Generation of Late Night|last=Miller|first=Liz Shannon|website=IndieWire|language=en|date=July 29, 2014|accessdate=September 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904015651/http://www.indiewire.com/2014/07/why-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-is-the-next-generation-of-late-night-23696/|archive-date=September 4, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He often coins [[hashtag|hashtags]] related to his segment for use in [[social media]], some of which go [[Viral phenomenon|viral]].<ref name=Emertainment>{{cite web|url=http://emertainmentmonthly.com/index.php/how-john-oliver-gets-social-media-right-while-the-rest-of-traditional-media-fails/|last=Solomon|first=Emily|title=How John Oliver Gets Social Media Right While the Rest of Traditional Media Fails|work=Emertainment Monthly|date=April 12, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404222905/http://emertainmentmonthly.com/index.php/how-john-oliver-gets-social-media-right-while-the-rest-of-traditional-media-fails/|archive-date=April 4, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA recurring element of the show is Oliver's use of mascots. The mascots used in the show include Jeff the Diseased Lung in a Cowboy Hat, Hoots the NSA Owl, Taryn the Tinder Chicken, and the Last Week Tonight puppets.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.ranker.com/list/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-mascots/ranker-tv | title=All the Mascot Costumes from Last Week Tonight, Ranked}}</ref> Oliver told Vulture in February 2019, \"I mean, the truth of the mascots is that we have a gigantic room filled with spectacular mascot costumes now. [Executive producer] Tim Carvell and I \u2014 I think we\u2019ve always seen the show as our attempt to make The Muppet Show and failing to do so. But occasionally, just occasionally, you get the kind of Muppet Show adoration in the ludicrous mascots.\"<ref>https://www.vulture.com/2019/02/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-hbo-interview-mascots.html</ref>\n\nThe typical structure of the show is to open with a recap of a few of the week's news stories, segue into a video compilation, and then move on to Oliver's main segment. Some of the episodes will follow up the main segment with another video compilation or news story. Oliver's speech is broken up with video compilations of recent news clips, or recurring segments, into which Oliver segues with the slogan, \"And now, this.\" Oliver has also ended some segments with mock trailers for fictional TV shows or commercials that satirize the subject of his speech.\n\n=== Celebrity guests===\nThe show frequently features one or more celebrity guests in its segments to help Oliver better get his point on the week's topic across. Guests have featured in many different capacities including giving monologues directly to camera, being interviewed by Oliver, playing musical numbers, participating in comedic skits with or without Oliver, or starring in fictitious parody [[Public service announcement|PSAs]]. On the show, guests are sometimes seen in the Last Week Tonight studio itself doing their part during the show's main taping, while at other times they are seen in video clips that were pre-recorded at a different location and later included in the show. Oliver often interviews personalities who were directly involved in or impacted by the issues being discussed in the show to get their first-hand experiences and viewpoints on the issue. Some of the famous personalities Oliver has interviewed include [[Edward Snowden]], the [[14th Dalai Lama|14th]] [[Dalai Lama]], [[Anita Hill|Professor Anita Hill]] and [[Monica Lewinsky]].\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Last Week Tonight with John Oliver episodes}}\n{{:List of Last Week Tonight with John Oliver episodes}}\n\n==YouTube channel==\n''Last Week Tonight'' has a [[YouTube]] channel where videos are intermittently (depending on series) added after a show has aired.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/user/LastWeekTonight |title=Last Week Tonight channel |access-date=March 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313183030/https://www.youtube.com/user/LastWeekTonight |archive-date=March 13, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Most of the videos are of the main segment from each episode. Some extended clips are also available on the show's YouTube channel, as are \"Web Exclusives\" that are produced solely for the channel, such as a July 2016 video in which Oliver responded to negative comments left on the channel itself.<ref name=Emertainment/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Framke |first1=Caroline |title=John Oliver ends 2016 by confronting Last Week Tonight's role in the liberal echo chamber |url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2016/11/20/13678748/john-oliver-election-2016 |website=Vox |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |date=November 20, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163235/https://www.vox.com/culture/2016/11/20/13678748/john-oliver-election-2016 |archive-date=June 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rhodan |first1=Maya |title=Watch John Oliver Read Mean 'Fan Mail' from YouTube |url=http://time.com/4401025/watch-john-oliver-read-mean-fan-mail-from-youtube/ |website=Time |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |date=July 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501084644/http://time.com/4401025/watch-john-oliver-read-mean-fan-mail-from-youtube/ |archive-date=May 1, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe show's production has also created content specifically for fan use. For the March 19, 2017, episode, which reported on Bolivia's growing coalition of workers clad in zebra suits to educate civilians about traffic laws, the show's production recorded 23 minutes of a person in a zebra costume dancing and gesticulating before a green screen so that viewers could edit it into other videos for humorous effect.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bradley |first1=Laura |title=John Oliver Slams Trump's Budget, Lightens Mood with Dancing Zebras |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/03/john-oliver-donald-trump-budget-proposal-dancing-zebras |website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |date=March 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608152244/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/03/john-oliver-donald-trump-budget-proposal-dancing-zebras |archive-date=June 8, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> A similar video called \"Real Animals, Fake Paws\" for use in reenacting [[U.S. Supreme Court]] cases was released after the October 19, 2014, episode where dogs were used instead of justices to make listening to oral court cases more amusing to the general public and to increase interest in the subject.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=tug71xZL7yc|title=Real Animals, Fake Paws Footage: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO)|last=LastWeekTonight|date=October 19, 2014|publisher=|via=YouTube|access-date=June 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620155905/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tug71xZL7yc|archive-date=June 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy April 2015, the channel had attained over a million subscribers.<ref name=Emertainment/> That number had risen to 3.6 million by July 2016,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Durkin |first1=J.D. |title=Oliver Responds to Harsh YouTube Comments in Newest Last Week Tonight Segment |url=https://www.mediaite.com/online/oliver-responds-to-harsh-youtube-comments-in-newest-last-week-tonight-segment/ |website=Mediaite |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |date=July 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163915/https://www.mediaite.com/online/oliver-responds-to-harsh-youtube-comments-in-newest-last-week-tonight-segment/ |archive-date=June 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and over 5 million by May 2017. {{As of|2020|April|df=}}, the channel had over 7.8 million subscribers and more than 2.4 billion views.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/user/LastWeekTonight/about \"Last Week Tonight\" videos] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170304225649/https://www.youtube.com/user/LastWeekTonight/about |date=March 4, 2017 }}. YouTube. Retrieved April 3, 2017.</ref>\n\n== Social media ==\n''Last Week Tonight'' has a Facebook page with over 2.6 million likes, a Twitter account with over 2.9 million followers, and an Instagram account with more than 450,000 followers {{As of|2019|July|lc=y|df=}}.\n\nOliver often makes use of joke [[hashtags]] to facilitate the [[viral spread]] of his videos on [[Twitter]] and [[Facebook]], as with the hashtag #NotMyChristian, which he used in 2014 to complain about the casting of actor [[Jamie Dornan]] in the feature film adaptation of ''[[Fifty Shades of Grey (film)|Fifty Shades of Grey]]''. The hashtag became a recurring punchline on the show, mentioned in both serious stories and casual segues.<ref name=\"Emertainment\" />\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:John Oliver 2014.jpg|thumb|250x250px|John Oliver, host of ''Last Week Tonight'']]\nOliver's debut show garnered 1.11 million viewers. The number of viewers online, through websites such as YouTube showing extended clips of different segments, have steadily climbed into multiple millions. The show's YouTube channel also features Web Exclusives which are occasionally posted when the main show is taking a week off. Across the TV airings, [[Digital video recorder|DVR]], [[Video on demand|on-demand]] and [[HBO Go]], ''Last Week Tonight'' averaged 4.1 million weekly viewers in its first season.<ref>{{cite news |last= O'Connell |first= Michael |title= John Oliver's Talk Show Ratings Edging Out HBO Colleague Bill Maher |work= The Hollywood Reporter |date= September 9, 2014 |url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-olivers-talk-show-ratings-735187 |accessdate= December 23, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141217013001/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-olivers-talk-show-ratings-735187 |archive-date= December 17, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n''Last Week Tonight'' has received widespread critical acclaim. Matthew Jacobs of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' named Oliver's program as 2014's best television show, writing \"the year's most surprising contribution to television is a show that bucked conventional formats, left us buzzing and paved the way for a burgeoning dynasty. ''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver'' is 2014's crowning achievement.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= Jacobs |first= Matthew |title= Why 'Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' Was 2014's Best Show |work= The Huffington Post |date= December 8, 2014 |url= https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/08/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-best-show-2014_n_6284074.html |accessdate= December 9, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141209032042/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/08/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-best-show-2014_n_6284074.html |archive-date= December 9, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n[[Hank Stuever]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' compared Oliver's program with ''The Daily Show'' several times in his review of Oliver's debut:\n\n<blockquote>Another scathing, stick-it-to-'em critique of American [[mass media]] and politics shellacked in satire and delivered by a funny if almost off-puttingly incredulous man with a British accent ... Exactly like ''The Daily Show'', the goal is to make elected and appointed officials, as well as just about any corporate enterprise, look foolish and inept while slyly culling together television news clips that make the media look equally inept at covering such evident truths.<ref>{{cite news |last= Stuever |first= Hank |title= John Oliver's 'Last Week Tonight' on HBO sticks to a familiar formula |work= The Washington Post |date= April 28, 2014 |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/style/wp/2014/04/28/john-olivers-last-week-tonight-on-hbo-sticks-to-a-familiar-formula/ |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150508221812/http://www.washingtonpost.com/news/style/wp/2014/04/28/john-olivers-last-week-tonight-on-hbo-sticks-to-a-familiar-formula/ |archive-date= May 8, 2015 |url-status= live }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n[[James Poniewozik]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' similarly compared ''Last Week'' with ''The Daily Show'', but also wrote that the \"full half-hour gives Oliver the room to do more,\" and praised Oliver's \"sharper tone and his globalist, English-outsider perspective,\" as well as his \"genuine passion over his subjects.\" Poniewozik wrote that Oliver's debut was \"a funny, confident start.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://time.com/79133/john-oliver-review-last-week/ |author= Poniewozik, James |date= April 28, 2014 |title= REVIEW: Last Week Tonight With John Oliver |work= Time |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140503214147/http://time.com/79133/john-oliver-review-last-week/ |archive-date= May 3, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' review began by ringing the same changes: \"The fear with ''Last Week Tonight'' is that it's ''The Daily Show'' except once a week&nbsp;\u2014 a staggered timeline that would rob the basic news-punning format of its intrinsic topical punch ... The first episode of his HBO series didn't stray far from the [[Jon Stewart|[Jon] Stewart]] mothership, stylistically ...\" However, the reviewer, Darren Franich, liked that Oliver has \"a half-hour of television that is simultaneously tighter and more ambitious, that the extra production time leads to sharper gags but also the ability to present more context\" and thought that the debut had \"plenty of funny throwaway lines.\" Franich appreciated Oliver's coverage of [[2014 Indian general election|the 2014 Indian election]], which the American press was largely ignoring,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/alyssaayres/2014/05/01/thanks-john-oliver-why-india-isnt-a-big-focus-for-u-s-television/ |last= Ayres |first= Alyssa |date= May 1, 2014 |title= Thanks, John Oliver! Why India Isn't a Big Focus for U.S. Television |work= [[Forbes]] |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140504055011/http://www.forbes.com/sites/alyssaayres/2014/05/01/thanks-john-oliver-why-india-isnt-a-big-focus-for-u-s-television/ |archive-date= May 4, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref> and, like Poniewozik, praised Oliver's \"passion.\" Franich concluded that ''Last Week Tonight'' \"suggested the sharpest possible version of its inspiration\" and that it \"should feel like an experiment\" but \"felt almost fully formed.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/04/28/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-review/ |last= Franich |first= Darren |date= April 28, 2014 |title= 'Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' review: The Weekly Show |work= Entertainment Weekly |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140503045808/http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/04/28/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-review/ |archive-date= May 3, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nDavid Haglund of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' was ambivalent, writing that the show is \"obviously a work in progress\" and that one segment \"felt like misplaced overkill,\" but also that it is \"good use of a weekly show, and it was funny to boot.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/television/2014/04/the_premiere_of_john_oliver_s_hbo_show_last_week_tonight_reviewed.html |last= Haglund |first= David |date= April 2014 |title= Last Week Tonight: Like The Daily Show, With Unbleeped Swears! |work= Slate |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140504203605/http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/television/2014/04/the_premiere_of_john_oliver_s_hbo_show_last_week_tonight_reviewed.html |archive-date= May 4, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref> [[Gawker]]'s Jordan Sargent claimed ''Last Week Tonight'' was \"the new ''Daily Show'',\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://defamer.gawker.com/john-olivers-last-week-tonight-is-the-new-daily-show-1572116205/all |author=Sargent, Jordan |date=May 6, 2014 |title=John Oliver's Last Week Tonight is the New Daily Show |publisher=Gawker |accessdate=May 6, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507030451/http://defamer.gawker.com/john-olivers-last-week-tonight-is-the-new-daily-show-1572116205/all |archivedate=May 7, 2014 }}</ref> while simultaneously criticizing the ''Daily Show'' for abandoning those \"who have moved on from caring about [[Fox News|Fox [News]]] and [[Republican Party of the United States|Republicans]].\"\n\nA number of commentators from mainstream media outlets, including ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/17/business/media/john-olivers-complicated-fun-connects-for-hbo.html|title=John Oliver's Complicated Fun Connects for HBO|date=November 16, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|last=Carr|first=David|newspaper=The New York Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150501135440/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/17/business/media/john-olivers-complicated-fun-connects-for-hbo.html|archive-date=May 1, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Huffington Post'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/26/john-oliver-journalism_n_5888184.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150814125641/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/26/john-oliver-journalism_n_5888184.html |archivedate=August 14, 2015|title=John Oliver Is Doing Some Really Good Investigative Journalism|date=September 26, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|last=Bauder|first=David|work=The Huffington Post}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3589285/unfortunately-john-oliver-you-are-a-journalist/|title=Unfortunately, John Oliver, You Are a Journalist|last=Poniewozik|first=James|date=November 17, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|work=Time|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725193947/http://time.com/3589285/unfortunately-john-oliver-you-are-a-journalist/|archive-date=July 25, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Associated Press]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/with-journalism-in-quiver-john-oliver-transcends-his-schtick-1.1760408|title=With journalism in quiver, John Oliver transcends his schtick|date=September 25, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|last=Bauder|first=David|agency=Associated Press|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614075700/http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/with-journalism-in-quiver-john-oliver-transcends-his-schtick-1.1760408|archive-date=June 14, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> have described Oliver's style of reporting as journalism or even investigative journalism. Oliver himself disagrees, stating that \"it's not journalism, it's comedy\u2014it's comedy first, and it's comedy second.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/last-week-tonight-does-real-journalism-no-matter-what-john-oliver-says|title='Last Week Tonight' Does Real Journalism, No Matter What John Oliver Says|last=Suebsaeng|first=Asawin|newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=September 29, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602195007/http://www.thedailybeast.com/last-week-tonight-does-real-journalism-no-matter-what-john-oliver-says|archive-date=June 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n{{:List of awards and nominations received by Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n\n==Reaction and influence==\nA [[Net Neutrality (Last Week Tonight)#\"Net Neutrality\"|June 2014 segment]] about [[net neutrality in the United States]] was thought to spur over 45,000 comments on the [[Federal Communications Commission]]'s electronic filing page about a net neutrality proposal that, if implemented, would have priority \"lanes\" for certain internet traffic. The FCC also received an extra 300,000 comments in an email inbox designated specifically for the proposal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2014/06/03/318458496/john-oliver-helps-rally-45-000-net-neutrality-comments-to-fcc|title=John Oliver Helps Rally 45,000 Net Neutrality Comments To FCC|last=Hu|first=Elise|work=NPR|date=June 3, 2014|accessdate=September 12, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150624041323/http://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2014/06/03/318458496/john-oliver-helps-rally-45-000-net-neutrality-comments-to-fcc|archive-date=June 24, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It was thought that Oliver's segment had a major role in the FCC's ultimate reversal of stance on that proposal,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Society/2015/0226/Net-neutrality-s-stunning-reversal-of-fortune-Is-it-John-Oliver-s-doing|title=Net neutrality's stunning reversal of fortune: Is it John Oliver's doing?|last=Bruinius|first=Harry|date=February 26, 2015|work=Christian Science Monitor|accessdate=September 15, 2017|issn=0882-7729|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922102025/https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Society/2015/0226/Net-neutrality-s-stunning-reversal-of-fortune-Is-it-John-Oliver-s-doing|archive-date=September 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> with the FCC instead implementing net-neutrality rules that prohibited priority \"lanes\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/03/12/technology/net-neutrality-rules-explained.html|title=What the Net Neutrality Rules Say|last=Sommer|first=Jeff|date=March 12, 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 13, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150313080607/http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/03/12/technology/net-neutrality-rules-explained.html|archive-date=March 13, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> A sequel in 2017 inspired over 150,000 comments on a subsequent proposal to scrap the new net neutrality rules.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/talkingtech/2017/05/09/john-oliver-may-have-helped-spur-150000-comments-fcc-net-neutrality/101480100/|title=John Oliver may have helped spur 150,000 comments to FCC on Net neutrality|last=Snider|first=Mike|date=May 10, 2017|work=USA TODAY|access-date=September 22, 2017|last2=Weise|first2=Elizabeth|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922101510/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/talkingtech/2017/05/09/john-oliver-may-have-helped-spur-150000-comments-fcc-net-neutrality/101480100/|archive-date=September 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA segment on the then [[Prime Minister of Australia]] [[Tony Abbott]] received widespread attention in Australia across the mainstream media and was trending on [[social media]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/tony-abbott-lambasted-on-us-tv-show-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver/news-story/cb0df94da804403072b59016dadf12b8|last= Bond|first= Nick|date= June 3, 2014|title= Tony Abbott lambasted on US TV show Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|publisher= [[News Corp Australia]]|accessdate= June 5, 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170922002508/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/tony-abbott-lambasted-on-us-tv-show-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver/news-story/cb0df94da804403072b59016dadf12b8|archive-date= September 22, 2017|url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/554572/20140603/tony-abbot-last-week-tonight-john-oliver.htm#.U4-z_CgkRTY |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140603190359/http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/554572/20140603/tony-abbot-last-week-tonight-john-oliver.htm#.U4-z_CgkRTY |archivedate= June 3, 2014 |author= Ma Evelyn Castino Quilas |date= June 3, 2014 |title= Tony Abbott Mocked in U.S. News Program, Aussies Cringe on Twitter |work= International Business Times |accessdate= June 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/tony-abbott-roasted-by-john-oliver-on-hbo-show-last-week-tonight-20140602-zrvl1.html |author= Nick Toscano |date= June 2, 2014 |title= Tony Abbott roasted by John Oliver on HBO show Last Week Tonight |work= [[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |accessdate= June 5, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180227040314/https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/tony-abbott-roasted-by-john-oliver-on-hbo-show-last-week-tonight-20140602-zrvl1.html |archive-date= February 27, 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to a document obtained by ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'', the military government of [[Thailand]] listed Oliver as \"[[L\u00e8se majest\u00e9 in Thailand|undermining the royal institution]]\" for calling Crown Prince [[Vajiralongkorn]] a \"buffoon\" and an \"idiot.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.vice.com/article/thailands-military-government-thinks-john-oliver-is-a-threat-to-its-monarchy|title=Thailand's Military Government Thinks John Oliver Is a Threat to Its Monarchy|last=Marshall|first=Andrew|publisher=Vice|date=July 24, 2014|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163841/https://news.vice.com/article/thailands-military-government-thinks-john-oliver-is-a-threat-to-its-monarchy|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jul/29/thai-junta-comedian-john-oliver-royal-jibes|last=Hodal|first=Kate|title=Thai junta unamused by comedian John Oliver's royal jibes|work=The Guardian|date=July 29, 2014|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163837/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jul/29/thai-junta-comedian-john-oliver-royal-jibes|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe show also made international headlines following Oliver's interview with [[Edward Snowden]], which included a graphic, in-depth conversation about the amount of power the [[United States government]] has at its disposal in terms of intelligence, both domestic and foreign. Oliver also confronted Snowden about the lack of knowledge of the American people about his work and why they may be hesitant to analyze it for themselves rather than accept preconceived notions of him being a [[whistleblower]]. Notably, he tried to help Snowden in creating public awareness for the fundamentality of the surveillance problem in putting forward the question \"Can they see my dick?\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/06/media/edward-snowden-john-oliver-interview/index.html|title=John Oliver lands Edward Snowden interview from Russia|publisher=CNNMoney|date=April 6, 2015|first=Brian|last=Stelter|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618211744/http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/06/media/edward-snowden-john-oliver-interview/index.html|archive-date=June 18, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/apr/06/edward-snowden-john-oliver-last-week-tonight-nsa-leaked-documents|title=John Oliver presses Edward Snowden on whether he read all leaked NSA material|last=Yuhas|first=Alan|work=The Guardian|date=April 6, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163305/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/apr/06/edward-snowden-john-oliver-last-week-tonight-nsa-leaked-documents|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn a segment about [[public defender]]s and how some offices are extremely underfunded, the New Orleans Public Defense office's crowdfunding efforts to improve their conditions were featured. In the days following the episode's broadcast, thousands of dollars were donated to the office by the show's fans, helping them raise their goal four days after the show aired.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://opdla.causevox.com/ |title=Orleans Public Defenders crowd-funding |publisher=causevox.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150917061217/http://opdla.causevox.com/ |archive-date=September 17, 2015 |url-status=dead |access-date=September 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFor a segment in the October 18, 2015, broadcast, Oliver put on a comically grand demonstration with Canadian actor [[Mike Myers]] to urge Canadian voters to vote against [[Stephen Harper]] in the next day's [[2015 Canadian federal election|Canadian federal election]]. As part of this gesture, Oliver displayed $5000 in cash in anticipation of being charged for the crime of being a foreigner attempting to induce Canadian citizens to change their vote as per section 331 of the [[Canada Elections Act]]. However, the agency responsible for overseeing federal elections in Canada, [[Elections Canada]], explained the next day that prosecution of Oliver will not be necessary since inducement in the act is defined as offering something material to voters. Per Elections Canada, Oliver has not tried to influence Canadian electorate, since the money shown was only for the anticipated fine, but merely expressed his opinion as a bystander, which is lawful.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Edwards|first1=Peter|title=Why John Oliver won't go to jail for flouting Canadian election law|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/federal-election/2015/10/19/john-oliver-flouts-canadian-election-law-to-blast-harper.html|accessdate=November 17, 2015|work=Toronto Star|date=October 19, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118044508/http://www.thestar.com/news/federal-election/2015/10/19/john-oliver-flouts-canadian-election-law-to-blast-harper.html|archive-date=November 18, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the June 17, 2018 episode, Oliver spoke at length about [[Xi Jinping]], [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]], in part criticizing his [[Censorship in China|censorship]] of Chinese media, his dictatorship<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cfr.org/backgrounder/media-censorship-china|title=Media Censorship in China|work=Council on Foreign Relations|access-date=June 23, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330080256/https://www.cfr.org/backgrounder/media-censorship-china|archive-date=March 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and consolidation of power.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/2135962/why-now-rationale-behind-xi-jinpings-power-consolidation|title=Why now? The rationale behind Xi Jinping's power consolidation|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=June 23, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624040136/http://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/2135962/why-now-rationale-behind-xi-jinpings-power-consolidation|archive-date=June 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Both \"John Oliver\" and \"Last Week Tonight\" were blocked from Chinese social media platform [[Sina Weibo]] immediately following the segment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-44557528|title=Chinese social media censors John Oliver|date=June 21, 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=June 23, 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622134355/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-44557528|archive-date=June 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[HBO]] website and content from the network were also blocked,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/2152323/china-blocks-hbo-after-john-oliver-parody-xi-jinping|title=China blocks HBO after John Oliver mockery of Xi Jinping|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=June 25, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625185611/http://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/2152323/china-blocks-hbo-after-john-oliver-parody-xi-jinping|archive-date=June 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> although Last Week Tonight had already been excluded from [[HBO (Asia)|HBO Asia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/25/world/asia/china-hbo-john-oliver-xi-jinping.html|title=China Blocks HBO Website After John Oliver's Jokes About Xi Jinping|access-date=June 25, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625130936/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/25/world/asia/china-hbo-john-oliver-xi-jinping.html|archive-date=June 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe promotion for Season 3 highlighted four derogatory quotes either the show or Oliver himself received: \"Comedian fool\" (former [[FIFA]] vice-president [[Jack Warner (football executive)|Jack Warner]], responding to a segment on the [[2015 FIFA corruption case]]), \"Makes people dumb\" (an article ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' wrote about the show), \"Very boring\" ([[Donald Trump]]'s assessment of the show), and \"More unpleasant than a diuretic\" (what [[President of Ecuador]] [[Rafael Correa]] said \"gringo talk shows\" were like, after being featured in a segment).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/136882-when-does-last-week-tonight-season-3-premiere-john-olivers-hit-show-is-about-to-jazz|title=When Does 'Last Week Tonight' Season 3 Premiere? John Oliver's Hit Show Is About To Jazz Up Your Winter|last=Tognotti|first=Chris|date=January 20, 2016|website=Bustle|accessdate=April 12, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402032053/http://www.bustle.com/articles/136882-when-does-last-week-tonight-season-3-premiere-john-olivers-hit-show-is-about-to-jazz|archive-date=April 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== The John Oliver Effect ===\n{{Main|John Oliver#Influence and the \"John Oliver effect\"|l1 = John Oliver (Influence)}}\nOn several occasions, show segments on major societal issues, such as the \"Chickens\" or \"Bail\" segments, were soon followed by real-world change and action on said issues by the public, policymakers and/or other institutions. Several media outlets, noticing this pattern, suggested that attention from the show had instigated these changes, going so far as to dub the phenomenon the \"John Oliver Effect\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/3674807/john-oliver-net-neutrality-civil-forfeiture-miss-america/|title=How the 'John Oliver Effect' Is Having a Real-Life Impact|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2015/09/29/john-oliver-impact/|title=The John Oliver Effect|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> One of the most commonly cited examples of this is Oliver's first Net Neutrality segment which allegedly led to more than 45,000 comments being sent to the [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]], crashing the website set up to receive comments in the process.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/jun/03/john-oliver-fcc-website-net-neutrality|title=John Oliver's cheeky net neutrality plea crashes FCC website|last=Holpuch|first=Amanda|date=2014-06-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nOliver himself does not believe the effect to be real and has openly ridiculed the idea on the show, even calling the term \"completely meaningless\".{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Tobacco===\n{{Main|Tobacco (Last Week Tonight)}}\n\"Tobacco\" is a segment about the tobacco industry, which aired on February 15, 2015, as part of the second episode of the second season. During the eighteen-minute segment, Oliver discusses tobacco industry trends and practices. He also introduces Jeff the Diseased Lung, a mascot he created for the American global cigarette and tobacco company [[Philip Morris International]], the makers of [[Marlboro (cigarette)|Marlboro]] brand of cigarettes. The anthropomorphic diseased lung, who smokes and coughs, has been compared to Joe Camel and the [[Marlboro Man]]. Oliver and his team promoted the cartoon character by sending shirts with Jeff's image to [[Togo]] and displaying billboards in [[Uruguay]], and by encouraging use of the hashtag #JeffWeCan, which trended on Twitter following the broadcast.\n\nThe segment received widespread media coverage, with several outlets praising Oliver's ability to launch successful marketing campaigns and change perceptions about smoking through the creation of the mascot. The mascot later made an appearance at a protest organized by the \"Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids\" in New York City in May 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.medicaldaily.com/john-olivers-jeff-diseased-lung-hits-times-square-anti-smoking-awareness-flash-mob-332252|last=Olson|first=Samantha|title=John Oliver's 'Jeff The Diseased Lung' Hits Times Square For Anti-Smoking Awareness Flash Mob|date=May 6, 2015|work=Medical Daily|access-date=September 3, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915181858/http://www.medicaldaily.com/john-olivers-jeff-diseased-lung-hits-times-square-anti-smoking-awareness-flash-mob-332252|archive-date=September 15, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kickbuttsday.org/index.php/updates/detail/2015_05_22_nyc|title=Youth advocates head to New York City to #StopMarlboro - Kick Butts Day|last=Olmstead|first=Erica|website=Kick Butts Day|date=May 22, 2015|access-date=September 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163701/https://www.kickbuttsday.org/index.php/updates/detail/2015_05_22_nyc|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPhilip Morris International issued a response to the segment, stating that it included \"many mischaracterizations\" of the company.<ref name=Parker>{{cite news|last=Parker|first=Ryan|title=John Oliver targets cigarettes on 'Last Week Tonight'; Philip Morris reacts|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-philip-morris-john-oliver-20150216-story.html|accessdate=November 24, 2015|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=February 16, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151122195954/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-philip-morris-john-oliver-20150216-story.html|archive-date=November 22, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Stranger Than Truth: John Oliver's 101 Favorite History Lies ===\nIn the Mandatory Minimums segment that aired on July 25, 2015, John Oliver talked about the controversial history of presidential pardoning, claiming that Abraham Lincoln once pardoned a man convicted of bestiality because he was intoxicated at the time; the man in question being John Wilkes Booth. He then confessed the statement was not true and for the first time mentioned a book compiling his favorite history lies.\n\nA couple of weeks later, he published a web-exclusive video  based on that reference, expanding the content for a book called \"Stranger Than Truth: John Oliver's 101 Favorite History Lies\", to be released in the following spring. At the end of the mini-segment, however, he confesses again that the entire book was also a lie.\n\nIn what seems a continuation of the lie saga, the book surprisingly appeared on Amazon UK in October 2018.\n\nThe book description reads as follow: <blockquote>There is absolutely nothing more fun than lying confidently about history. Lying is incredibly fun. In fact, the only thing that feels better than lying to someone is lying to someone, then regaining their trust, and then lying to them again. This book, for example, was promised to be released in April 2016. But that was a lie. The plan was always October 2018. Because, you know, now is a time in history when lying openly gets you elected to office. </blockquote><blockquote>In this book, you will find plenty of plausible but completely unverifiable nonsense. Almost like watching Fox News but with a better sense of humour. Hopefully, it will teach you much about nothing other than the true joy of lying to people. Honestly, there has never been a better moment in history to be a liar. We have reached a point where truths have become lies and lies are now the truth. So learn from the greatest and get inspired by the best lies in history. </blockquote><blockquote>*NB: Most profits from this book are going to finance railway infrastructure under the English Channel. Contains strong language.<ref>{{Cite book|title=STRANGER THAN TRUTH.|last=PAUL.|first=OSPREY, FEY. DORIAN|date=2018|publisher=BLURB|isbn=978-0464820208|location=[S.l.]|oclc=1057754076}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption===\n{{Main|Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption}}\nIn August 2015, after delivering his \"Televangelists\" segment, Oliver hired a professional tax lawyer to set up a church called [[Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption]] as a legal entity. He did this partly as a way to demonstrate how \"disturbingly easy\" it is, in terms of paperwork, to set up a [[Tax exemption|tax-exempt]] religious organization as viewed by the [[Internal Revenue Service]]. As Oliver explained, the requirements needed to be defined as a \"church\" are quite broad. Since regulatory guidelines require an established location for a church, Oliver chose his studio location in New York City as its official location,<ref name=\"Mediaite\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/john-oliver-one-ups-colbert-super-pac-by-creating-his-own-tax-exempt-church/ |last=Wilstein |first=Matt |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=John Oliver One-Ups Colbert Super PAC by Creating His Own Tax-Exempt Church |work=Mediaite |quote=\"... This is real,\" John Oliver repeatedly told his Last Week Tonight audience last night after announcing the creation of his new megachurch, Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption ...\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150825011710/http://www.mediaite.com/tv/john-oliver-one-ups-colbert-super-pac-by-creating-his-own-tax-exempt-church/ |archive-date=August 25, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> although he registered the [[nonprofit organization]] in the state of [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://religionnews.com/2015/08/18/john-oliver-hbo-last-week-tonight-televangelists-church-irs-creflo-dollar-tilton-copeland/ |last=Pellot |first=Brian |date=August 18, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title='Megareverend' John Oliver trolls televangelists with new tax-exempt church |agency=[[Religion News Service]] |quote=\"... Oliver registered his church as a nonprofit corporation in Texas, named his New York studio as its \"established place of worship,\"...\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150819025650/http://www.religionnews.com/2015/08/18/john-oliver-hbo-last-week-tonight-televangelists-church-irs-creflo-dollar-tilton-copeland/ |archive-date=August 19, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Oliver's \"megachurch\" had a [[Toll-free telephone number|toll-free phone number]] which allowed callers to donate to the church, and said that any money collected would be redistributed to the charitable relief organization [[Doctors Without Borders]].<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite news |url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/08/john-oliver-takes-on-televangelism-on-last-week-tonight |first=Nate |last=Scott |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=John Oliver takes on televangelism on 'Last Week Tonight' |work=[[USA Today]] |quote=... You can donate to the church, too. (Though eventually, all the donations will be moved to Doctors Without Borders.) ... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822104843/http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/08/john-oliver-takes-on-televangelism-on-last-week-tonight |archive-date=August 22, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Pedestrian>{{cite web |url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/entertainment/john-oliver-launches-his-very-own-anti-evangelist-church/ |last=Bracken |first=Claire |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=John Oliver launches his very own anti-Evangelist church |work=Pedestrian News |quote=\"... John Oliver ran a segment on \"church's who exploit people's faith for monetary gain\" and explored the ease at which these can be created in America ...\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904194105/https://www.pedestrian.tv/entertainment/john-oliver-launches-his-very-own-anti-evangelist-church/ |archive-date=September 4, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Oliver announced the formation of his church on the episode of the show that aired on August 16, 2015.<ref name=\"TimeMag\">{{cite news |url=http://time.com/3999933/john-oliver-televangelist-church-alst-week-tonight/ |first=Melissa |last=Locker |title=John Oliver Becomes a Televangelist and Finally Starts His Own Church |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |work=Time |quote=... The satirical aim of Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption will be to collect copious, tax-exempt donations ... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824174155/http://time.com/3999933/john-oliver-televangelist-church-alst-week-tonight/ |archive-date=August 24, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nMatt Wilstein, writing for ''[[Mediaite]]'', saw Oliver's stunt as being along the same lines as comedian [[Stephen Colbert]]'s setting up of a [[501(c)(4)]] organization\u2014[[Colbert Super PAC]]\u2014as a way to \"test the absurd limits of the Supreme Court's [[Citizens United v. FEC|Citizens United decision]]\"; Oliver's megachurch, in contrast, is a way to test whether the IRS might view his \"megachurch\" as a tax-exempt organization.<ref name=\"Mediaite\"/> Steve Thorngate, writing in ''[[The Christian Century]]'', suggested that the question of the religious exemption from taxation was more difficult and nuanced than Oliver portrayed, and not a simple matter of government regulation, describing Oliver's pivot to IRS policy as \"unhelpful.\" However, Thorngate agreed that Oliver's exposure and criticism of \"manipulative sleazeballs\" who \"fleece the faithful\" is \"spot-on.\"<ref name=\"ChristianCentury\">{{cite web |url=https://www.christiancentury.org/blogs/archive/2015-08/why-john-olivers-televangelism-segment-about-irs |first=Steve |last=Thorngate |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=Why is John Oliver's televangelism segment about the IRS? |work=The Christian Century |quote=\"... Oliver's scornful outrage: televangelists who fleece the faithful ... The question of religious tax exemption generally is more complicated. ...\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150820000830/http://www.christiancentury.org/blogs/archive/2015-08/why-john-olivers-televangelism-segment-about-irs |archive-date=August 20, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Leonardo Blair, writing for ''[[Christian Post]]'', described Oliver's segment as a \"brutal takedown\" of televangelists and churches which preach \"the [[prosperity theology|prosperity gospel]],\" a message that dupes people into thinking that cash donations will solve medical or financial problems, while in fact the donations go to the personal aggrandizement of televangelists who buy expensive jets or large mansions.<ref name=\"ChristianPost\">{{cite web |url=https://www.christianpost.com/news/comedian-john-oliver-lampoons-televangelists-on-last-week-tonight-show-opens-our-lady-of-perpetual-exemption-church-143003/ |first=Blair |last=Leonardo |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=Comedian John Oliver Lampoons Televangelists on 'Last Week Tonight' Show; Opens Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption Church |work=[[The Christian Post]] |quote=... From Creflo Dollar to Kenneth Copeland, late night comedian John Oliver delivered a brutal takedown. ... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150823142157/http://www.christianpost.com/news/comedian-john-oliver-lampoons-televangelists-on-last-week-tonight-show-opens-our-lady-of-perpetual-exemption-church-143003/ |archive-date=August 23, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA week later, on the following episode, Oliver devoted a short segment to the donations the church had received, which included money from around the world. Oliver said he had received \"thousands of envelopes with thousands of dollars\" from donors. Displayed were several US Post Office containers full of mail. Oliver told viewers that the more money they sent in, the more \"blessings\" would be returned to them, adding that \"that is still something I'm \u2014 amazingly \u2014 legally allowed to say.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title = John Oliver Televangelist Church Received \"Thousands of Dollars,\" Seeds and Beef Jerky|url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-televangelist-church-received-817058|website = The Hollywood Reporter|date = August 24, 2015|accessdate = August 25, 2015|quote = ... We have received thousands of envelopes with thousands of dollars ...|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150826221454/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-televangelist-church-received-817058|archive-date = August 26, 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nOliver announced that the Church would be shutting down during his show on September 13, 2015. All monetary donations have been forwarded to Doctors Without Borders.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourladyofperpetualexemption.com/ | title=Closed. Praise Be Unto You | date=September 13, 2015 | accessdate=September 13, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150827212918/http://www.ourladyofperpetualexemption.com/ | archive-date=August 27, 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Donald Trump ===\n{{Main|Donald Trump (Last Week Tonight)|Last Week Tonight segments about Donald Trump}}\n[[Donald Trump (Last Week Tonight)|\"Donald Trump\"]] is a segment discussing American businessman Donald Trump. It aired on February 28, 2016, as part of the third episode of the third season. During the 22-minute segment, Oliver discusses [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Trump's 2016 presidential campaign]] and his long career in business. He also reveals that the Trump family name was changed at one point from the ancestral name 'Drumpf'. Although the changing of names was once a common [[Anglicisation of names|practice]] among many non-English immigrants to the United States, the segment popularized the term \"Donald Drumpf\" and started a campaign urging viewers to \"Make Donald Drumpf Again,\" a play on Trump's own campaign slogan, \"[[Make America Great Again]].\" It is the most popular segment the show has ever done. The segment garnered more than 85 million views on Facebook and YouTube combined which, an HBO spokesman has said, \"is a record for any piece of HBO content.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/03/30/media/john-oliver-donald-trump/index.html|title=Even John Oliver enjoys a Drumpf bump|last=Stelter|first=Brian|date=March 30, 2016|website=CNNMoney|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331201056/http://money.cnn.com/2016/03/30/media/john-oliver-donald-trump/index.html|archive-date=March 31, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Throughout the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]] and following [[Inauguration of Donald Trump|Trump's inauguration]], Oliver made [[Last Week Tonight segments about Donald Trump|additional segments regarding Trump]].\n\n===Debt buyers===\n\"Debt Buyers\" is a segment discussing the business and questionable practice of [[debt buyers]]. It aired on June 5, 2016, as part of the fourteenth episode of the third season. Oliver announced he had purchased nearly $15 million in medical debt that belonged to 9,000 debtors. He did this through a company he had created, called \"Central Asset Recovery Professionals Inc.\" (CARP), which he described as being \"for [[Carp|the bottom-feeding fish]].\" Oliver stated that it was \"pretty clear by now [that] debt buying is a grimy business, and badly needs more oversight\" and went to point out that starting such a business was \"disturbingly easy.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2016/06/06/john-oliver-buys-and-forgives-15-million-of-debt-last-week-tonight/85488616/ |first=Kelly |last=Lawler |title=John Oliver buys and forgives $15 million of debt |website=USA Today |date=June 6, 2016 |accessdate=June 6, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160606180535/http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2016/06/06/john-oliver-buys-and-forgives-15-million-of-debt-last-week-tonight/85488616/ |archive-date=June 6, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> It cost him $50 to register the business in [[Mississippi]], while it cost less than $60,000 to purchase almost $15 million in [[bad debt]], medical debt from Texas. Oliver forgave the debt in its entirety, and claimed that it was the largest single giveaway in the American television history, eclipsing that of [[General Motors]] on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' in 2004 where it gifted cars to Winfrey's studio audience, worth an estimated $8 million in total.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/news/archive/2016/06/john-oliver-debt/485834/ | first=J. Weston | last=Phippen | title=John Oliver's $15 Million Debt Giveaway | website=The Atlantic | date=June 6, 2016 | accessdate=June 6, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160607105724/http://www.theatlantic.com/news/archive/2016/06/john-oliver-debt/485834/ | archive-date=June 7, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Writing for ''Slate'', Jordan Weissmann disputed the $15 million figure: \"[Oliver] says CARP paid around $60,000 ... for its paper, which was 'out-of-statute'\u2014meaning the debts were so old that creditors technically couldn't even sue over them anymore. That suggests the seller thought the debts were worth no more than, well, $60,000.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/moneybox/2016/06/06/john_oliver_did_not_really_give_away_15_million_on_his_show.html |title=Sorry, but John Oliver Did Not Really Just Give Away $15 Million |last=Weissmann |first=Jordan |date=June 6, 2016 |newspaper=Slate |issn=1091-2339 |access-date=June 7, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160606221649/http://www.slate.com/blogs/moneybox/2016/06/06/john_oliver_did_not_really_give_away_15_million_on_his_show.html |archive-date=June 6, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The episode was highlighted in the academic journal ''Religions''.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Krantz |first=David |title=Shmita Revolution: The Reclamation and Reinvention of the Sabbatical Year |work=Religions |date=August 8, 2016 |url=http://www.mdpi.com/2077-1444/7/8/100 |accessdate=August 30, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920052704/http://www.mdpi.com/2077-1444/7/8/100 |archive-date=September 20, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The show partnered with RIP Medical Debt, Inc. to abolish the debt.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kasperkevic |first1=Jana |title=John Oliver buys and forgives $15m worth of medical debt |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/jun/06/john-oliver-medical-debt-forgiveness-last-week-tonight |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=June 6, 2016 |quote=Instead of collecting the debt, however, Last Week Tonight partnered with RIP Medical Debt charity and decided to forgive that debt. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619140428/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/jun/06/john-oliver-medical-debt-forgiveness-last-week-tonight |archive-date=June 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ripmedicaldebt.org/the-miracle-of-debt-forgiveness-on-hbos-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver/|title=The Miracle of Debt Forgiveness on HBO's Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|last=Goff|first=Robert|website=RIP Medical Debt, Inc.|date=June 5, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115132834/https://www.ripmedicaldebt.org/the-miracle-of-debt-forgiveness-on-hbos-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver/|archive-date=November 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Coal mining and Bob Murray ===\nOn June 18, 2017, ''Last Week Tonight''{{'}}s main segment was about coal mining and [[Robert E. Murray|Bob Murray]]. In his segment, Oliver talked about how the safety condition inside the coal mines specifically the 2007 [[Crandall Canyon Mine]] collapse, which killed six miners, in which Oliver criticized Murray for claiming the collapse was caused by an [[earthquake]], despite all evidence demonstrating otherwise.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsy.com/stories/coal-ceo-sues-john-oliver-and-his-show-for-defamation/|title=John Oliver Is In Legal Trouble For His Rant About A Coal CEO|last=Suneson|first=Grant|work=Newsy|date=June 22, 2017|accessdate=June 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623041444/http://www.newsy.com/stories/coal-ceo-sues-john-oliver-and-his-show-for-defamation/|archive-date=June 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The show ended with a costumed [[squirrel]] named \"Mr. Nutterbutter\" presenting Murray with a voided check for \"3 acorns and 18 cents\" in response to Murray's company presenting its employees with low sums of money as bonuses, and how the employees retaliate by voiding the checks, and in reference to a claim that stated that Murray supposedly got the idea to start his company from a talking squirrel.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Coal: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO) |series=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver |date=June 18, 2017 |accessdate=June 23, 2017 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aw6RsUhw1Q8 |network=HBO |last=Oliver |first=John (host) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623002244/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aw6RsUhw1Q8 |archivedate=June 23, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> On June 22, Bob Murray presented a [[lawsuit]] against Oliver, HBO, and [[Time Warner]] for defamation. HBO believes ''Last Week Tonight'' has done nothing wrong, with a [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] lawyer describing the lawsuit as \"frivolous.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In February 2018, a West Virginia judge stated that he plans to dismiss the lawsuit filed by Murray as unfounded.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Oppenheim|first1=Maya|title=Coal tycoon's defamation lawsuit against John Oliver dismissed by judge|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/john-oliver-bob-murray-defamation-lawsuit-dismissed-judge-murray-energy-corp-a8226846.html|accessdate=February 26, 2018|work=The Independent|date=February 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225060807/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/john-oliver-bob-murray-defamation-lawsuit-dismissed-judge-murray-energy-corp-a8226846.html|archive-date=February 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter Murray's appeal to the West Virginia Supreme Court was delayed due to impeachment of the judges, Murray offered to drop the charges and HBO accepted.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2019/nov/11/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-lawsuits-murray-energy|title=John Oliver takes on muzzling lawsuits \u2013 and the man who sued his show|last=Horton|first=Adrian|date=November 11, 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On November 10, 2019, Oliver discussed the case in a segment about [[SLAPP|SLAPP suits]], revealing that the suit cost HBO $200,000 in legal costs and tripled the show's libel insurance fees. Oliver acknowledged that, despite the segment being vetted, the content would likely lead to another lawsuit, and that he would stand behind his team if it were to happen.<ref name=\":1\" /> The segment was ended with a five-minute, [[Times Square]]-set [[musical number]] featuring crude and ludicrous fictional anecdotes about Murray; the musical is titled \"Eat Shit, Bob.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===''A Day in the Life of Marlon Bundo''===\n{{Main|A Day in the Life of Marlon Bundo}}\nOn March 18, 2018, Oliver announced the publication of a children's book, ''[[A Day in the Life of Marlon Bundo]]'', which parodies a book that [[Mike Pence]]'s family wrote about their family rabbit, [[Marlon Bundo's: A Day in the Life of the Vice President|Marlon Bundo]]. Oliver used his book as a platform to criticize Pence's positions on LGBT issues, as it featured a rabbit in a same-sex relationship.<ref name=\"Daily Beast Bundo\">{{cite news |last=Stern |first=Marlow |date=March 19, 2018 |title=John Oliver Trolls Vice President Mike Pence With Gay Children's Book of His Pet Bunny |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/john-oliver-trolls-vice-president-mike-pence-with-gay-childrens-book-of-his-pet-bunny |work=Daily Beast |location= |access-date=March 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319104738/https://www.thedailybeast.com/john-oliver-trolls-vice-president-mike-pence-with-gay-childrens-book-of-his-pet-bunny |archive-date=March 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The book became the number-one book and e-book on [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] the next day, and the top-selling audiobook on [[Audible (store)|Audible]].<ref name=\"Politico Bundo\">{{cite news |last=Nelson |first=Louis |date=March 19, 2018 |title=Comey's memoir tops Amazon's best-sellers list |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/03/19/james-comey-memoir-sales-470281 |work=Politico |location= |access-date=March 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319140528/https://www.politico.com/story/2018/03/19/james-comey-memoir-sales-470281 |archive-date=March 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/03/john-oliver-marlon-bundo-book-mike-pence-troll|title=John Oliver's Gay-Bunny Book Is Outselling the Mike Pence Book It's Trolling|first=Hillary|last=Busis|website=Vanity Fair|date=March 20, 2018|accessdate=June 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Russell Crowe's jockstrap===\n{{main|Russell Crowe's jockstrap}}\n[[Russell Crowe's jockstrap]] became a notable piece of memorabilia when it was purchased by the ''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver'' and then donated to a Blockbuster Video shop. The jockstrap reappeared in a skit in the final episode of the 2018 season of the show.\n\n===Robocalls===\nThe March 10, 2019, episode dealt primarily with [[robocalls]], and how the problem had mushroomed in recent years since being increasingly deregulated under [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC Chairman]] [[Ajit Pai]]. To prove the point of how easy it was for any company to begin flooding anyone with robocalls, Oliver had one of his IT techs develop a system in which all of the FCC chairs would, at regular intervals on their personal phone numbers, receive a robocall followed immediately by [[bagpipe]] music. Oliver freely admitted his astonishment at just how easy this was to accomplish; the IT technician tasked with setting the system up told him they needed only 15 minutes to complete the project, doing so on a minimal budget. And per the very FCC regulations currently in place, Oliver quickly scrolled a section of fine print on screen at a random time during the segment, in which his office address was randomly embedded, and each FCC chair was required to send him an official letter to that address, notifying him in writing that they wished to have him cease all robocalls forthwith. Oliver was also flabbergasted at discovering that while tens of millions of dollars in fines were levied against companies for violating robocall regulations, only a few thousand dollars have ever been collected, effectively giving the companies free rein to continue robocalling unabated.\n\n===''Guinness World Records''===\nThe main story of the August 11, 2019 episode was [[Turkmenistan]] and its autocratic leader [[Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow]]. The last portion of the segment centered around Berdimuhamedow's obsession with ''[[Guinness World Records]]'', with the Turkmen capital of [[Ashgabat]] being home to the most buildings with white marble cladding, the largest indoor [[Ferris wheel]], and the largest statue of a horse's head, among others. Oliver found that ''Guinness World Records'' received sums of money ranging from US$12,000 to US$500,000 from companies and authoritarian nations to set records for publicity. He ended the show with a 600 square foot [[marble cake]] adorned with a picture of Berdimuhamedow falling from a horse; he had requested a Guinness adjudicator to certify it as the world's largest marble cake, a record previously set by [[Betty Crocker]] in Saudi Arabia in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.generalmills.com/2017/09/a-gift-fresh-from-the-heart-in-saudi-arabia/|title=A gift 'fresh from the heart' in Saudi Arabia|website=General Mills|language=en|date=September 27, 2017|access-date=August 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815165112/https://blog.generalmills.com/2017/09/a-gift-fresh-from-the-heart-in-saudi-arabia/|archive-date=August 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Guinness refused, stating that because their brand was \"aligned with kids and families\", they would not send an adjudicator; Oliver mockingly commented that he didn't \"run a brutal enough dictatorship to meet Guinness World Records' high ethical standards\". Oliver claimed that Guinness offered to certify it after the fact only if he signed an agreement not to criticize their practices on the show, which Oliver dismissed as \"ridiculous\".<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-9QYu8LtH2E |title=Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedov: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver |date=August 11, 2019 |author=HBO |access-date=August 15, 2019 |via=YouTube |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815170404/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-9QYu8LtH2E&gl=US&hl=en |archive-date=August 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5648682/john-oliver-turkmenistan-cake/|title=John Oliver Bakes Very Large Cake to Annoy Turkmenistan|website=Time|language=en|access-date=August 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814150445/https://time.com/5648682/john-oliver-turkmenistan-cake/|archive-date=August 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Guinness called Oliver's allegations \"false and unfair\", claiming that they did not send an adjudicator because they felt the cake was specifically for the purpose of mocking a record holder, stating it was their policy \"not to partake in any activities which may belittle their achievements or subject them to ridicule\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2019/8/guinness-world-records-on-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-586398/|title=Guinness World Records on Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|date=August 12, 2019|website=Guinness World Records|language=en-GB|access-date=August 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813023105/https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2019/8/guinness-world-records-on-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-586398/|archive-date=August 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Narendra Modi===\n\nJohn Oliver extensively satirized Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] in a broadcast which went online on February 23, 2020 calling him a temporary symbol of hate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qVIXUhZ2AWs |title=Last Week Tonight With John Oliver |publisher=Last Week Tonight |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> This was during a visit of US President [[Donald Trump]] to India, and in an [[Namaste Trump|organized rally]] which unexpectedly coincided with [[North East Delhi riots|large-scale violence in Delhi]], the country's capital. In this episode, Oliver likened Modi's [[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP party's]] political beliefs to [[Adolf Hitler|Adolf Hitler's]], by noting that this party's founders, in 1925, had admired Hitler for his methods to ensure \u201cthe purity of the race\u201d \u2013 \u201cwhich is just not a chill thing to admire Hitler - and that, there is one and only one thing that it\u2019s OK to admire Hitler for, and it\u2019s the fact that he killed Hitler.\" <ref name=\"TempHate\">{{cite news|last1=Horton|first1=Adrian|title=John Oliver explains Trump's support of Modi, India's 'temporary symbol of hate'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/feb/24/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-recap-trump-modi-india|accessdate=February 26, 2018|work=Guardian|date=February 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229180408/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/feb/24/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-recap-trump-modi-india|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Oliver also lampooned Trump's choice of words to describe Modi as \"the father of India\", suggesting that there is a [[Mahatma Gandhi|certain Gandhi]] that already holds that exact title.<ref name=\"TempHate\"/> The brunt of his attacks, however, were aimed at Modi's \"increasingly controversial reputation and [[Citizenship Amendment Act protests|widespread protests against his government's citizenship measures]].\"<ref name=\"TempHate\"/>In his attempt to explain the political climate in India under BJP which condones [[Violence against Muslims in India|widespread violence against Muslims]], Oliver mentions how Modi's party-appointed head of [[Uttar Pradesh]], the largest BJP-ruled state of India, said at a recent rally: \u201cIf they kill one Hindu then we will also kill 100 of them (Muslims).\"<ref name=\"TempHate\"/>He further adds that Modi's party has also edited religious pluralism out of history textbooks, and introduced primary school textbooks teaching Indian supremacy, and that the image is \"nauseating\" and that for perhaps the first time in Modi's whole career, his actions are creating a massive and sustained backlash.<ref name=\"TempHate\"/>Oliver concludes this segment by saying that when Trump says Modi is bringing India together, \u201cwith any luck, the thing that unites them may actually end up being their complete disgust over what he is trying to do\u201d, since India, home of the \u201csymbol of love\u201d [[Taj Mahal]], \u201cfrankly deserves much more than this temporary symbol of hate\u201d.<ref name=\"TempHate\"/>\n\n[[Disney+ Hotstar|Hotstar]], an Indian streaming service who holds rights to HBO programming in the country, refused to stream the episode, leading to criticism by local viewers (including Hotstar's apps being [[Review bombing|review bombed]] with 1-star reviews).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/entertainment/news/hotstar-1-star-reviews-modi-john-oliver-last-week-tonight-censorship-backlash-2185798|title=Hotstar Gets 1-Star Reviews for Pro-Government Censorship of John Oliver|website=NDTV Gadgets 360|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> Oliver addressed the censorship in the March 8, 2020 episode, also noting that since the acquisition of Hotstar by [[The Walt Disney Company]] (which occurred as part of its [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|acquisition of 21st Century Fox]]),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/entertainment/news/hotstar-southeast-asia-expansion-disney-bob-iger-star-india-2081496|title=Disney Plans Southeast Asia Expansion for Hotstar|website=NDTV Gadgets 360|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> Hotstar had begun to censor jokes regarding Disney characters from the program, such as his \"factually-accurate\" claim that [[Donald Duck]] had a [[corkscrew penis]].<ref name=\"thr-lwthotstar\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/john-oliver-slams-disney-owned-hotstar-removing-jokes-disney-1283146|title=John Oliver Slams Disney-Owned Streamer for Censoring 'Last Week Tonight' Jokes About Disney|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==International broadcast==\n''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver'' episode clips can be seen internationally on [[YouTube]]. It is broadcast on [[Pay television|premium]] channel [[HBO Canada]] that is [[simulcast]] with HBO in the U.S.; around the same time it is shown on the international [[HBO (international)|HBO]] channels. It airs in Australia on [[The Comedy Channel]] hours after the U.S. airing<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2014/04/airdate-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver.html|title=Airdate: Last Week Tonight|last=Knox|first=David|date=April 11, 2014|accessdate=June 2, 2014|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602200503/http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2014/04/airdate-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver.html|archive-date=June 2, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> and airs in New Zealand on [[SoHo (TV channel)|SoHo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dannews.co.nz/2015/01/28/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-coming-to-soho/|title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver coming to SoHo|date=January 28, 2015|publisher=Dan News|accessdate=August 13, 2015|archivedate=August 13, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150813114138/http://dannews.co.nz/2015/01/28/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-coming-to-soho/}}</ref> In the United Kingdom and Ireland, it is broadcast on Mondays on [[Sky Comedy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sky.com/watch/title/series/b7a772c4-8fdb-4e28-be16-66141b9b34d6/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver |title=Last Week Tonight With John Oliver |publisher=Sky |accessdate=February 20, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> In Belgium, it is broadcast on Thursdays by the [[Telenet (Belgium)|Telenet]] cable-only channel [[Prime (Flanders)|PRIME Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prime.be/series/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-2|title=Last Week Tonight With John Oliver S2|publisher=Telenet/PRIME|accessdate=February 21, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150221095413/http://www.prime.be/series/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-2|archivedate=February 21, 2015}}</ref> It airs in South Africa on [[M-Net]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel24.co.za/TV/News/M-Net-adds-exciting-new-late-night-talk-show-to-its-schedule-20140430|publisher=channel24.co.za|title=M-Net adds exciting new late night talk show to its schedule|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=September 9, 2015|last=Ferreira|first=Thinus|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930202818/http://www.channel24.co.za/TV/News/M-Net-adds-exciting-new-late-night-talk-show-to-its-schedule-20140430|archive-date=September 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and in Portugal on [[RTP3]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ferreira|first1=David|trans-title=|title=Conhe\u00e7a a programa\u00e7\u00e3o da nova RTP3 (com v\u00eddeo)|url=http://www.atelevisao.com/cabo/conheca-a-programacao-da-nova-rtp3/|language=Portuguese|accessdate=September 29, 2015|publisher=A Televis\u00e3o|date=September 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930130307/http://www.atelevisao.com/cabo/conheca-a-programacao-da-nova-rtp3/|archive-date=September 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In India, the show is streamed on Hotstar Premium.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.hotstar.com/tv/last-week-tonight/s-585 | title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver TV Series Full Episodes, Watch Last Week Tonight with John Oliver TV Show Online | access-date=November 18, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118164539/https://www.hotstar.com/tv/last-week-tonight/s-585 | archive-date=November 18, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Comedy|Television}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.hbo.com/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=3530232|title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n* {{tv.com show|last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver|Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n* {{Facebook|LastWeekTonight}}\n* {{YouTube|u=LastWeekTonight|Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{Last Week Tonight}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= [[List of awards and nominations received by Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|Awards for ''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver'']]\n|list=\n{{Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Talk Show}}\n{{Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Variety Talk Series}}\n{{TCA Award for Outstanding Achievement in News and Information}}\n{{Writers Guild of America Award for Television: Comedy-Variety Talk Series}}\n}}\n{{Late night television in the United States}}\n{{HBONetwork Shows}}\n\n[[Category:Last Week Tonight with John Oliver| ]]\n[[Category:2014 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s American late-night television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American political comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American satirical television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American television talk shows]]\n[[Category:2020s American late-night television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American political comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American satirical television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American television talk shows]]\n[[Category:American news parodies]]\n[[Category:American television spin-offs]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:HBO original programming]]\n[[Category:Political satirical television series]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award-winning television series]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Television censorship in China]]\n[[Category:Censored television series]]\n[[Category:Works banned in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American late-night talk show}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = Last Week Tonight {{nowrap|with John Oliver}}\n| show_name_2        = Last Week Tonight\n| image              = Last Week Tonight.svg\n| image_alt          = Black and red text on a white background reading \"Last Week Tonight with John Oliver\".\n| caption            =\n| genre              = {{plainlist|\n* [[Comedy]]\n* [[News satire]]\n* [[Political satire]]\n* [[Talk show]]\n}}\n| creator            = [[John Oliver]]\n| writer             = <!-- Per infobox template rules, writer(s) should not be included if series has 5+ writers -->\n| director           = {{plainlist|\n* Joe Perota\n* Christopher Werner\n* Jim Hoskinson\n* Paul Pennolino\n* Bruce Leddy\n}}\n| presenter          = John Oliver\n| starring           =\n| narrated           = [[David Kaye (voice actor)|David Kaye]]\n| opentheme          = \"Go\" by [[Valley Lodge (band)|Valley Lodge]]<ref>{{cite tweet|user=LastWeekTonight|number=476822910494310400|date=June 11, 2014|title=By the way, our theme song \"Go\" is performed by the excellent rock band @ValleyLodge!}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dave Hill|title=Valley Lodge's \"Go\" Is the Theme Song for \"Last Week Tonight with John Oliver\" on HBO|url=http://davehillonline.com/blog/2014/04/valley-lodges-go-is-the-theme-song-for-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-on-hbo/|publisher=DaveHillOnline.com|date=April 29, 2014|accessdate=April 2, 2016|author-link=Dave Hill (comedian)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401105027/http://davehillonline.com/blog/2014/04/valley-lodges-go-is-the-theme-song-for-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-on-hbo/|archive-date=April 1, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| country            = United States\n| language           = English\n| num_seasons        = 7\n| num_episodes       = 187\n| list_episodes      = List of Last Week Tonight with John Oliver episodes\n| executive_producer = {{plainlist|\n* John Oliver\n* [[Tim Carvell]]\n* Liz Stanton\n* James Taylor\n* [[Jon Thoday]]\n}}\n| location           = [[CBS Broadcast Center]]<br />New York, New York\n| runtime            = 30\u201340 minutes<ref>{{cite tweet|user=LastWeekTonight|number=927269314025140225|date=November 5, 2017|title=You got an extra hour of sleep this morning, so you should be well-rested for tonight's 40-minute episode that starts at 11:15.}}</ref>\n| company            = {{plainlist|\n* Avalon Television\n* Partially Important Productions\n}}\n| distributor        = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| network            = [[HBO]]\n| picture_format     = [[1080i]] ([[16:9]] [[HDTV]])\n| audio_format       = [[Dolby Surround]]\n| first_aired        = {{Start date|2014|4|27}}\n| last_aired         = present\n| website            = http://www.hbo.com/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver\n}}\n'''''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver''''' (often abridged as '''''Last Week Tonight''''') is an American [[late-night talk show|late-night talk]] and [[news satire]] television program hosted by comedian [[John Oliver]].<ref name=\"order\">{{cite news |last=Patten |first=Dominic |date=February 12, 2014 |title=HBO Sets Name & Date For John Oliver Debut |url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/02/hbo-sets-name-date-for-john-oliver-debut/ |url-status=live |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140214111313/http://www.deadline.com/2014/02/hbo-sets-name-date-for-john-oliver-debut/ |archivedate=February 14, 2014 |accessdate=February 12, 2014}}</ref> The half-hour-long show premiered on Sunday, April 27, 2014, on [[HBO]].<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Connell|first=Michael|title=John Oliver's HBO Series Gets Name, April Premiere|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/john-olivers-hbo-series-gets-679764|accessdate=March 10, 2014|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=February 12, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140324102357/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/john-olivers-hbo-series-gets-679764|archive-date=March 24, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Last Week Tonight'' shares some similarities with [[Comedy Central]]'s ''[[The Daily Show]]'' (where Oliver was previously [[List of The Daily Show correspondents|featured as a correspondent]] and fill-in host), as it takes a satirical look at news, politics and current events, but on a weekly basis.<ref name=\"order\"/>\n\nOliver has stated that he has \"full [[artistic freedom|creative freedom]], including free rein to [[Criticisms of corporations|criticize corporations]]\". His initial contract with HBO was for two years with an option for extension.<ref name=\"freedom\">{{cite news|last=Guthrie|first=Marisa|title=John Oliver on the Luxurious 'Freedom' of HBO, His Complicated Relationship With NYC|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-luxurious-freedom-hbo-696165|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=April 19, 2014|date=April 16, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418232827/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-luxurious-freedom-hbo-696165|archive-date=April 18, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2017, HBO announced that the show had been renewed for three additional seasons of 30 episodes each, keeping the show on the air through 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/12/arts/television/john-oliver-hbo-contract.html |title=John Oliver Extends HBO Contract Through 2020 |last=Koblin |first=John |work=The New York Times |date=September 12, 2017 |accessdate=September 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912182739/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/12/arts/television/john-oliver-hbo-contract.html |archive-date=September 12, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The show's seventh season, the last season promised by the 2017 renewal announcement, premiered on February 16, 2020.<ref name=\"S6\">{{cite news |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title='Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' Gets Season 6 Premiere Date On HBO |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-season-6-premiere-date-hbo-1202528068/ |accessdate=January 2, 2019 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=January 2, 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102235844/https://deadline.com/2019/01/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-season-6-premiere-date-hbo-1202528068/ |archive-date=January 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nOliver described his preparations for the show to an interviewer for ''[[The Atlantic#The Wire|The Wire]]'': \"... I basically have to watch everything. The only thing I kind of watch for pleasure is [[Fareed Zakaria GPS|Fareed Zakaria's show]] on Sundays ... That and ''[[60 Minutes]]'' I watch for pleasure, or maybe ''[[Frontline (American TV program)|Frontline]]'' ... I have a TV on in my office all the time and I'll generally flick around on that from [[CNN]], [[Fox News|Fox]], [[MSNBC]], [[Bloomberg Television|Bloomberg]], [[CNBC]], [[Al Jazeera America|Al Jazeera]] ... I'm watching with a certain thing in mind and that is how to see a story told badly.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thewire.com/entertainment/2014/05/john-oliver-what-i-read/361405/ |author= Zuckerman, Esther |date= May 1, 2014 |title= John Oliver: What I Read |work= The Wire |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140504083727/http://www.thewire.com/entertainment/2014/05/john-oliver-what-i-read/361405/ |archive-date= May 4, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nHe said to another interviewer that he is concerned about dealing with [[news values|old news]]:\n\n<blockquote>If something happens on a Monday, realistically all the meat is going to be picked off that bone by the time it gets to us&nbsp;\u2014 there's probably barely a point in doing it ... I think we'll be attracted to some extent by stories that are off the grid ... Our show may end up skewing more international in terms of stories.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://unfetteredequality.com/2014/08/13/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-changing-journalism-for-the-better |title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver: Changing journalism for the better |last=Hoxie |first=Angie |date=August 13, 2014 |accessdate=February 18, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218055110/http://unfetteredequality.com/2014/08/13/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-changing-journalism-for-the-better/ |archive-date=February 18, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n[[Tim Carvell]], executive producer of ''Last Week Tonight'', explained in an interview how the cast and crew deal with a half hour of Oliver speaking without any [[Television advertisement|commercial]] breaks.<ref name=\"usnews\">{{cite web |url= https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/04/22/5-things-to-know-about-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver |author= Sneed, Tierney |date= April 22, 2014 |title= Why ''Last Week Tonight'' Will Not Just Be ''The Daily Show'' on Sundays |work= [[U.S. News & World Report]] |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140504081746/http://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/04/22/5-things-to-know-about-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver |archive-date= May 4, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Structural considerations are leading to changes in the content in the show that will inherently make it different from ''The Daily Show'' ... We realized early on, you don't necessarily want to hear anybody talk to you for a half an hour straight&nbsp;\u2013 even John, who is very charming&nbsp;\u2013 so we are constructing these little, produced comedy elements that will serve the function of commercial breaks throughout the show, which will let us get out of the studio, get us away from John's voice and break the show up a bit.}}\n\nCarvell also revealed that HBO gave them freedom in choosing guests for the show, advising them not to feel obligated to feature celebrities.<ref name=\"usnews\" /> When asked by an interviewer about \"[[correspondent]]s\" such as those featured on ''The Daily Show'', Oliver replied, \"we're not going to be a parody news show, so no people pretending to be journalists.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/blogs/tv-news/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-interview-two-days-later-222215388.html|last=Furlong|first=Maggie|title='Last Week Tonight,' Two Days Later: John Oliver on His First Show, Dream Guests, and Old White Racists|website=Yahoo!|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=May 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619185957/https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/blogs/tv-news/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-interview-two-days-later-222215388.html|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the fifth episode of season 7, Oliver stated that the studio and the show's offices were shut down after employees tested positive for [[COVID-19]] and that the show would go on temporary hiatus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/films-tv-delayed-coronavirus-canceled-1203532033/|title=All the Shows and Movies Shut Down or Delayed Because of Coronavirus|publisher=Variety|date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The show returned on March&nbsp;29, filmed from Oliver's home, to cover the coronavirus and the response to it.<ref>https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/john-oliver-coronavirus-last-week-tonight-march-29.html</ref>\n\n==Format==\n{{more citations needed section|date=August 2015}}\nThe format is similar to ''[[The Daily Show]]'', with Oliver sitting at a desk in front of a backdrop of a skyline containing buildings from around the world, often relating to the current topic. Unlike ''The Daily Show'', Oliver tends to explore one concept in depth but retains the appearance of commercial breaks to intercut larger topics with smaller segments that are not necessarily related to the topic at hand. The show is taped in front of a [[studio audience]], and HBO offers a limited number of free tickets to attend each week's ''Last Week Tonight'' taping. As of March 15, 2020 the show is being filmed with no live audience at an unspecified studio location due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].\n\nThe show's theme starts off every episode containing images relating to it or the world at large with satirical captions written in [[dog Latin]]. Each episode covers a small handful of shorter segments, and then one main segment. While the short segments almost always relate to recent news, the episode's main segment usually covers in length and detail a political issue, even if that issue did not have news media attention during the preceding week. On occasion, the short segments are omitted and the main segment takes up the entirety of the episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2016/2/14/10989154/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-season-3|last=Framke|first=Caroline|title=John Oliver on making Last Week Tonight and why he won't focus on the 2016 election|website=Vox|date=February 14, 2016|accessdate=March 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320052802/http://www.vox.com/2016/2/14/10989154/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-season-3|archive-date=March 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOliver injects humor into his presentation, including satirical [[analogies]], and allusions to popular culture and celebrities. The show includes a panel in the upper-left corner that frequently displays a photo or graphic for that accompanies subject at hand, which aids in the humor. A full-screen graphic will show and play a video clip (such as excerpts from news show or documentaries) when Oliver is citing it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2014/07/why-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-is-the-next-generation-of-late-night-23696/|title=Why 'Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' is The Next Generation of Late Night|last=Miller|first=Liz Shannon|website=IndieWire|language=en|date=July 29, 2014|accessdate=September 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904015651/http://www.indiewire.com/2014/07/why-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-is-the-next-generation-of-late-night-23696/|archive-date=September 4, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He often coins [[hashtag|hashtags]] related to his segment for use in [[social media]], some of which go [[Viral phenomenon|viral]].<ref name=Emertainment>{{cite web|url=http://emertainmentmonthly.com/index.php/how-john-oliver-gets-social-media-right-while-the-rest-of-traditional-media-fails/|last=Solomon|first=Emily|title=How John Oliver Gets Social Media Right While the Rest of Traditional Media Fails|work=Emertainment Monthly|date=April 12, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404222905/http://emertainmentmonthly.com/index.php/how-john-oliver-gets-social-media-right-while-the-rest-of-traditional-media-fails/|archive-date=April 4, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA recurring element of the show is Oliver's use of mascots. The mascots used in the show include Jeff the Diseased Lung in a Cowboy Hat, Hoots the NSA Owl, Taryn the Tinder Chicken, and the Last Week Tonight puppets.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.ranker.com/list/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-mascots/ranker-tv | title=All the Mascot Costumes from Last Week Tonight, Ranked}}</ref> Oliver told Vulture in February 2019, \"I mean, the truth of the mascots is that we have a gigantic room filled with spectacular mascot costumes now. [Executive producer] Tim Carvell and I \u2014 I think we\u2019ve always seen the show as our attempt to make The Muppet Show and failing to do so. But occasionally, just occasionally, you get the kind of Muppet Show adoration in the ludicrous mascots.\"<ref>https://www.vulture.com/2019/02/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-hbo-interview-mascots.html</ref>\n\nThe typical structure of the show is to open with a recap of a few of the week's news stories, segue into a video compilation, and then move on to Oliver's main segment. Some of the episodes will follow up the main segment with another video compilation or news story. Oliver's speech is broken up with video compilations of recent news clips, or recurring segments, into which Oliver segues with the slogan, \"And now, this.\" Oliver has also ended some segments with mock trailers for fictional TV shows or commercials that satirize the subject of his speech.\n\n=== Celebrity guests===\nThe show frequently features one or more celebrity guests in its segments to help Oliver better get his point on the week's topic across. Guests have featured in many different capacities including giving monologues directly to camera, being interviewed by Oliver, playing musical numbers, participating in comedic skits with or without Oliver, or starring in fictitious parody [[Public service announcement|PSAs]]. On the show, guests are sometimes seen in the Last Week Tonight studio itself doing their part during the show's main taping, while at other times they are seen in video clips that were pre-recorded at a different location and later included in the show. Oliver often interviews personalities who were directly involved in or impacted by the issues being discussed in the show to get their first-hand experiences and viewpoints on the issue. Some of the famous personalities Oliver has interviewed include [[Edward Snowden]], the [[14th Dalai Lama|14th]] [[Dalai Lama]], [[Anita Hill|Professor Anita Hill]] and [[Monica Lewinsky]].\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Last Week Tonight with John Oliver episodes}}\n{{:List of Last Week Tonight with John Oliver episodes}}\n\n==YouTube channel==\n''Last Week Tonight'' has a [[YouTube]] channel where videos are intermittently (depending on series) added after a show has aired.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/user/LastWeekTonight |title=Last Week Tonight channel |access-date=March 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313183030/https://www.youtube.com/user/LastWeekTonight |archive-date=March 13, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Most of the videos are of the main segment from each episode. Some extended clips are also available on the show's YouTube channel, as are \"Web Exclusives\" that are produced solely for the channel, such as a July 2016 video in which Oliver responded to negative comments left on the channel itself.<ref name=Emertainment/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Framke |first1=Caroline |title=John Oliver ends 2016 by confronting Last Week Tonight's role in the liberal echo chamber |url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2016/11/20/13678748/john-oliver-election-2016 |website=Vox |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |date=November 20, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163235/https://www.vox.com/culture/2016/11/20/13678748/john-oliver-election-2016 |archive-date=June 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rhodan |first1=Maya |title=Watch John Oliver Read Mean 'Fan Mail' from YouTube |url=http://time.com/4401025/watch-john-oliver-read-mean-fan-mail-from-youtube/ |website=Time |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |date=July 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501084644/http://time.com/4401025/watch-john-oliver-read-mean-fan-mail-from-youtube/ |archive-date=May 1, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe show's production has also created content specifically for fan use. For the March 19, 2017, episode, which reported on Bolivia's growing coalition of workers clad in zebra suits to educate civilians about traffic laws, the show's production recorded 23 minutes of a person in a zebra costume dancing and gesticulating before a green screen so that viewers could edit it into other videos for humorous effect.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bradley |first1=Laura |title=John Oliver Slams Trump's Budget, Lightens Mood with Dancing Zebras |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/03/john-oliver-donald-trump-budget-proposal-dancing-zebras |website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |date=March 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608152244/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/03/john-oliver-donald-trump-budget-proposal-dancing-zebras |archive-date=June 8, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> A similar video called \"Real Animals, Fake Paws\" for use in reenacting [[U.S. Supreme Court]] cases was released after the October 19, 2014, episode where dogs were used instead of justices to make listening to oral court cases more amusing to the general public and to increase interest in the subject.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=tug71xZL7yc|title=Real Animals, Fake Paws Footage: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO)|last=LastWeekTonight|date=October 19, 2014|publisher=|via=YouTube|access-date=June 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620155905/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tug71xZL7yc|archive-date=June 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy April 2015, the channel had attained over a million subscribers.<ref name=Emertainment/> That number had risen to 3.6 million by July 2016,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Durkin |first1=J.D. |title=Oliver Responds to Harsh YouTube Comments in Newest Last Week Tonight Segment |url=https://www.mediaite.com/online/oliver-responds-to-harsh-youtube-comments-in-newest-last-week-tonight-segment/ |website=Mediaite |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |date=July 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163915/https://www.mediaite.com/online/oliver-responds-to-harsh-youtube-comments-in-newest-last-week-tonight-segment/ |archive-date=June 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and over 5 million by May 2017. {{As of|2020|April|df=}}, the channel had over 7.8 million subscribers and more than 2.4 billion views.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/user/LastWeekTonight/about \"Last Week Tonight\" videos] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170304225649/https://www.youtube.com/user/LastWeekTonight/about |date=March 4, 2017 }}. YouTube. Retrieved April 3, 2017.</ref>\n\n== Social media ==\n''Last Week Tonight'' has a Facebook page with over 2.6 million likes, a Twitter account with over 2.9 million followers, and an Instagram account with more than 450,000 followers {{As of|2019|July|lc=y|df=}}.\n\nOliver often makes use of joke [[hashtags]] to facilitate the [[viral spread]] of his videos on [[Twitter]] and [[Facebook]], as with the hashtag #NotMyChristian, which he used in 2014 to complain about the casting of actor [[Jamie Dornan]] in the feature film adaptation of ''[[Fifty Shades of Grey (film)|Fifty Shades of Grey]]''. The hashtag became a recurring punchline on the show, mentioned in both serious stories and casual segues.<ref name=\"Emertainment\" />\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:John Oliver 2014.jpg|thumb|250x250px|John Oliver, host of ''Last Week Tonight'']]\nOliver's debut show garnered 1.11 million viewers. The number of viewers online, through websites such as YouTube showing extended clips of different segments, have steadily climbed into multiple millions. The show's YouTube channel also features Web Exclusives which are occasionally posted when the main show is taking a week off. Across the TV airings, [[Digital video recorder|DVR]], [[Video on demand|on-demand]] and [[HBO Go]], ''Last Week Tonight'' averaged 4.1 million weekly viewers in its first season.<ref>{{cite news |last= O'Connell |first= Michael |title= John Oliver's Talk Show Ratings Edging Out HBO Colleague Bill Maher |work= The Hollywood Reporter |date= September 9, 2014 |url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-olivers-talk-show-ratings-735187 |accessdate= December 23, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141217013001/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-olivers-talk-show-ratings-735187 |archive-date= December 17, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n''Last Week Tonight'' has received widespread critical acclaim. Matthew Jacobs of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' named Oliver's program as 2014's best television show, writing \"the year's most surprising contribution to television is a show that bucked conventional formats, left us buzzing and paved the way for a burgeoning dynasty. ''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver'' is 2014's crowning achievement.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= Jacobs |first= Matthew |title= Why 'Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' Was 2014's Best Show |work= The Huffington Post |date= December 8, 2014 |url= https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/08/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-best-show-2014_n_6284074.html |accessdate= December 9, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141209032042/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/08/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-best-show-2014_n_6284074.html |archive-date= December 9, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n[[Hank Stuever]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' compared Oliver's program with ''The Daily Show'' several times in his review of Oliver's debut:\n\n<blockquote>Another scathing, stick-it-to-'em critique of American [[mass media]] and politics shellacked in satire and delivered by a funny if almost off-puttingly incredulous man with a British accent ... Exactly like ''The Daily Show'', the goal is to make elected and appointed officials, as well as just about any corporate enterprise, look foolish and inept while slyly culling together television news clips that make the media look equally inept at covering such evident truths.<ref>{{cite news |last= Stuever |first= Hank |title= John Oliver's 'Last Week Tonight' on HBO sticks to a familiar formula |work= The Washington Post |date= April 28, 2014 |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/style/wp/2014/04/28/john-olivers-last-week-tonight-on-hbo-sticks-to-a-familiar-formula/ |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150508221812/http://www.washingtonpost.com/news/style/wp/2014/04/28/john-olivers-last-week-tonight-on-hbo-sticks-to-a-familiar-formula/ |archive-date= May 8, 2015 |url-status= live }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n[[James Poniewozik]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' similarly compared ''Last Week'' with ''The Daily Show'', but also wrote that the \"full half-hour gives Oliver the room to do more,\" and praised Oliver's \"sharper tone and his globalist, English-outsider perspective,\" as well as his \"genuine passion over his subjects.\" Poniewozik wrote that Oliver's debut was \"a funny, confident start.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://time.com/79133/john-oliver-review-last-week/ |author= Poniewozik, James |date= April 28, 2014 |title= REVIEW: Last Week Tonight With John Oliver |work= Time |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140503214147/http://time.com/79133/john-oliver-review-last-week/ |archive-date= May 3, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' review began by ringing the same changes: \"The fear with ''Last Week Tonight'' is that it's ''The Daily Show'' except once a week&nbsp;\u2014 a staggered timeline that would rob the basic news-punning format of its intrinsic topical punch ... The first episode of his HBO series didn't stray far from the [[Jon Stewart|[Jon] Stewart]] mothership, stylistically ...\" However, the reviewer, Darren Franich, liked that Oliver has \"a half-hour of television that is simultaneously tighter and more ambitious, that the extra production time leads to sharper gags but also the ability to present more context\" and thought that the debut had \"plenty of funny throwaway lines.\" Franich appreciated Oliver's coverage of [[2014 Indian general election|the 2014 Indian election]], which the American press was largely ignoring,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/alyssaayres/2014/05/01/thanks-john-oliver-why-india-isnt-a-big-focus-for-u-s-television/ |last= Ayres |first= Alyssa |date= May 1, 2014 |title= Thanks, John Oliver! Why India Isn't a Big Focus for U.S. Television |work= [[Forbes]] |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140504055011/http://www.forbes.com/sites/alyssaayres/2014/05/01/thanks-john-oliver-why-india-isnt-a-big-focus-for-u-s-television/ |archive-date= May 4, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref> and, like Poniewozik, praised Oliver's \"passion.\" Franich concluded that ''Last Week Tonight'' \"suggested the sharpest possible version of its inspiration\" and that it \"should feel like an experiment\" but \"felt almost fully formed.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/04/28/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-review/ |last= Franich |first= Darren |date= April 28, 2014 |title= 'Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' review: The Weekly Show |work= Entertainment Weekly |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140503045808/http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/04/28/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-review/ |archive-date= May 3, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nDavid Haglund of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' was ambivalent, writing that the show is \"obviously a work in progress\" and that one segment \"felt like misplaced overkill,\" but also that it is \"good use of a weekly show, and it was funny to boot.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/television/2014/04/the_premiere_of_john_oliver_s_hbo_show_last_week_tonight_reviewed.html |last= Haglund |first= David |date= April 2014 |title= Last Week Tonight: Like The Daily Show, With Unbleeped Swears! |work= Slate |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140504203605/http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/television/2014/04/the_premiere_of_john_oliver_s_hbo_show_last_week_tonight_reviewed.html |archive-date= May 4, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref> [[Gawker]]'s Jordan Sargent claimed ''Last Week Tonight'' was \"the new ''Daily Show'',\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://defamer.gawker.com/john-olivers-last-week-tonight-is-the-new-daily-show-1572116205/all |author=Sargent, Jordan |date=May 6, 2014 |title=John Oliver's Last Week Tonight is the New Daily Show |publisher=Gawker |accessdate=May 6, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507030451/http://defamer.gawker.com/john-olivers-last-week-tonight-is-the-new-daily-show-1572116205/all |archivedate=May 7, 2014 }}</ref> while simultaneously criticizing the ''Daily Show'' for abandoning those \"who have moved on from caring about [[Fox News|Fox [News]]] and [[Republican Party of the United States|Republicans]].\"\n\nA number of commentators from mainstream media outlets, including ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/17/business/media/john-olivers-complicated-fun-connects-for-hbo.html|title=John Oliver's Complicated Fun Connects for HBO|date=November 16, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|last=Carr|first=David|newspaper=The New York Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150501135440/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/17/business/media/john-olivers-complicated-fun-connects-for-hbo.html|archive-date=May 1, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Huffington Post'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/26/john-oliver-journalism_n_5888184.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150814125641/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/26/john-oliver-journalism_n_5888184.html |archivedate=August 14, 2015|title=John Oliver Is Doing Some Really Good Investigative Journalism|date=September 26, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|last=Bauder|first=David|work=The Huffington Post}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3589285/unfortunately-john-oliver-you-are-a-journalist/|title=Unfortunately, John Oliver, You Are a Journalist|last=Poniewozik|first=James|date=November 17, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|work=Time|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725193947/http://time.com/3589285/unfortunately-john-oliver-you-are-a-journalist/|archive-date=July 25, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Associated Press]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/with-journalism-in-quiver-john-oliver-transcends-his-schtick-1.1760408|title=With journalism in quiver, John Oliver transcends his schtick|date=September 25, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|last=Bauder|first=David|agency=Associated Press|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614075700/http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/with-journalism-in-quiver-john-oliver-transcends-his-schtick-1.1760408|archive-date=June 14, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> have described Oliver's style of reporting as journalism or even investigative journalism. Oliver himself disagrees, stating that \"it's not journalism, it's comedy\u2014it's comedy first, and it's comedy second.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/last-week-tonight-does-real-journalism-no-matter-what-john-oliver-says|title='Last Week Tonight' Does Real Journalism, No Matter What John Oliver Says|last=Suebsaeng|first=Asawin|newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=September 29, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602195007/http://www.thedailybeast.com/last-week-tonight-does-real-journalism-no-matter-what-john-oliver-says|archive-date=June 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n{{:List of awards and nominations received by Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n\n==Reaction and influence==\nA [[Net Neutrality (Last Week Tonight)#\"Net Neutrality\"|June 2014 segment]] about [[net neutrality in the United States]] was thought to spur over 45,000 comments on the [[Federal Communications Commission]]'s electronic filing page about a net neutrality proposal that, if implemented, would have priority \"lanes\" for certain internet traffic. The FCC also received an extra 300,000 comments in an email inbox designated specifically for the proposal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2014/06/03/318458496/john-oliver-helps-rally-45-000-net-neutrality-comments-to-fcc|title=John Oliver Helps Rally 45,000 Net Neutrality Comments To FCC|last=Hu|first=Elise|work=NPR|date=June 3, 2014|accessdate=September 12, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150624041323/http://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2014/06/03/318458496/john-oliver-helps-rally-45-000-net-neutrality-comments-to-fcc|archive-date=June 24, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It was thought that Oliver's segment had a major role in the FCC's ultimate reversal of stance on that proposal,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Society/2015/0226/Net-neutrality-s-stunning-reversal-of-fortune-Is-it-John-Oliver-s-doing|title=Net neutrality's stunning reversal of fortune: Is it John Oliver's doing?|last=Bruinius|first=Harry|date=February 26, 2015|work=Christian Science Monitor|accessdate=September 15, 2017|issn=0882-7729|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922102025/https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Society/2015/0226/Net-neutrality-s-stunning-reversal-of-fortune-Is-it-John-Oliver-s-doing|archive-date=September 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> with the FCC instead implementing net-neutrality rules that prohibited priority \"lanes\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/03/12/technology/net-neutrality-rules-explained.html|title=What the Net Neutrality Rules Say|last=Sommer|first=Jeff|date=March 12, 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 13, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150313080607/http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/03/12/technology/net-neutrality-rules-explained.html|archive-date=March 13, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> A sequel in 2017 inspired over 150,000 comments on a subsequent proposal to scrap the new net neutrality rules.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/talkingtech/2017/05/09/john-oliver-may-have-helped-spur-150000-comments-fcc-net-neutrality/101480100/|title=John Oliver may have helped spur 150,000 comments to FCC on Net neutrality|last=Snider|first=Mike|date=May 10, 2017|work=USA TODAY|access-date=September 22, 2017|last2=Weise|first2=Elizabeth|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922101510/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/talkingtech/2017/05/09/john-oliver-may-have-helped-spur-150000-comments-fcc-net-neutrality/101480100/|archive-date=September 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA segment on the then [[Prime Minister of Australia]] [[Tony Abbott]] received widespread attention in Australia across the mainstream media and was trending on [[social media]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/tony-abbott-lambasted-on-us-tv-show-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver/news-story/cb0df94da804403072b59016dadf12b8|last= Bond|first= Nick|date= June 3, 2014|title= Tony Abbott lambasted on US TV show Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|publisher= [[News Corp Australia]]|accessdate= June 5, 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170922002508/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/tony-abbott-lambasted-on-us-tv-show-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver/news-story/cb0df94da804403072b59016dadf12b8|archive-date= September 22, 2017|url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/554572/20140603/tony-abbot-last-week-tonight-john-oliver.htm#.U4-z_CgkRTY |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140603190359/http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/554572/20140603/tony-abbot-last-week-tonight-john-oliver.htm#.U4-z_CgkRTY |archivedate= June 3, 2014 |author= Ma Evelyn Castino Quilas |date= June 3, 2014 |title= Tony Abbott Mocked in U.S. News Program, Aussies Cringe on Twitter |work= International Business Times |accessdate= June 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/tony-abbott-roasted-by-john-oliver-on-hbo-show-last-week-tonight-20140602-zrvl1.html |author= Nick Toscano |date= June 2, 2014 |title= Tony Abbott roasted by John Oliver on HBO show Last Week Tonight |work= [[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |accessdate= June 5, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180227040314/https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/tony-abbott-roasted-by-john-oliver-on-hbo-show-last-week-tonight-20140602-zrvl1.html |archive-date= February 27, 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to a document obtained by ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'', the military government of [[Thailand]] listed Oliver as \"[[L\u00e8se majest\u00e9 in Thailand|undermining the royal institution]]\" for calling Crown Prince [[Vajiralongkorn]] a \"buffoon\" and an \"idiot.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.vice.com/article/thailands-military-government-thinks-john-oliver-is-a-threat-to-its-monarchy|title=Thailand's Military Government Thinks John Oliver Is a Threat to Its Monarchy|last=Marshall|first=Andrew|publisher=Vice|date=July 24, 2014|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163841/https://news.vice.com/article/thailands-military-government-thinks-john-oliver-is-a-threat-to-its-monarchy|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jul/29/thai-junta-comedian-john-oliver-royal-jibes|last=Hodal|first=Kate|title=Thai junta unamused by comedian John Oliver's royal jibes|work=The Guardian|date=July 29, 2014|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163837/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jul/29/thai-junta-comedian-john-oliver-royal-jibes|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe show also made international headlines following Oliver's interview with [[Edward Snowden]], which included a graphic, in-depth conversation about the amount of power the [[United States government]] has at its disposal in terms of intelligence, both domestic and foreign. Oliver also confronted Snowden about the lack of knowledge of the American people about his work and why they may be hesitant to analyze it for themselves rather than accept preconceived notions of him being a [[whistleblower]]. Notably, he tried to help Snowden in creating public awareness for the fundamentality of the surveillance problem in putting forward the question \"Can they see my dick?\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/06/media/edward-snowden-john-oliver-interview/index.html|title=John Oliver lands Edward Snowden interview from Russia|publisher=CNNMoney|date=April 6, 2015|first=Brian|last=Stelter|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618211744/http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/06/media/edward-snowden-john-oliver-interview/index.html|archive-date=June 18, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/apr/06/edward-snowden-john-oliver-last-week-tonight-nsa-leaked-documents|title=John Oliver presses Edward Snowden on whether he read all leaked NSA material|last=Yuhas|first=Alan|work=The Guardian|date=April 6, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163305/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/apr/06/edward-snowden-john-oliver-last-week-tonight-nsa-leaked-documents|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn a segment about [[public defender]]s and how some offices are extremely underfunded, the New Orleans Public Defense office's crowdfunding efforts to improve their conditions were featured. In the days following the episode's broadcast, thousands of dollars were donated to the office by the show's fans, helping them raise their goal four days after the show aired.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://opdla.causevox.com/ |title=Orleans Public Defenders crowd-funding |publisher=causevox.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150917061217/http://opdla.causevox.com/ |archive-date=September 17, 2015 |url-status=dead |access-date=September 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFor a segment in the October 18, 2015, broadcast, Oliver put on a comically grand demonstration with Canadian actor [[Mike Myers]] to urge Canadian voters to vote against [[Stephen Harper]] in the next day's [[2015 Canadian federal election|Canadian federal election]]. As part of this gesture, Oliver displayed $5000 in cash in anticipation of being charged for the crime of being a foreigner attempting to induce Canadian citizens to change their vote as per section 331 of the [[Canada Elections Act]]. However, the agency responsible for overseeing federal elections in Canada, [[Elections Canada]], explained the next day that prosecution of Oliver will not be necessary since inducement in the act is defined as offering something material to voters. Per Elections Canada, Oliver has not tried to influence Canadian electorate, since the money shown was only for the anticipated fine, but merely expressed his opinion as a bystander, which is lawful.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Edwards|first1=Peter|title=Why John Oliver won't go to jail for flouting Canadian election law|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/federal-election/2015/10/19/john-oliver-flouts-canadian-election-law-to-blast-harper.html|accessdate=November 17, 2015|work=Toronto Star|date=October 19, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118044508/http://www.thestar.com/news/federal-election/2015/10/19/john-oliver-flouts-canadian-election-law-to-blast-harper.html|archive-date=November 18, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the June 17, 2018 episode, Oliver spoke at length about [[Xi Jinping]], [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]], in part criticizing his [[Censorship in China|censorship]] of Chinese media, his dictatorship<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cfr.org/backgrounder/media-censorship-china|title=Media Censorship in China|work=Council on Foreign Relations|access-date=June 23, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330080256/https://www.cfr.org/backgrounder/media-censorship-china|archive-date=March 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and consolidation of power.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/2135962/why-now-rationale-behind-xi-jinpings-power-consolidation|title=Why now? The rationale behind Xi Jinping's power consolidation|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=June 23, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624040136/http://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/2135962/why-now-rationale-behind-xi-jinpings-power-consolidation|archive-date=June 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Both \"John Oliver\" and \"Last Week Tonight\" were blocked from Chinese social media platform [[Sina Weibo]] immediately following the segment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-44557528|title=Chinese social media censors John Oliver|date=June 21, 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=June 23, 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622134355/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-44557528|archive-date=June 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[HBO]] website and content from the network were also blocked,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/2152323/china-blocks-hbo-after-john-oliver-parody-xi-jinping|title=China blocks HBO after John Oliver mockery of Xi Jinping|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=June 25, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625185611/http://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/2152323/china-blocks-hbo-after-john-oliver-parody-xi-jinping|archive-date=June 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> although Last Week Tonight had already been excluded from [[HBO (Asia)|HBO Asia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/25/world/asia/china-hbo-john-oliver-xi-jinping.html|title=China Blocks HBO Website After John Oliver's Jokes About Xi Jinping|access-date=June 25, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625130936/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/25/world/asia/china-hbo-john-oliver-xi-jinping.html|archive-date=June 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe promotion for Season 3 highlighted four derogatory quotes either the show or Oliver himself received: \"Comedian fool\" (former [[FIFA]] vice-president [[Jack Warner (football executive)|Jack Warner]], responding to a segment on the [[2015 FIFA corruption case]]), \"Makes people dumb\" (an article ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' wrote about the show), \"Very boring\" ([[Donald Trump]]'s assessment of the show), and \"More unpleasant than a diuretic\" (what [[President of Ecuador]] [[Rafael Correa]] said \"gringo talk shows\" were like, after being featured in a segment).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/136882-when-does-last-week-tonight-season-3-premiere-john-olivers-hit-show-is-about-to-jazz|title=When Does 'Last Week Tonight' Season 3 Premiere? John Oliver's Hit Show Is About To Jazz Up Your Winter|last=Tognotti|first=Chris|date=January 20, 2016|website=Bustle|accessdate=April 12, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402032053/http://www.bustle.com/articles/136882-when-does-last-week-tonight-season-3-premiere-john-olivers-hit-show-is-about-to-jazz|archive-date=April 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== The John Oliver Effect ===\n{{Main|John Oliver#Influence and the \"John Oliver effect\"|l1 = John Oliver (Influence)}}\nOn several occasions, show segments on major societal issues, such as the \"Chickens\" or \"Bail\" segments, were soon followed by real-world change and action on said issues by the public, policymakers and/or other institutions. Several media outlets, noticing this pattern, suggested that attention from the show had instigated these changes, going so far as to dub the phenomenon the \"John Oliver Effect\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/3674807/john-oliver-net-neutrality-civil-forfeiture-miss-america/|title=How the 'John Oliver Effect' Is Having a Real-Life Impact|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2015/09/29/john-oliver-impact/|title=The John Oliver Effect|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> One of the most commonly cited examples of this is Oliver's first Net Neutrality segment which allegedly led to more than 45,000 comments being sent to the [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]], crashing the website set up to receive comments in the process.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/jun/03/john-oliver-fcc-website-net-neutrality|title=John Oliver's cheeky net neutrality plea crashes FCC website|last=Holpuch|first=Amanda|date=2014-06-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nOliver himself does not believe the effect to be real and has openly ridiculed the idea on the show, even calling the term \"completely meaningless\".{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Tobacco===\n{{Main|Tobacco (Last Week Tonight)}}\n\"Tobacco\" is a segment about the tobacco industry, which aired on February 15, 2015, as part of the second episode of the second season. During the eighteen-minute segment, Oliver discusses tobacco industry trends and practices. He also introduces Jeff the Diseased Lung, a mascot he created for the American global cigarette and tobacco company [[Philip Morris International]], the makers of [[Marlboro (cigarette)|Marlboro]] brand of cigarettes. The anthropomorphic diseased lung, who smokes and coughs, has been compared to Joe Camel and the [[Marlboro Man]]. Oliver and his team promoted the cartoon character by sending shirts with Jeff's image to [[Togo]] and displaying billboards in [[Uruguay]], and by encouraging use of the hashtag #JeffWeCan, which trended on Twitter following the broadcast.\n\nThe segment received widespread media coverage, with several outlets praising Oliver's ability to launch successful marketing campaigns and change perceptions about smoking through the creation of the mascot. The mascot later made an appearance at a protest organized by the \"Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids\" in New York City in May 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.medicaldaily.com/john-olivers-jeff-diseased-lung-hits-times-square-anti-smoking-awareness-flash-mob-332252|last=Olson|first=Samantha|title=John Oliver's 'Jeff The Diseased Lung' Hits Times Square For Anti-Smoking Awareness Flash Mob|date=May 6, 2015|work=Medical Daily|access-date=September 3, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915181858/http://www.medicaldaily.com/john-olivers-jeff-diseased-lung-hits-times-square-anti-smoking-awareness-flash-mob-332252|archive-date=September 15, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kickbuttsday.org/index.php/updates/detail/2015_05_22_nyc|title=Youth advocates head to New York City to #StopMarlboro - Kick Butts Day|last=Olmstead|first=Erica|website=Kick Butts Day|date=May 22, 2015|access-date=September 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163701/https://www.kickbuttsday.org/index.php/updates/detail/2015_05_22_nyc|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPhilip Morris International issued a response to the segment, stating that it included \"many mischaracterizations\" of the company.<ref name=Parker>{{cite news|last=Parker|first=Ryan|title=John Oliver targets cigarettes on 'Last Week Tonight'; Philip Morris reacts|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-philip-morris-john-oliver-20150216-story.html|accessdate=November 24, 2015|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=February 16, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151122195954/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-philip-morris-john-oliver-20150216-story.html|archive-date=November 22, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Stranger Than Truth: John Oliver's 101 Favorite History Lies ===\nIn the Mandatory Minimums segment that aired on July 25, 2015, John Oliver talked about the controversial history of presidential pardoning, claiming that Abraham Lincoln once pardoned a man convicted of bestiality because he was intoxicated at the time; the man in question being John Wilkes Booth. He then confessed the statement was not true and for the first time mentioned a book compiling his favorite history lies.\n\nA couple of weeks later, he published a web-exclusive video  based on that reference, expanding the content for a book called \"Stranger Than Truth: John Oliver's 101 Favorite History Lies\", to be released in the following spring. At the end of the mini-segment, however, he confesses again that the entire book was also a lie.\n\nIn what seems a continuation of the lie saga, the book surprisingly appeared on Amazon UK in October 2018.\n\nThe book description reads as follow: <blockquote>There is absolutely nothing more fun than lying confidently about history. Lying is incredibly fun. In fact, the only thing that feels better than lying to someone is lying to someone, then regaining their trust, and then lying to them again. This book, for example, was promised to be released in April 2016. But that was a lie. The plan was always October 2018. Because, you know, now is a time in history when lying openly gets you elected to office. </blockquote><blockquote>In this book, you will find plenty of plausible but completely unverifiable nonsense. Almost like watching Fox News but with a better sense of humour. Hopefully, it will teach you much about nothing other than the true joy of lying to people. Honestly, there has never been a better moment in history to be a liar. We have reached a point where truths have become lies and lies are now the truth. So learn from the greatest and get inspired by the best lies in history. </blockquote><blockquote>*NB: Most profits from this book are going to finance railway infrastructure under the English Channel. Contains strong language.<ref>{{Cite book|title=STRANGER THAN TRUTH.|last=PAUL.|first=OSPREY, FEY. DORIAN|date=2018|publisher=BLURB|isbn=978-0464820208|location=[S.l.]|oclc=1057754076}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption===\n{{Main|Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption}}\nIn August 2015, after delivering his \"Televangelists\" segment, Oliver hired a professional tax lawyer to set up a church called [[Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption]] as a legal entity. He did this partly as a way to demonstrate how \"disturbingly easy\" it is, in terms of paperwork, to set up a [[Tax exemption|tax-exempt]] religious organization as viewed by the [[Internal Revenue Service]]. As Oliver explained, the requirements needed to be defined as a \"church\" are quite broad. Since regulatory guidelines require an established location for a church, Oliver chose his studio location in New York City as its official location,<ref name=\"Mediaite\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/john-oliver-one-ups-colbert-super-pac-by-creating-his-own-tax-exempt-church/ |last=Wilstein |first=Matt |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=John Oliver One-Ups Colbert Super PAC by Creating His Own Tax-Exempt Church |work=Mediaite |quote=\"... This is real,\" John Oliver repeatedly told his Last Week Tonight audience last night after announcing the creation of his new megachurch, Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption ...\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150825011710/http://www.mediaite.com/tv/john-oliver-one-ups-colbert-super-pac-by-creating-his-own-tax-exempt-church/ |archive-date=August 25, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> although he registered the [[nonprofit organization]] in the state of [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://religionnews.com/2015/08/18/john-oliver-hbo-last-week-tonight-televangelists-church-irs-creflo-dollar-tilton-copeland/ |last=Pellot |first=Brian |date=August 18, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title='Megareverend' John Oliver trolls televangelists with new tax-exempt church |agency=[[Religion News Service]] |quote=\"... Oliver registered his church as a nonprofit corporation in Texas, named his New York studio as its \"established place of worship,\"...\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150819025650/http://www.religionnews.com/2015/08/18/john-oliver-hbo-last-week-tonight-televangelists-church-irs-creflo-dollar-tilton-copeland/ |archive-date=August 19, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Oliver's \"megachurch\" had a [[Toll-free telephone number|toll-free phone number]] which allowed callers to donate to the church, and said that any money collected would be redistributed to the charitable relief organization [[Doctors Without Borders]].<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite news |url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/08/john-oliver-takes-on-televangelism-on-last-week-tonight |first=Nate |last=Scott |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=John Oliver takes on televangelism on 'Last Week Tonight' |work=[[USA Today]] |quote=... You can donate to the church, too. (Though eventually, all the donations will be moved to Doctors Without Borders.) ... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822104843/http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/08/john-oliver-takes-on-televangelism-on-last-week-tonight |archive-date=August 22, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Pedestrian>{{cite web |url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/entertainment/john-oliver-launches-his-very-own-anti-evangelist-church/ |last=Bracken |first=Claire |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=John Oliver launches his very own anti-Evangelist church |work=Pedestrian News |quote=\"... John Oliver ran a segment on \"church's who exploit people's faith for monetary gain\" and explored the ease at which these can be created in America ...\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904194105/https://www.pedestrian.tv/entertainment/john-oliver-launches-his-very-own-anti-evangelist-church/ |archive-date=September 4, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Oliver announced the formation of his church on the episode of the show that aired on August 16, 2015.<ref name=\"TimeMag\">{{cite news |url=http://time.com/3999933/john-oliver-televangelist-church-alst-week-tonight/ |first=Melissa |last=Locker |title=John Oliver Becomes a Televangelist and Finally Starts His Own Church |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |work=Time |quote=... The satirical aim of Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption will be to collect copious, tax-exempt donations ... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824174155/http://time.com/3999933/john-oliver-televangelist-church-alst-week-tonight/ |archive-date=August 24, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nMatt Wilstein, writing for ''[[Mediaite]]'', saw Oliver's stunt as being along the same lines as comedian [[Stephen Colbert]]'s setting up of a [[501(c)(4)]] organization\u2014[[Colbert Super PAC]]\u2014as a way to \"test the absurd limits of the Supreme Court's [[Citizens United v. FEC|Citizens United decision]]\"; Oliver's megachurch, in contrast, is a way to test whether the IRS might view his \"megachurch\" as a tax-exempt organization.<ref name=\"Mediaite\"/> Steve Thorngate, writing in ''[[The Christian Century]]'', suggested that the question of the religious exemption from taxation was more difficult and nuanced than Oliver portrayed, and not a simple matter of government regulation, describing Oliver's pivot to IRS policy as \"unhelpful.\" However, Thorngate agreed that Oliver's exposure and criticism of \"manipulative sleazeballs\" who \"fleece the faithful\" is \"spot-on.\"<ref name=\"ChristianCentury\">{{cite web |url=https://www.christiancentury.org/blogs/archive/2015-08/why-john-olivers-televangelism-segment-about-irs |first=Steve |last=Thorngate |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=Why is John Oliver's televangelism segment about the IRS? |work=The Christian Century |quote=\"... Oliver's scornful outrage: televangelists who fleece the faithful ... The question of religious tax exemption generally is more complicated. ...\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150820000830/http://www.christiancentury.org/blogs/archive/2015-08/why-john-olivers-televangelism-segment-about-irs |archive-date=August 20, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Leonardo Blair, writing for ''[[Christian Post]]'', described Oliver's segment as a \"brutal takedown\" of televangelists and churches which preach \"the [[prosperity theology|prosperity gospel]],\" a message that dupes people into thinking that cash donations will solve medical or financial problems, while in fact the donations go to the personal aggrandizement of televangelists who buy expensive jets or large mansions.<ref name=\"ChristianPost\">{{cite web |url=https://www.christianpost.com/news/comedian-john-oliver-lampoons-televangelists-on-last-week-tonight-show-opens-our-lady-of-perpetual-exemption-church-143003/ |first=Blair |last=Leonardo |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=Comedian John Oliver Lampoons Televangelists on 'Last Week Tonight' Show; Opens Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption Church |work=[[The Christian Post]] |quote=... From Creflo Dollar to Kenneth Copeland, late night comedian John Oliver delivered a brutal takedown. ... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150823142157/http://www.christianpost.com/news/comedian-john-oliver-lampoons-televangelists-on-last-week-tonight-show-opens-our-lady-of-perpetual-exemption-church-143003/ |archive-date=August 23, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA week later, on the following episode, Oliver devoted a short segment to the donations the church had received, which included money from around the world. Oliver said he had received \"thousands of envelopes with thousands of dollars\" from donors. Displayed were several US Post Office containers full of mail. Oliver told viewers that the more money they sent in, the more \"blessings\" would be returned to them, adding that \"that is still something I'm \u2014 amazingly \u2014 legally allowed to say.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title = John Oliver Televangelist Church Received \"Thousands of Dollars,\" Seeds and Beef Jerky|url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-televangelist-church-received-817058|website = The Hollywood Reporter|date = August 24, 2015|accessdate = August 25, 2015|quote = ... We have received thousands of envelopes with thousands of dollars ...|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150826221454/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-televangelist-church-received-817058|archive-date = August 26, 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nOliver announced that the Church would be shutting down during his show on September 13, 2015. All monetary donations have been forwarded to Doctors Without Borders.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourladyofperpetualexemption.com/ | title=Closed. Praise Be Unto You | date=September 13, 2015 | accessdate=September 13, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150827212918/http://www.ourladyofperpetualexemption.com/ | archive-date=August 27, 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Donald Trump ===\n{{Main|Donald Trump (Last Week Tonight)|Last Week Tonight segments about Donald Trump}}\n[[Donald Trump (Last Week Tonight)|\"Donald Trump\"]] is a segment discussing American businessman Donald Trump. It aired on February 28, 2016, as part of the third episode of the third season. During the 22-minute segment, Oliver discusses [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Trump's 2016 presidential campaign]] and his long career in business. He also reveals that the Trump family name was changed at one point from the ancestral name 'Drumpf'. Although the changing of names was once a common [[Anglicisation of names|practice]] among many non-English immigrants to the United States, the segment popularized the term \"Donald Drumpf\" and started a campaign urging viewers to \"Make Donald Drumpf Again,\" a play on Trump's own campaign slogan, \"[[Make America Great Again]].\" It is the most popular segment the show has ever done. The segment garnered more than 85 million views on Facebook and YouTube combined which, an HBO spokesman has said, \"is a record for any piece of HBO content.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/03/30/media/john-oliver-donald-trump/index.html|title=Even John Oliver enjoys a Drumpf bump|last=Stelter|first=Brian|date=March 30, 2016|website=CNNMoney|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331201056/http://money.cnn.com/2016/03/30/media/john-oliver-donald-trump/index.html|archive-date=March 31, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Throughout the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]] and following [[Inauguration of Donald Trump|Trump's inauguration]], Oliver made [[Last Week Tonight segments about Donald Trump|additional segments regarding Trump]].\n\n===Debt buyers===\n\"Debt Buyers\" is a segment discussing the business and questionable practice of [[debt buyers]]. It aired on June 5, 2016, as part of the fourteenth episode of the third season. Oliver announced he had purchased nearly $15 million in medical debt that belonged to 9,000 debtors. He did this through a company he had created, called \"Central Asset Recovery Professionals Inc.\" (CARP), which he described as being \"for [[Carp|the bottom-feeding fish]].\" Oliver stated that it was \"pretty clear by now [that] debt buying is a grimy business, and badly needs more oversight\" and went to point out that starting such a business was \"disturbingly easy.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2016/06/06/john-oliver-buys-and-forgives-15-million-of-debt-last-week-tonight/85488616/ |first=Kelly |last=Lawler |title=John Oliver buys and forgives $15 million of debt |website=USA Today |date=June 6, 2016 |accessdate=June 6, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160606180535/http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2016/06/06/john-oliver-buys-and-forgives-15-million-of-debt-last-week-tonight/85488616/ |archive-date=June 6, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> It cost him $50 to register the business in [[Mississippi]], while it cost less than $60,000 to purchase almost $15 million in [[bad debt]], medical debt from Texas. Oliver forgave the debt in its entirety, and claimed that it was the largest single giveaway in the American television history, eclipsing that of [[General Motors]] on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' in 2004 where it gifted cars to Winfrey's studio audience, worth an estimated $8 million in total.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/news/archive/2016/06/john-oliver-debt/485834/ | first=J. Weston | last=Phippen | title=John Oliver's $15 Million Debt Giveaway | website=The Atlantic | date=June 6, 2016 | accessdate=June 6, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160607105724/http://www.theatlantic.com/news/archive/2016/06/john-oliver-debt/485834/ | archive-date=June 7, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Writing for ''Slate'', Jordan Weissmann disputed the $15 million figure: \"[Oliver] says CARP paid around $60,000 ... for its paper, which was 'out-of-statute'\u2014meaning the debts were so old that creditors technically couldn't even sue over them anymore. That suggests the seller thought the debts were worth no more than, well, $60,000.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/moneybox/2016/06/06/john_oliver_did_not_really_give_away_15_million_on_his_show.html |title=Sorry, but John Oliver Did Not Really Just Give Away $15 Million |last=Weissmann |first=Jordan |date=June 6, 2016 |newspaper=Slate |issn=1091-2339 |access-date=June 7, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160606221649/http://www.slate.com/blogs/moneybox/2016/06/06/john_oliver_did_not_really_give_away_15_million_on_his_show.html |archive-date=June 6, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The episode was highlighted in the academic journal ''Religions''.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Krantz |first=David |title=Shmita Revolution: The Reclamation and Reinvention of the Sabbatical Year |work=Religions |date=August 8, 2016 |url=http://www.mdpi.com/2077-1444/7/8/100 |accessdate=August 30, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920052704/http://www.mdpi.com/2077-1444/7/8/100 |archive-date=September 20, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The show partnered with RIP Medical Debt, Inc. to abolish the debt.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kasperkevic |first1=Jana |title=John Oliver buys and forgives $15m worth of medical debt |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/jun/06/john-oliver-medical-debt-forgiveness-last-week-tonight |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=June 6, 2016 |quote=Instead of collecting the debt, however, Last Week Tonight partnered with RIP Medical Debt charity and decided to forgive that debt. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619140428/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/jun/06/john-oliver-medical-debt-forgiveness-last-week-tonight |archive-date=June 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ripmedicaldebt.org/the-miracle-of-debt-forgiveness-on-hbos-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver/|title=The Miracle of Debt Forgiveness on HBO's Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|last=Goff|first=Robert|website=RIP Medical Debt, Inc.|date=June 5, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115132834/https://www.ripmedicaldebt.org/the-miracle-of-debt-forgiveness-on-hbos-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver/|archive-date=November 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Coal mining and Bob Murray ===\nOn June 18, 2017, ''Last Week Tonight''{{'}}s main segment was about coal mining and [[Robert E. Murray|Bob Murray]]. In his segment, Oliver talked about how the safety condition inside the coal mines specifically the 2007 [[Crandall Canyon Mine]] collapse, which killed six miners, in which Oliver criticized Murray for claiming the collapse was caused by an [[earthquake]], despite all evidence demonstrating otherwise.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsy.com/stories/coal-ceo-sues-john-oliver-and-his-show-for-defamation/|title=John Oliver Is In Legal Trouble For His Rant About A Coal CEO|last=Suneson|first=Grant|work=Newsy|date=June 22, 2017|accessdate=June 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623041444/http://www.newsy.com/stories/coal-ceo-sues-john-oliver-and-his-show-for-defamation/|archive-date=June 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The show ended with a costumed [[squirrel]] named \"Mr. Nutterbutter\" presenting Murray with a voided check for \"3 acorns and 18 cents\" in response to Murray's company presenting its employees with low sums of money as bonuses, and how the employees retaliate by voiding the checks, and in reference to a claim that stated that Murray supposedly got the idea to start his company from a talking squirrel.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Coal: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO) |series=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver |date=June 18, 2017 |accessdate=June 23, 2017 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aw6RsUhw1Q8 |network=HBO |last=Oliver |first=John (host) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623002244/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aw6RsUhw1Q8 |archivedate=June 23, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> On June 22, Bob Murray presented a [[lawsuit]] against Oliver, HBO, and [[Time Warner]] for defamation. HBO believes ''Last Week Tonight'' has done nothing wrong, with a [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] lawyer describing the lawsuit as \"frivolous.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In February 2018, a West Virginia judge stated that he plans to dismiss the lawsuit filed by Murray as unfounded.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Oppenheim|first1=Maya|title=Coal tycoon's defamation lawsuit against John Oliver dismissed by judge|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/john-oliver-bob-murray-defamation-lawsuit-dismissed-judge-murray-energy-corp-a8226846.html|accessdate=February 26, 2018|work=The Independent|date=February 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225060807/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/john-oliver-bob-murray-defamation-lawsuit-dismissed-judge-murray-energy-corp-a8226846.html|archive-date=February 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter Murray's appeal to the West Virginia Supreme Court was delayed due to impeachment of the judges, Murray offered to drop the charges and HBO accepted.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2019/nov/11/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-lawsuits-murray-energy|title=John Oliver takes on muzzling lawsuits \u2013 and the man who sued his show|last=Horton|first=Adrian|date=November 11, 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On November 10, 2019, Oliver discussed the case in a segment about [[SLAPP|SLAPP suits]], revealing that the suit cost HBO $200,000 in legal costs and tripled the show's libel insurance fees. Oliver acknowledged that, despite the segment being vetted, the content would likely lead to another lawsuit, and that he would stand behind his team if it were to happen.<ref name=\":1\" /> The segment was ended with a five-minute, [[Times Square]]-set [[musical number]] featuring crude and ludicrous fictional anecdotes about Murray; the musical is titled \"Eat Shit, Bob.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===''A Day in the Life of Marlon Bundo''===\n{{Main|A Day in the Life of Marlon Bundo}}\nOn March 18, 2018, Oliver announced the publication of a children's book, ''[[A Day in the Life of Marlon Bundo]]'', which parodies a book that [[Mike Pence]]'s family wrote about their family rabbit, [[Marlon Bundo's: A Day in the Life of the Vice President|Marlon Bundo]]. Oliver used his book as a platform to criticize Pence's positions on LGBT issues, as it featured a rabbit in a same-sex relationship.<ref name=\"Daily Beast Bundo\">{{cite news |last=Stern |first=Marlow |date=March 19, 2018 |title=John Oliver Trolls Vice President Mike Pence With Gay Children's Book of His Pet Bunny |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/john-oliver-trolls-vice-president-mike-pence-with-gay-childrens-book-of-his-pet-bunny |work=Daily Beast |location= |access-date=March 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319104738/https://www.thedailybeast.com/john-oliver-trolls-vice-president-mike-pence-with-gay-childrens-book-of-his-pet-bunny |archive-date=March 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The book became the number-one book and e-book on [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] the next day, and the top-selling audiobook on [[Audible (store)|Audible]].<ref name=\"Politico Bundo\">{{cite news |last=Nelson |first=Louis |date=March 19, 2018 |title=Comey's memoir tops Amazon's best-sellers list |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/03/19/james-comey-memoir-sales-470281 |work=Politico |location= |access-date=March 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319140528/https://www.politico.com/story/2018/03/19/james-comey-memoir-sales-470281 |archive-date=March 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/03/john-oliver-marlon-bundo-book-mike-pence-troll|title=John Oliver's Gay-Bunny Book Is Outselling the Mike Pence Book It's Trolling|first=Hillary|last=Busis|website=Vanity Fair|date=March 20, 2018|accessdate=June 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Russell Crowe's jockstrap===\n{{main|Russell Crowe's jockstrap}}\n[[Russell Crowe's jockstrap]] became a notable piece of memorabilia when it was purchased by the ''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver'' and then donated to a Blockbuster Video shop. The jockstrap reappeared in a skit in the final episode of the 2018 season of the show.\n\n===Robocalls===\nThe March 10, 2019, episode dealt primarily with [[robocalls]], and how the problem had mushroomed in recent years since being increasingly deregulated under [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC Chairman]] [[Ajit Pai]]. To prove the point of how easy it was for any company to begin flooding anyone with robocalls, Oliver had one of his IT techs develop a system in which all of the FCC chairs would, at regular intervals on their personal phone numbers, receive a robocall followed immediately by [[bagpipe]] music. Oliver freely admitted his astonishment at just how easy this was to accomplish; the IT technician tasked with setting the system up told him they needed only 15 minutes to complete the project, doing so on a minimal budget. And per the very FCC regulations currently in place, Oliver quickly scrolled a section of fine print on screen at a random time during the segment, in which his office address was randomly embedded, and each FCC chair was required to send him an official letter to that address, notifying him in writing that they wished to have him cease all robocalls forthwith. Oliver was also flabbergasted at discovering that while tens of millions of dollars in fines were levied against companies for violating robocall regulations, only a few thousand dollars have ever been collected, effectively giving the companies free rein to continue robocalling unabated.\n\n===''Guinness World Records''===\nThe main story of the August 11, 2019 episode was [[Turkmenistan]] and its autocratic leader [[Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow]]. The last portion of the segment centered around Berdimuhamedow's obsession with ''[[Guinness World Records]]'', with the Turkmen capital of [[Ashgabat]] being home to the most buildings with white marble cladding, the largest indoor [[Ferris wheel]], and the largest statue of a horse's head, among others. Oliver found that ''Guinness World Records'' received sums of money ranging from US$12,000 to US$500,000 from companies and authoritarian nations to set records for publicity. He ended the show with a 600 square foot [[marble cake]] adorned with a picture of Berdimuhamedow falling from a horse; he had requested a Guinness adjudicator to certify it as the world's largest marble cake, a record previously set by [[Betty Crocker]] in Saudi Arabia in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.generalmills.com/2017/09/a-gift-fresh-from-the-heart-in-saudi-arabia/|title=A gift 'fresh from the heart' in Saudi Arabia|website=General Mills|language=en|date=September 27, 2017|access-date=August 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815165112/https://blog.generalmills.com/2017/09/a-gift-fresh-from-the-heart-in-saudi-arabia/|archive-date=August 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Guinness refused, stating that because their brand was \"aligned with kids and families\", they would not send an adjudicator; Oliver mockingly commented that he didn't \"run a brutal enough dictatorship to meet Guinness World Records' high ethical standards\". Oliver claimed that Guinness offered to certify it after the fact only if he signed an agreement not to criticize their practices on the show, which Oliver dismissed as \"ridiculous\".<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-9QYu8LtH2E |title=Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedov: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver |date=August 11, 2019 |author=HBO |access-date=August 15, 2019 |via=YouTube |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815170404/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-9QYu8LtH2E&gl=US&hl=en |archive-date=August 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5648682/john-oliver-turkmenistan-cake/|title=John Oliver Bakes Very Large Cake to Annoy Turkmenistan|website=Time|language=en|access-date=August 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814150445/https://time.com/5648682/john-oliver-turkmenistan-cake/|archive-date=August 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Guinness called Oliver's allegations \"false and unfair\", claiming that they did not send an adjudicator because they felt the cake was specifically for the purpose of mocking a record holder, stating it was their policy \"not to partake in any activities which may belittle their achievements or subject them to ridicule\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2019/8/guinness-world-records-on-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-586398/|title=Guinness World Records on Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|date=August 12, 2019|website=Guinness World Records|language=en-GB|access-date=August 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813023105/https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2019/8/guinness-world-records-on-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-586398/|archive-date=August 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Narendra Modi===\n\nJohn Oliver extensively satirized Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] in a broadcast which went online on February 23, 2020 calling him a temporary symbol of hate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qVIXUhZ2AWs |title=Last Week Tonight With John Oliver |publisher=Last Week Tonight |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> This was during a visit of US President [[Donald Trump]] to India, and in an [[Namaste Trump|organized rally]] which unexpectedly coincided with [[North East Delhi riots|large-scale violence in Delhi]], the country's capital. In this episode, Oliver likened Modi's [[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP party's]] political beliefs to [[Adolf Hitler|Adolf Hitler's]], by noting that this party's founders, in 1925, had admired Hitler for his methods to ensure \u201cthe purity of the race\u201d \u2013 \u201cwhich is just not a chill thing to admire Hitler - and that, there is one and only one thing that it\u2019s OK to admire Hitler for, and it\u2019s the fact that he killed Hitler.\" <ref name=\"TempHate\">{{cite news|last1=Horton|first1=Adrian|title=John Oliver explains Trump's support of Modi, India's 'temporary symbol of hate'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/feb/24/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-recap-trump-modi-india|accessdate=February 26, 2018|work=Guardian|date=February 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229180408/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/feb/24/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-recap-trump-modi-india|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Oliver also lampooned Trump's choice of words to describe Modi as \"the father of India\", suggesting that there is a [[Mahatma Gandhi|certain Gandhi]] that already holds that exact title.<ref name=\"TempHate\"/> The brunt of his attacks, however, were aimed at Modi's \"increasingly controversial reputation and [[Citizenship Amendment Act protests|widespread protests against his government's citizenship measures]].\"<ref name=\"TempHate\"/>In his attempt to explain the political climate in India under BJP which condones [[Violence against Muslims in India|widespread violence against Muslims]], Oliver mentions how Modi's party-appointed head of [[Uttar Pradesh]], the largest BJP-ruled state of India, said at a recent rally: \u201cIf they kill one Hindu then we will also kill 100 of them (Muslims).\"<ref name=\"TempHate\"/>He further adds that Modi's party has also edited religious pluralism out of history textbooks, and introduced primary school textbooks teaching Indian supremacy, and that the image is \"nauseating\" and that for perhaps the first time in Modi's whole career, his actions are creating a massive and sustained backlash.<ref name=\"TempHate\"/>Oliver concludes this segment by saying that when Trump says Modi is bringing India together, \u201cwith any luck, the thing that unites them may actually end up being their complete disgust over what he is trying to do\u201d, since India, home of the \u201csymbol of love\u201d [[Taj Mahal]], \u201cfrankly deserves much more than this temporary symbol of hate\u201d.<ref name=\"TempHate\"/>\n\n[[Disney+ Hotstar|Hotstar]], an Indian streaming service who holds rights to HBO programming in the country, refused to stream the episode, leading to criticism by local viewers (including Hotstar's apps being [[Review bombing|review bombed]] with 1-star reviews).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/entertainment/news/hotstar-1-star-reviews-modi-john-oliver-last-week-tonight-censorship-backlash-2185798|title=Hotstar Gets 1-Star Reviews for Pro-Government Censorship of John Oliver|website=NDTV Gadgets 360|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> Oliver addressed the censorship in the March 8, 2020 episode, also noting that since the acquisition of Hotstar by [[The Walt Disney Company]] (which occurred as part of its [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|acquisition of 21st Century Fox]]),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/entertainment/news/hotstar-southeast-asia-expansion-disney-bob-iger-star-india-2081496|title=Disney Plans Southeast Asia Expansion for Hotstar|website=NDTV Gadgets 360|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> Hotstar had begun to censor jokes regarding Disney characters from the program, such as his \"factually-accurate\" claim that [[Donald Duck]] had a [[corkscrew penis]].<ref name=\"thr-lwthotstar\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/john-oliver-slams-disney-owned-hotstar-removing-jokes-disney-1283146|title=John Oliver Slams Disney-Owned Streamer for Censoring 'Last Week Tonight' Jokes About Disney|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==International broadcast==\n''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver'' episode clips can be seen internationally on [[YouTube]]. It is broadcast on [[Pay television|premium]] channel [[HBO Canada]] that is [[simulcast]] with HBO in the U.S.; around the same time it is shown on the international [[HBO (international)|HBO]] channels. It airs in Australia on [[The Comedy Channel]] hours after the U.S. airing<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2014/04/airdate-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver.html|title=Airdate: Last Week Tonight|last=Knox|first=David|date=April 11, 2014|accessdate=June 2, 2014|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602200503/http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2014/04/airdate-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver.html|archive-date=June 2, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> and airs in New Zealand on [[SoHo (TV channel)|SoHo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dannews.co.nz/2015/01/28/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-coming-to-soho/|title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver coming to SoHo|date=January 28, 2015|publisher=Dan News|accessdate=August 13, 2015|archivedate=August 13, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150813114138/http://dannews.co.nz/2015/01/28/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-coming-to-soho/}}</ref> In the United Kingdom and Ireland, it is broadcast on Mondays on [[Sky Comedy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sky.com/watch/title/series/b7a772c4-8fdb-4e28-be16-66141b9b34d6/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver |title=Last Week Tonight With John Oliver |publisher=Sky |accessdate=February 20, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> In Belgium, it is broadcast on Thursdays by the [[Telenet (Belgium)|Telenet]] cable-only channel [[Prime (Flanders)|PRIME Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prime.be/series/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-2|title=Last Week Tonight With John Oliver S2|publisher=Telenet/PRIME|accessdate=February 21, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150221095413/http://www.prime.be/series/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-2|archivedate=February 21, 2015}}</ref> It airs in South Africa on [[M-Net]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel24.co.za/TV/News/M-Net-adds-exciting-new-late-night-talk-show-to-its-schedule-20140430|publisher=channel24.co.za|title=M-Net adds exciting new late night talk show to its schedule|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=September 9, 2015|last=Ferreira|first=Thinus|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930202818/http://www.channel24.co.za/TV/News/M-Net-adds-exciting-new-late-night-talk-show-to-its-schedule-20140430|archive-date=September 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and in Portugal on [[RTP3]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ferreira|first1=David|trans-title=|title=Conhe\u00e7a a programa\u00e7\u00e3o da nova RTP3 (com v\u00eddeo)|url=http://www.atelevisao.com/cabo/conheca-a-programacao-da-nova-rtp3/|language=Portuguese|accessdate=September 29, 2015|publisher=A Televis\u00e3o|date=September 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930130307/http://www.atelevisao.com/cabo/conheca-a-programacao-da-nova-rtp3/|archive-date=September 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In India, the show is streamed on Hotstar Premium.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.hotstar.com/tv/last-week-tonight/s-585 | title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver TV Series Full Episodes, Watch Last Week Tonight with John Oliver TV Show Online | access-date=November 18, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118164539/https://www.hotstar.com/tv/last-week-tonight/s-585 | archive-date=November 18, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Comedy|Television}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.hbo.com/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=3530232|title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n* {{tv.com show|last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver|Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n* {{Facebook|LastWeekTonight}}\n* {{YouTube|u=LastWeekTonight|Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{Last Week Tonight}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= [[List of awards and nominations received by Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|Awards for ''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver'']]\n|list=\n{{Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Talk Show}}\n{{Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Variety Talk Series}}\n{{TCA Award for Outstanding Achievement in News and Information}}\n{{Writers Guild of America Award for Television: Comedy-Variety Talk Series}}\n}}\n{{Late night television in the United States}}\n{{HBONetwork Shows}}\n\n[[Category:Last Week Tonight 