{"title_page": "List of legendary creatures from Japan", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2017}}\n{{jmyth infobox}}\nThe following is a list of [[demons]], [[ghosts]], [[kami]], [[obake]], [[y\u014dkai]], [[y\u016brei]] and other [[legendary creatures]] that are notable in [[Japanese folklore]] and [[Japanese mythology|mythology]].\n\n{{compact ToC|num=yes}}\n\n==A==\n* Abe no seimei - A half human half yokai that is famed for being an onmyoji (specialist in magic and divination). \n*[[Abumi-guchi]] \u2013 A furry creature formed from the stirrup of a mounted military commander who worked for [[Yamata no Orochi]].\n* [[Abura-akago]] \u2013 An infant [[ghost]] who licks the oil out of [[Traditional lighting equipment of Japan|''andon'']] lamps.\n* [[Abura-sumashi]] \u2013 A spirit with a large head who lives on a mountain pass in [[Kumamoto Prefecture]].\n*Abura-tokkuri - A possessed pot.\n* [[Akabeko]] \u2013 A red [[cattle|cow]] involved in the construction of Enz\u014d-ji in [[Yanaizu, Fukushima]].\n* [[Akamanto]] - A ghost in red mantle that offers either red or blue toilet paper roll in toilets. \n* [[Akaname]] \u2013 A spirit who licks off filth in untidy bathrooms.\n* [[Akashita]] \u2013 A creature that looms in a black cloud over a floodgate.\n* [[Akateko (folklore)|Akateko]] \u2013 A red hand dangling out of a tree.\n* [[Akkorokamui]] \u2013 An [[Ainu people|Ainu]] monster resembling a [[fish]] or [[octopus]].\n* [[Akurojin-no-hi]] \u2013 A ghostly fire from [[Mie Prefecture]].\n* [[Akub\u014dzu]] \u2013Akub\u014dzu, live in the ashes of hearths, they are from [[Akita Prefecture|Akita]] and [[Iwate Prefecture|Iwate]].\n* [[Amabie]] \u2013 A Japanese mermaid yokai.\n* [[Amaburakosagi]] \u2013 A ritual-disciplinary [[demon]] from [[Shikoku]].\n* [[Amamehagi]] \u2013 A ritual-disciplinary [[demon]] from [[Hokuriku region|Hokuriku]].\n* [[Amanojaku]] \u2013 A small [[demon]] that instigates people into wickedness.\n* [[Amanozako]] \u2013 A monstrous goddess mentioned in the [[Kujiki]].\n* [[Amazake-babaa]] \u2013 An old woman who asks for sweet sake and brings disease.\n* [[Amefurikoz\u014d]] \u2013 A little boy spirit who plays in the rain.\n* [[Amemasu]] \u2013 An [[Ainu people|Ainu]] creature resembling a [[fish]] or [[whale]].\n* [[Ameonna]] \u2013 A rain-making female spirit.\n* [[Amikiri]] \u2013 A net-cutting bird-headed, crustacean-armed, snake-bodied spirit.\n* [[Amor\u014dnagu]] \u2013 A ''Tennyo'' from the island of Amami \u014cshima.\n* [[Amaterasu]] \u2013 A sun goddess.\n* [[Anmo]] \u2013 A ritual-disciplinary [[demon]] from [[Iwate Prefecture]].\n* [[Aoandon]] \u2013 The demonic spirit which arises from an ''andon'' lamp at the end of a ''Hyakumonogatari Kaidankai''.\n* [[Aob\u014dzu]] \u2013 The blue monk who kidnaps children.\n* [[Aony\u014db\u014d]] \u2013 A female [[ghost]] who lurks in an abandoned imperial palace.\n* [[Aosaginohi]] \u2013 A luminescent [[heron]].\n* [[Arikura-no-baba]] \u2013 An old woman with magical powers.\n* [[Ashimagari]] \u2013 A spirit which entangles the legs of travelers.\n* [[Ashinagatenaga]] \u2013 A pair of characters, one with long legs and the other with long arms.\n* [[Ayakashi (y\u014dkai)]] \u2013 A phenomenon considered to be the [[funayurei]].\n* [[Azukiarai]] (or ''Azukitogi'') \u2013 A spirit that washes ''azuki'' beans.\n\n==B==\n* [[Bake-kujira]] \u2013 A ghostly whale skeleton that drifts along the coastline of [[Shimane Prefecture]].\n* [[Bakeneko]] \u2013 A shape-shifting cat.\n* [[Bakez\u014dri]] \u2013 A [[z\u014dri]] straw sandal spirit.\n* [[Baku (spirit)]] \u2013 Supernatural beings that devour dreams and nightmares.\n* [[Basan]] \u2013 A large fire-breathing [[chicken]] monster.\n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|Bash\u014dnosei]] - Banana tree spirit\n* [[Betobeto-san]] \u2013 Invisible spirit which follows people at night, making the sound of footsteps.\n* [[Binb\u014dgami]] \u2013 The spirit of poverty.\n* [[Tsukumogami#Types of tsukumogami|Biwa-bokuboku]] \u2013 Animated [[biwa]] lute.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume - \u660e|Buruburu]] \u2013 A spirit which clings to people inducing cowardice and shivers. \n* [[White Tiger (Chinese astronomy)|Byakko]] \u2013 Japanese version of the Chinese [[White Tiger (Chinese astronomy)|White Tiger]].\n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|By\u014dbunozoki]] - [[Tsukumogami]] that emerges from by\u014dbu to peep on people. \n\n==C==\n* [[Ch\u014dchinobake]] \u2013 A possessed [[Japanese lantern|ch\u014dchin lantern]].\n* [[Ch\u014dchinbi]] \u2013 Demonic flames which appear in footpaths between rice-fields.\n\n==D==\n* [[Daidarabotchi]] \u2013 A [[Giant (mythology)|giant]] responsible for creating the geographical features of Japan.\n* [[Tengu#Great and small demons|Daitengu]] \u2013 The most powerful ''[[tengu]]'', each of whom lives on a separate mountain.\n* [[Danzaburou-danuki]] \u2013 a [[bake-danuki]] from [[Sado Island]].\n* [[Datsue-ba]] \u2013 An old woman in the Underworld who removes clothes (or skin if unclothed) of the dead.\n* [[Dodomeki]] \u2013 A hundred-eyed demon.\n* [[D\u014dnotsura]] \u2013 A headless humanlike y\u014dkai with its face on its torso.\n\n==E==\n* [[Enenra]] \u2013 A monster made of smoke.\n* [[Kappa (folklore)|Enk\u014d]] \u2013 [[Kappa (folklore)|Kappa]] of [[Shikoku]] and western [[Honsh\u016b]].\n\n==F==\n* [[F\u016bjin]] \u2013 The wind god.\n* [[F\u016bri]] \u2013 A monkey-like yokai.\n* [[Funay\u016brei]] \u2013 [[Ghost]]s of people who died at sea.\n* [[Furaribi]] \u2013 A creature engulfed in flames that flies aimlessly.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Furutsubaki-no-rei]] \u2013 A soul-sucking plant.\n* [[Tsukumogami#Types of tsukumogami|Furu-utsubo]] \u2013 A beloved quiver of slain archers. \n* [[Futakuchi-onna]] \u2013 The two-mouthed woman.\n\n==G==\n* [[Gazu Hyakki Yagy\u014d|Gagoze]] \u2013 A demon who attacked young priests at Gang\u014d-ji temple.\n* [[Preta|Gaki]] \u2013 Starving ghosts of especially greedy people.\n* [[Gashadokuro]] \u2013 A giant [[Skeleton (undead)|skeleton]] that is the spirit of the unburied dead. Also known as ''[[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Gaikotsu]]''.\n* [[Black Tortoise|Genbu]] \u2013 Japanese version of the Chinese [[Black Tortoise]].\n* [[Gory\u014d]] \u2013 The [[vengeful spirit]]s of the dead.\n* [[Ox-Head and Horse-Face|Gozu and Mezu]] \u2013 Underworld guards.\n* [[Tengu#Great and small demons|Guhin]] \u2013 Another name for tengu.\n* [[Gy\u016bki]] \u2013 Another name for Ushi-oni.\n\n==H==\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Hakanohi]] \u2013 A fire which lights on graves.\n* Hakuja no Myojin<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TSgwAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA170&lpg=PA170&dq=Hakuja+no+Myojin#v=onepage&q=Hakuja+no+Myojin&f=false|title=The Oriental Economic Review|author=|date=14 July 2018|publisher=Oriental Information Agency|via=Google Books}}</ref> \u2013 A white serpent God.\n* [[Hachishaku-sama]] \u2013 A woman that is 8 feet tall and famous by kidnapping children.\n* [[Hakutaku]] \u2013 A beast which handed down knowledge on harmful spirits.\n* [[Hanako-san]] \u2013 A spirit of a young World War II-era girl who inhabits and haunts school restrooms.\n* [[Hannya]] \u2013 A noh mask representing a jealous female [[demon]].\n*Haradashi \u2013 A creature with a giant face on its stomach.\n* [[Harionago]] \u2013 A woman with a thorn-like barb on the tip of each strand of her hair.\n* [[Hashihime]] \u2013 A woman-turned-spirit associated with the bridge at Uji.\n* [[Heikegani]] \u2013 [[Crab]]s with human-faced shells. They are the spirits of the warriors killed in the [[Battle of Dan-no-ura]].\n* [[Hibagon]] \u2013 The Japanese version of the [[Bigfoot]] or the [[Yeti]].\n* [[Hiderigami]] \u2013 The spirit of drought.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Hihi]] \u2013 A baboon-like Chinese yokai.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Hikeshibaba]] \u2013 An old woman who extinguishes lanterns.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Hinode]] \u2013 The Sunrise.\n* [[Hitodama]] \u2013 A fireball [[ghost]] that appears when someone dies, signifying the dead person's spirit.\n* [[Hitotsume-koz\u014d]] \u2013 A one-eyed child spirit.\n* [[Hitotsume-ny\u016bd\u014d]] \u2013 A one-eyed monk spirit.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Hiyorib\u014d]] \u2013 The spirit which stops rainfall.\n* [[Hoji (Japanese mythology)|Hoji]] \u2013 The wicked spirit of Tamamo-no-Mae.\n* [[Hone-onna]] \u2013 The [[Skeleton (undead)|skeleton]]-woman.\n* [[Fenghuang|H\u014d-\u014d]] \u2013 The legendary [[Fenghuang]] bird of China.\n* [[Kitsune#Hoshi no tama (\u307b\u3057\u306e\u305f\u307e)|Hoshi-no-Tama]] \u2013 A ball guarded by a Kitsune (fox) which can give the one who obtains it power to force the Kitsune to help them. It is said to hold some reserves of the Kitsune's power.\n* [[H\u014ds\u014dshi]] \u2013 A ritual exorcist.\n* [[Hotoke]] \u2013 A deceased person.\n* [[Hyakki Yak\u014d]] \u2013 The [[demon]]s' night parade.\n* [[Hy\u014dsube]] \u2013 A kind of hair-covered [[Kappa (folklore)|Kappa]].\n\n==I==\n* [[Ibaraki-doji]] \u2013 Offspring of an oni.\n* [[Tsukumogami#Types of tsukumogami|Ichiren-Bozu]] \u2013 Animated prayer beads.\n* [[Ikiry\u014d]] \u2013 Essentially a living [[ghost]], as it is a living person's soul outside of their body.\n* [[Ikuchi]] \u2013 A sea-serpent that travels over boats in an arc while dripping oil.\n* [[Inugami]] \u2013 A dog-spirit created, worshipped, and employed by a family via sorcery.\n* [[Inugami Gyoubu]] \u2013 A type of bake-danuki.\n* [[Isonade]] \u2013 A [[fish]]-like [[sea monster]] with a barb-covered tail.\n* [[Issie]] \u2013 A lake monster.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Itsumade]] \u2013 A fire-breathing birdlike monster.\n* [[Ittan-momen]] \u2013 A possessed roll of cotton that attempts to smother people by wrapping itself around their faces.\n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|Iyaya]] \u2013 A woman whose face is reflected as an old man.\n\n==J==\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Jami]] \u2013 A wicked mountain spirit.\n* [[Janjanbi]] \u2013 A soul in the form of a ball of fire, named for the sound it makes.\n* [[Jibakurei]] \u2013 A spirit that protects a specific place.\n* [[Jikininki]] \u2013 [[Ghost]]s that eat human corpses. \n* [[Jinmenju]] \u2013 A tree with human-faced fruits.\n* [[Jinmenken]] - A human-faced dog.\n* [[Namazu (Japanese mythology)|Jishin-namazu]] \u2013 The giant [[catfish]] that causes earthquakes and [[tsunami]]. It was blamed during the [[Ansei]] quake & tsunami.\n* [[Jor\u014dgumo]] \u2013 A [[spider]]-woman.\n* [[Tsukumogami#Types of tsukumogami|Jatai]] \u2013 Animated folding screen cloth.\n* [[Jubokko]] \u2013 A [[vampire|vampiric]] tree.\n\n==K==\n* {{Nihongo|[[Kahaku]]|\u6cb3\u4f2f}} \u2013 Another name for a [[Kappa (folklore)|Kappa]].\n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|Kakurezato]]\n* [[Kamaitachi]] \u2013 The slashing sickle-clawed [[weasel]] that haunts the mountains.\n* [[Kamikiri (haircutting)|Kamikiri]] - A yokai that secretly cut people's hair. \n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Kambariny\u016bd\u014d]] \u2013 A monk spirit that spies on people using the toilet.\n* Kameosa \u2013 A possessed sake jar.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Kanedama]] \u2013 A spirit that carries money.\n* [[Kappa (folklore)|Kappa]] \u2013 A famous water monster with a water-filled head and a love of cucumbers.\n* [[Tengu#Great and small demons|Karasu-tengu]] \u2013 Crow demon.\n* [[Karura]]  \u2013 Anthropomorphic eagle akin to the Hindu [[Garuda]].\n* [[Kasa-obake]] \u2013 A possessed paper umbrella monster.\n* [[Kasha folklore|Kasha]] \u2013 A cat-like demon that descends from the sky and carries away corpses.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Katawaguruma]] \u2013 A type of [[Wanyudo]], with an anguished woman instead of a monk's head in a burning wheel.\n* [[Otter#Japanese folklore|Kawauso]] \u2013 River otters.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Kawaakago]] \u2013 A river spirit that pretends to be a crying baby.\n* [[Kechibi]] \u2013 Fireballs with human faces inside.\n* [[Kene\u014d]] \u2013 An old man seated in the underworld who weighs the clothes given to him by [[Datsue-ba]].\n* [[Keukegen]] \u2013 A small dog-like creature covered entirely in long hair.\n* [[Kijimuna]] \u2013 A tree sprite from Okinawa.\n* [[Qilin|Kirin]] \u2013 The Japanese version of the Qilin of China, which is part [[dragon]] and part [[deer]] with antlers, fish scales and an ox's tail. Said to be a protective creature and the guardian of the metal element.\n* [[Kitsune]] \u2013 A [[fox]] spirit.\n* [[Kitsunebi]] \u2013 Flames created by the Kitsune.\n* [[Kitsune no yomeiri]] - Ghost lights\n* [[Kiyohime]] \u2013 A woman who transformed into a [[Snake|serpent]] [[demon]] out of the rage of unrequited love.\n* [[Kodama (spirit)|Kodama]] \u2013 A spirit that lives in a tree.\n* [[Ubume|Kokakuch\u014d]] \u2013 The ''Ubume'' bird.\n* [[Komainu]] \u2013 The pair of [[lion]]-dogs that guard the entrances of temples.\n* [[Konaki-jiji]] \u2013 This yokai disguises itself as an abandoned baby then cries until someone picks it up.\n* [[Tengu#Great and small demons|Konoha-tengu]] \u2013 A bird-like ''[[Tengu]]''.\n* [[Koromodako]] \u2013 An octopus-like Yokai that lives in the waters bordering Kyoto and Fukui.\n* [[Koro-pok-guru|Koropokkuru]] \u2013 A little person from [[Ainu people|Ainu]] folklore.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Kosenj\u014dbi]] \u2013 Fireballs that float over former battlefields.\n* [[Kosode-no-te]] \u2013 A possessed [[kosode]].\n* [[Kubikajiri]] \u2013 Female corpse-chewing graveyard spirit.\n* [[Kuchisake-onna]] \u2013 The slit-mouthed woman.\n* [[Kuda-gitsune]] \u2013 A small [[fox]]-like animal used in sorcery.\n* [[Kudan (y\u014dkai)|Kudan]] \u2013 A cow with a human face.\n* [[Kyonsh\u012b]] \u2013 The Japanese version of the Chinese hopping vampire, known as \"[[jiangshi]]\".\n* Kumo Y\u014dkai \u2013 A Japanese spider demon.\n* Kunekune - A tall, slender strip of paper sheet that wiggles on rice or barley fields during hot summer. \n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|Ky\u014dkotsu]] \u2013 A skeletal figure that emerges from a well.\n* [[Gazu Hyakki Tsurezure Bukuro#Second Volume|Ky\u014drinrin]] \u2013 Possessed scrolls or papers.\n\n==M==\n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi|Mekurabe]] \u2013 The multiplying skulls that menaced [[Taira no Kiyomori]] in his courtyard.\n* [[Menreiki]] - A spirit composed of Gigaku masks.\n* [[Miage-ny\u016bd\u014d]] \u2013 A spirit that grows as fast as you can look up at it.\n* [[Mikaribaba]] \u2013 A one-eyed old woman.\n* [[Mikoshi-ny\u016bd\u014d]] \u2013 A bald [[goblin]] with an extending neck. \n* [[Misaki]] \u2013 High-ranking divine spirits.\n* [[Mizuchi]] \u2013 A dangerous water [[dragon]].\n* [[Mokumokuren]] \u2013 A swarm of eyes that appear on a paper sliding door in an old building.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Momonj\u012b]] - AN old-man who is waiting for travelers at every fork in the road.\n* [[Y\u014dkai|Mononoke]] \u2013 Any mischievous and troublesome creature/entity of uncertain origin.\n* Morinji-no-kama \u2013 Another name for ''Bunbuku Chagama'', the ''[[bake-danuki]]'' teakettle.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|M\u014dry\u014d]] \u2013 A general term for various water demons that eat corpses.\n* [[Mujina]] \u2013 A shapeshifting [[badger]].\n* [[My\u014dbu#Legends connecting kitsune to the title my\u014dbu|My\u014dbu]] \u2013 A title sometimes given to a [[fox]].\n\n==N==\n* [[Namahage]] \u2013 A ritual-disciplinary [[demon]] from the [[Oga Peninsula]].\n* [[Namazu (Japanese mythology)|Namazu]] \u2013 A giant [[catfish]] that causes earthquakes.\n* [[Nekomata]] \u2013 A cat yokai. \n* [[Ningen (folklore)|Ningen]] - An enormous white sea creature with humanoid features. \n* [[Ningyo]] \u2013 A fish person or \"[[mermaid]]\".\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Nobusuma]] \u2013 A flying squirrel-like monster (possibly inspired by the [[Indian giant flying squirrel]]).\n* [[Gazu Hyakki Yagy\u014d|Noderab\u014d]] \u2013 Strange creatures that stand near a temple bell.\n* [[Noppera-b\u014d]] \u2013 A faceless [[ghost]].\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Nozuchi]] \u2013 A fat snake-like creature.\n* [[Yako (fox)|Nogitsune]] \u2013 A dangerous [[kitsune]].\n* [[Nue]] \u2013 A monster with the head of a [[monkey]], the body of a [[raccoon dog]], the legs of a [[tiger]], and a [[snake]]-headed tail. It plagued the emperor with nightmares in the ''[[The Tale of the Heike|Heike Monogatari]]''. \n* [[Nukekubi]] \u2013 A vicious humanlike monster whose head detaches from its body, often confused with the ''[[Rokurokubi]]''.\n* [[Nuppeppo]] \u2013 An animated lump of decaying human flesh.\n* [[Nure-onna]] \u2013 A female [[snake]]-like monster who appears on the shore.\n* [[Nuribotoke]] \u2013 An animated corpse with blackened flesh and dangling eyeballs.\n* [[Nurikabe (folklore)|Nurikabe]] \u2013 A ghostly wall that traps a traveler at night.\n* [[Nurarihyon]] \u2013 A strange character who sneaks into houses on busy evenings.\n* [[Ny\u016bd\u014d-b\u014dzu]] \u2013 A [[yokai]] that grows larger the further one looks up.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#First Volume|Ny\u016bnaisuzume]]- [[Old World sparrow|Sparrows]] that flew from the mouth of exiled poet Fujiwara-no Sanekata.\n\n==O==\n* [[Obake]] (or ''Bakemono'') \u2013 Shapeshifting spirits.\n* Obariyon \u2013 [[Y\u014dkai]] which rides piggyback on a human victim and becomes unbearably heavy.\n* [[Oboroguruma]] \u2013 An oxen cart with a face in its carriage.\n* [[Yotsuya Kaidan|Oiwa]] \u2013 The [[ghost]] of a woman with a distorted face who was murdered by her husband. One of the most famous [[onry\u014d]].\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|\u014ckaburo]] -  Cross-dressing [[y\u014dkai]]\n* [[Ehon Hyaku Monogatari|\u014cgama]] \u2013 A giant [[toad]] which breathes rainbow-like smoke and wields a giant spear against whoever attacks it.\n* [[Japanese wolf#Culture|\u014ckami]] \u2013 A powerful [[wolf]] spirit that either takes your life or protects it depending on the actions one does in his or her life.\n* [[Banch\u014d Sarayashiki|Okiku]] \u2013 The plate-counting [[ghost]] of a servant girl.\n* [[\u014ckubi]] \u2013 The huge face of a woman which appears in the sky.\n* [[Okuri-inu]] \u2013 A spectral [[dog]] which follows lone travelers, attacking them if they trip. Similar to the [[Black dog (ghost)|Black dog]] of English folklore.\n* [[\u014cmagatoki]] \u2013 Dusk.\n* [[\u014cmukade]] \u2013 A giant, human-eating [[centipede]] that lives in the mountains.\n* [[Oni (folklore)|Oni]] \u2013 The classic Japanese [[demon]]. It is an [[ogre]]-like creature which often has horns.\n** [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|Oni of Rashomon]]\n* [[Onibaba (folklore)|Onibaba]] \u2013 The [[demon]]ic [[hag]] of [[Adachigahara]].\n* [[Onibi]] \u2013 A demonic flame which can suck out life if people come too near.\n* [[Onihitokuchi]] \u2013 One-eyed [[oni]] that kills and eat humans.\n* [[Onikuma]] \u2013 Bear [[y\u014dkai]].\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Onmoraki]] \u2013 A [[bird]]-demon created from the spirits of freshly dead corpses.\n* [[\u014cny\u016bd\u014d]] \u2013 Wastebasket taxon for all 'priestly' demons.\n* [[Onry\u014d]] \u2013 A vengeful [[ghost]] formed from powerful feelings like [[Rage (emotion)|rage]] or [[Sorrow (emotion)|sorrow]].\n* [[Otoroshi]] \u2013 A hairy creature that perches on the torii gates to shrines and temples.\n* [[Onmyoji]] \u2013 A human who has powers like a [[y\u014dkai]]'s.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#First Volume|Osakabe]] \u2013 An old woman [[y\u014dkai]] which resides in [[Himeji Castle]] and who can read and manipulate hearts.\n\n==R==\n* [[Raijin]] \u2013 The God of Thunder.\n* [[Raij\u016b]] \u2013 A beast that falls to earth in a lightning bolt.\n* [[R\u014djinbi]] \u2013 A ghostly fire that appears with an old person.\n* [[Rokurokubi]] \u2013 A person, usually female, whose neck can stretch indefinitely.\n* [[Japanese dragon|Ryuu]] \u2013 The Japanese [[dragon]].\n\n==S==\n* [[Sha Wujing|Sa Goj\u014d]] \u2013 The water-monster Sha Wujing from ''[[Journey to the West]]'', often interpreted in Japan as a [[Kappa (folklore)|kappa]].\n*Sagari - Hanging horse head. \n* [[Samebito]] \u2013 A [[shark]]-man from the undersea [[Ry\u016bg\u016b-j\u014d|Dragon Palace]].\n* [[Sankai]] \u2013 An amorphous afterbirth spirit.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#First Volume|Sansei]] \u2013 A humanoid with a single leg twisted backwards.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Sarakazoe]] - A type of [[onibi]] that appears as a counting plate.\n* [[Satori (folklore)|Satori]] \u2013 An [[ape]]-like creature that can read one's thoughts.\n* [[Sazae-oni]] \u2013 A turban [[snail]] that turns into a woman.\n* [[Sessh\u014d-seki]] \u2013 The poisonous \"killing stones\" which Tamamo-no-Mae transformed into.\n* [[Azure Dragon|Seiry\u016b]] \u2013 Japanese version of the Chinese [[Azure Dragon]].\n* [[Shachihoko]] \u2013 A [[tiger]]-headed [[fish]] whose image is often used in architecture.\n* [[Shibaemon-tanuki]] \u2013 A [[bake-danuki]] from [[Awaji Island]].\n* [[Shichinin misaki]] \u2013 A group of seven ghosts who sicken the living.\n* [[Shidaidaka]] \u2013 A humanoid [[yokai]] that appears above roads.\n* [[Shikigami]] \u2013 A spirit summoned to do the bidding of an [[Onmy\u014dji]].\n* [[Shikome]] \u2013 Wild women sent by [[Izanami]] to harm [[Izanagi]].\n* [[Shinigami]] \u2013 The Japanese [[Death (personification)|Grim Reaper]].\n* [[Shiranui (Optical phenomenon)|Shiranui]] \u2013 A mysterious flame seen over the seas in [[Kumamoto Prefecture]].\n* [[Shirime]] (\u5c3b\u76ee) \u2013 An apparition in the shape of a man having an eye in the place of his anus.\n* [[Shir\u014dneri]] \u2013 Possessed [[mosquito]] nettings or dust clothes.\n* [[Shiry\u014d]] \u2013 The souls of the dead, the opposite of [[ikiryo]].\n* [[Shisa]] \u2013 The Okinawan version of the ''Shishi''.\n* [[Imperial guardian lion|Shishi]] \u2013 The paired [[lion]]-dogs that guard the entrances of temples.\n* [[Sh\u014dj\u014d]] \u2013 Red-haired sea [[Sprite (creature)|sprite]]s who love alcohol.\n* [[Gazu Hyakki Yagy\u014d|Sh\u014dkera]] \u2013 A creature which peeks in through the skylight of an old house.\n* [[S\u014dj\u014db\u014d]] \u2013 The famous ''Daitengu'' of [[Mount Kurama]].\n* Suiko \u2013 Another name for the [[Kappa (folklore)|kappa]].\n* [[Sun Wukong|Son Gok\u016b]] \u2013 The [[monkey]] king Sun Wukong from [[Journey to the West|''Journey to the West''.]]\n* Sunakake Baba \u2013 A witch who uses sand.\n* [[Sunekosuri]] \u2013 A dog-like [[yokai]] that rubs up against people's legs when it is raining.\n*Susanoo - the storm god, younger brother of the sun goddess Amaterasu.\n* [[Shuten-doji]] \u2013  [[Oni]]\n* [[Vermilion Bird|Suzaku]] \u2013 The Japanese version of the Chinese [[Vermilion Bird]].\n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|Suzuri-no-tamashii]] - Inkstone spirit.\n\n==T==\n*[[Takaonna|Taka-onna]] \u2013 A female monster that can stretch its waist to peer inside buildings.\n* [[Tamamo-no-Mae]] \u2013 A wicked nine-tailed [[fox]] who appeared as a courtesan.\n* [[Bake-danuki|Tanuki]] \u2013 A shape-shifting [[Japanese raccoon dog]].\n* [[Teke Teke]] \u2013 A vengeful spirit of a school girl, with a half upper torso body, who goes around killing people by slicing them in half with a scythe, mimicking her own disfigurement.\n* [[Ten (folklore)|Ten]] \u2013 A shapeshifting mischievous [[weasel]].  \n* [[Tengu]] \u2013 A wise [[demon]] with two variants: a red man with a long nose, or a bird-like [[demon]].\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Tenj\u014dkudari]] - A female [[yokai]] that crawls on the ceiling. \n* [[Tenka (kaika)]] - Ghost lights\n* [[Tenko (fox)]] - Divine beast\n* [[Tennin]] \u2013 A heavenly being.\n* [[Tenome|Te-no-me]] \u2013 A ghost of a blind man with his eyes on his hands.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#First Volume|Teratsutsuki]] - The [[onry\u014d]] of a man who lived in the 6th century CE.\n* [[Gazu Hyakki Yagy\u014d|Tesso]] \u2013 A priest who was snubbed by the emperor and became a swarm of rats which laid waste to a rival temple.\n* [[T\u014dfu-koz\u014d]] \u2013 A yokai that appears as a young boy carrying a plate of tofu.\n* [[Tsuchigumo]] \u2013 A clan of spider-like [[yokai]].\n* [[Tsuchinoko]] \u2013 A legendary [[Snake|serpentine]] monster. It is now a cryptid resembling a fat [[snake]].\n* Tsukinowaguma \u2013 A legendary bear.<ref>Clarissa Pinkola Est\u00e9s, ''Women who Run with the Wolves'' (1996), Ch. 12.</ref>\n* [[Tsukuyomi]] \u2013 A moon god.\n* [[Tsukumogami]] \u2013 An animated [[tea caddy]] that [[Matsunaga Hisahide]] used to bargain a peace with [[Oda Nobunaga]]. It is now understood to mean any 100-year-old inanimate object that has come to life.\n* [[Tsurube-otoshi]] \u2013 A monster that drops out of the tops of trees.\n\n==U==\n* [[Ubume]] \u2013 The spirit of a woman who died in childbirth.\n* Uma-no-ashi \u2013 A horse's leg which dangles from a tree and kicks passersby.\n* [[Umib\u014dzu]] \u2013 A giant monster appearing on the surface of the sea.\n* Umi-ny\u014db\u014d \u2013 A female sea monster who steals fish.\n* [[Ungaiky\u014d]] \u2013 A possessed mirror.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#First Volume|Ushi-no-tokimairi]] \u2013 A curse done at the ox hour (between 1 and 3 in the morning) by a [[black magic]] user, with various effects.\n* [[Ushi-oni]] \u2013 A name given to an assortment of [[ox]]-headed monsters.\n* [[Kudan (y\u014dkai)#Ushi-onna|Ushi-onna]] \u2013 A kimono-clad woman with a cow head.\n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|Ushirogami]] - A one-eyed, footless spirit.\n* [[Uwan]] \u2013 A spirit named for the sound it shouts when surprising people.\n\n==W==\n* [[Gazu Hyakki Yagy\u014d|Waira]] \u2013 A large beast that lurks in the mountains, about which little is known.\n* [[Wani (dragon)|Wani]] \u2013 A water monster comparable to an [[alligator]] or [[crocodile]]. A related word has been applied to the [[saltwater crocodile]].\n* [[Wany\u016bd\u014d]] \u2013 A flaming wheel with a man's head in the center, that sucks out the soul of anyone who sees it.\n\n==Y==\n* [[Yad\u014dkai]] \u2013 Monks who have turned to mischief.\n* [[Yama-biko]] \u2013 Small creatures that create echoes.\n* [[Yamajijii]] \u2013 An old man with one eye and one leg.\n* [[Yamako]] \u2013 An [[ape]]like occasionally cannibalistic creature that can read minds. \n* [[Gazu Hyakki Tsurezure Bukuro|Yamaoroshi]] \u2013 A possessed vegetable [[grater]], almost porcupine-like in appearance.\n* [[Yamata no Orochi]] \u2013 The eight-headed dragon/[[snake|serpent]] monster slain by the god Susanoo.\n* [[wiktionary:\u5c71\u72ac|Yama-inu]] \u2013 A dog-like mountain spirit, that may appear to travelers on mountain roads; may be friendly, or may attack and kill the traveler, depending on the tale (also see the [[Japanese wolf]]).\n* [[Yama-uba]] \u2013 A [[crone]]-like y\u014dkai.\n* [[Yashima no Hage-tanuki]] \u2013 A [[bake-danuki]] that protects the [[Taira clan]].\n* [[Three-legged bird|Yatagarasu]] \u2013 The three-legged [[crow]] of Amaterasu.\n* [[Yato-no-kami]] \u2013 Deadly [[Snake]] gods which infested a field.\n* [[Yobuko]] \u2013 A mountain-dwelling spirit.\n* [[Y\u014dkai]]/Youkai \u2013 A class of supernatural monsters, spirits, and demons in Japanese folklore. They can also be called [[ayakashi (y\u014dkai)|ayakashi]] (\u5996?), [[mononoke]] (\u7269\u306e\u602a?), or mamono (\u9b54\u7269?).\n* [[Yomotsu-shikome]] \u2013 The [[hag]]s of the underworld.\n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|Yonakinoishi]]\n* [[Y\u014dsei]] \u2013 The Japanese word for \"[[fairy]]\".\n* [[Yosuzume]] \u2013 A mysterious bird that sings at night, sometimes indicating that the [[okuri-inu]] is near.\n* [[Yuki-onna]] \u2013 The snow woman.\n* [[Yurei]] \u2013 Ghosts in a more Western sense.\n\n==Z==\n* [[Zashiki-warashi]] \u2013 A protective childlike house spirit.\n* [[Zennyo Ry\u016b\u014d]] \u2013 A rain-making dragon.\n* [[Tsukumogami#Types of tsukumogami|Zorigami]] \u2013 An animated clock.\n* [[Zuijin]] \u2013 A tutelary spirit.\n* [[Zunbera-b\u014d]] \u2013 Another name for the [[Noppera-b\u014d]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Japanese mythology]]\n* [[Kwaidan|Kaidan]]\n{{Portal bar|Asia|Japan|Mythology|Religion}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.onmarkproductions.com/html/buddhism.shtml Photo Dictionary of Japanese Buddhist and Shinto Deities]\n* [https://hyakumonogatari.com \u767e\u7269\u8a9e\u602a\u8ac7\u4f1a Hyakumonogatari Kaidankai | Translated Japanese Ghost Stories and Tales of the Weird and the Strange], a blog by Mizuki Shigeru \n* [http://en.gigazine.net/news/20081230_youkai_bronze/ 133 Yokai Statues on Mizuki Shigeru Road]\n\n{{Japanese folklore long}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese legendary creatures| ]]\n[[Category:Y\u014dkai| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of legendary creatures|Japan]]\n[[Category:Mythological dogs|Japan]]\n[[Category:Japanese culture-related lists|Legendary creatures from Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2017}}\n{{jmyth infobox}}\nThe following is a list of [[demons]], [[ghosts]], [[kami]], [[obake]], [[y\u014dkai]], [[y\u016brei]] and other [[legendary creatures]] that are notable in [[Japanese folklore]] and [[Japanese mythology|mythology]].\n\n{{compact ToC|num=yes}}\n\n==A==\n* [[Abumi-guchi]] \u2013 A furry creature formed from the stirrup of a mounted military commander who worked for [[Yamata no Orochi]].\n* [[Abura-akago]] \u2013 An infant [[ghost]] who licks the oil out of [[Traditional lighting equipment of Japan|''andon'']] lamps.\n* [[Abura-sumashi]] \u2013 A spirit with a large head who lives on a mountain pass in [[Kumamoto Prefecture]].\n*Abura-tokkuri - A possessed pot.\n* [[Akabeko]] \u2013 A red [[cattle|cow]] involved in the construction of Enz\u014d-ji in [[Yanaizu, Fukushima]].\n* [[Akamanto]] - A ghost in red mantle that offers either red or blue toilet paper roll in toilets. \n* [[Akaname]] \u2013 A spirit who licks off filth in untidy bathrooms.\n* [[Akashita]] \u2013 A creature that looms in a black cloud over a floodgate.\n* [[Akateko (folklore)|Akateko]] \u2013 A red hand dangling out of a tree.\n* [[Akkorokamui]] \u2013 An [[Ainu people|Ainu]] monster resembling a [[fish]] or [[octopus]].\n* [[Akurojin-no-hi]] \u2013 A ghostly fire from [[Mie Prefecture]].\n* [[Akub\u014dzu]] \u2013Akub\u014dzu, live in the ashes of hearths, they are from [[Akita Prefecture|Akita]] and [[Iwate Prefecture|Iwate]].\n* [[Amabie]] \u2013 A Japanese mermaid yokai.\n* [[Amaburakosagi]] \u2013 A ritual-disciplinary [[demon]] from [[Shikoku]].\n* [[Amamehagi]] \u2013 A ritual-disciplinary [[demon]] from [[Hokuriku region|Hokuriku]].\n* [[Amanojaku]] \u2013 A small [[demon]] that instigates people into wickedness.\n* [[Amanozako]] \u2013 A monstrous goddess mentioned in the [[Kujiki]].\n* [[Amazake-babaa]] \u2013 An old woman who asks for sweet sake and brings disease.\n* [[Amefurikoz\u014d]] \u2013 A little boy spirit who plays in the rain.\n* [[Amemasu]] \u2013 An [[Ainu people|Ainu]] creature resembling a [[fish]] or [[whale]].\n* [[Ameonna]] \u2013 A rain-making female spirit.\n* [[Amikiri]] \u2013 A net-cutting bird-headed, crustacean-armed, snake-bodied spirit.\n* [[Amor\u014dnagu]] \u2013 A ''Tennyo'' from the island of Amami \u014cshima.\n* [[Amaterasu]] \u2013 A sun goddess.\n* [[Anmo]] \u2013 A ritual-disciplinary [[demon]] from [[Iwate Prefecture]].\n* [[Aoandon]] \u2013 The demonic spirit which arises from an ''andon'' lamp at the end of a ''Hyakumonogatari Kaidankai''.\n* [[Aob\u014dzu]] \u2013 The blue monk who kidnaps children.\n* [[Aony\u014db\u014d]] \u2013 A female [[ghost]] who lurks in an abandoned imperial palace.\n* [[Aosaginohi]] \u2013 A luminescent [[heron]].\n* [[Arikura-no-baba]] \u2013 An old woman with magical powers.\n* [[Ashimagari]] \u2013 A spirit which entangles the legs of travelers.\n* [[Ashinagatenaga]] \u2013 A pair of characters, one with long legs and the other with long arms.\n* [[Ayakashi (y\u014dkai)]] \u2013 A phenomenon considered to be the [[funayurei]].\n* [[Azukiarai]] (or ''Azukitogi'') \u2013 A spirit that washes ''azuki'' beans.\n\n==B==\n* [[Bake-kujira]] \u2013 A ghostly whale skeleton that drifts along the coastline of [[Shimane Prefecture]].\n* [[Bakeneko]] \u2013 A shape-shifting cat.\n* [[Bakez\u014dri]] \u2013 A [[z\u014dri]] straw sandal spirit.\n* [[Baku (spirit)]] \u2013 Supernatural beings that devour dreams and nightmares.\n* [[Basan]] \u2013 A large fire-breathing [[chicken]] monster.\n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|Bash\u014dnosei]] - Banana tree spirit\n* [[Betobeto-san]] \u2013 Invisible spirit which follows people at night, making the sound of footsteps.\n* [[Binb\u014dgami]] \u2013 The spirit of poverty.\n* [[Tsukumogami#Types of tsukumogami|Biwa-bokuboku]] \u2013 Animated [[biwa]] lute.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume - \u660e|Buruburu]] \u2013 A spirit which clings to people inducing cowardice and shivers. \n* [[White Tiger (Chinese astronomy)|Byakko]] \u2013 Japanese version of the Chinese [[White Tiger (Chinese astronomy)|White Tiger]].\n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|By\u014dbunozoki]] - [[Tsukumogami]] that emerges from by\u014dbu to peep on people. \n\n==C==\n* [[Ch\u014dchinobake]] \u2013 A possessed [[Japanese lantern|ch\u014dchin lantern]].\n* [[Ch\u014dchinbi]] \u2013 Demonic flames which appear in footpaths between rice-fields.\n\n==D==\n* [[Daidarabotchi]] \u2013 A [[Giant (mythology)|giant]] responsible for creating the geographical features of Japan.\n* [[Tengu#Great and small demons|Daitengu]] \u2013 The most powerful ''[[tengu]]'', each of whom lives on a separate mountain.\n* [[Danzaburou-danuki]] \u2013 a [[bake-danuki]] from [[Sado Island]].\n* [[Datsue-ba]] \u2013 An old woman in the Underworld who removes clothes (or skin if unclothed) of the dead.\n* [[Dodomeki]] \u2013 A hundred-eyed demon.\n* [[D\u014dnotsura]] \u2013 A headless humanlike y\u014dkai with its face on its torso.\n\n==E==\n* [[Enenra]] \u2013 A monster made of smoke.\n* [[Kappa (folklore)|Enk\u014d]] \u2013 [[Kappa (folklore)|Kappa]] of [[Shikoku]] and western [[Honsh\u016b]].\n\n==F==\n* [[F\u016bjin]] \u2013 The wind god.\n* [[F\u016bri]] \u2013 A monkey-like yokai.\n* [[Funay\u016brei]] \u2013 [[Ghost]]s of people who died at sea.\n* [[Furaribi]] \u2013 A creature engulfed in flames that flies aimlessly.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Furutsubaki-no-rei]] \u2013 A soul-sucking plant.\n* [[Tsukumogami#Types of tsukumogami|Furu-utsubo]] \u2013 A beloved quiver of slain archers. \n* [[Futakuchi-onna]] \u2013 The two-mouthed woman.\n\n==G==\n* [[Gazu Hyakki Yagy\u014d|Gagoze]] \u2013 A demon who attacked young priests at Gang\u014d-ji temple.\n* [[Preta|Gaki]] \u2013 Starving ghosts of especially greedy people.\n* [[Gashadokuro]] \u2013 A giant [[Skeleton (undead)|skeleton]] that is the spirit of the unburied dead. Also known as ''[[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Gaikotsu]]''.\n* [[Black Tortoise|Genbu]] \u2013 Japanese version of the Chinese [[Black Tortoise]].\n* [[Gory\u014d]] \u2013 The [[vengeful spirit]]s of the dead.\n* [[Ox-Head and Horse-Face|Gozu and Mezu]] \u2013 Underworld guards.\n* [[Tengu#Great and small demons|Guhin]] \u2013 Another name for tengu.\n* [[Gy\u016bki]] \u2013 Another name for Ushi-oni.\n\n==H==\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Hakanohi]] \u2013 A fire which lights on graves.\n* Hakuja no Myojin<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TSgwAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA170&lpg=PA170&dq=Hakuja+no+Myojin#v=onepage&q=Hakuja+no+Myojin&f=false|title=The Oriental Economic Review|author=|date=14 July 2018|publisher=Oriental Information Agency|via=Google Books}}</ref> \u2013 A white serpent God.\n* [[Hachishaku-sama]] \u2013 A woman that is 8 feet tall and famous by kidnapping children.\n* [[Hakutaku]] \u2013 A beast which handed down knowledge on harmful spirits.\n* [[Hanako-san]] \u2013 A spirit of a young World War II-era girl who inhabits and haunts school restrooms.\n* [[Hannya]] \u2013 A noh mask representing a jealous female [[demon]].\n*Haradashi \u2013 A creature with a giant face on its stomach.\n* [[Harionago]] \u2013 A woman with a thorn-like barb on the tip of each strand of her hair.\n* [[Hashihime]] \u2013 A woman-turned-spirit associated with the bridge at Uji.\n* [[Heikegani]] \u2013 [[Crab]]s with human-faced shells. They are the spirits of the warriors killed in the [[Battle of Dan-no-ura]].\n* [[Hibagon]] \u2013 The Japanese version of the [[Bigfoot]] or the [[Yeti]].\n* [[Hiderigami]] \u2013 The spirit of drought.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Hihi]] \u2013 A baboon-like Chinese yokai.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Hikeshibaba]] \u2013 An old woman who extinguishes lanterns.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Hinode]] \u2013 The Sunrise.\n* [[Hitodama]] \u2013 A fireball [[ghost]] that appears when someone dies, signifying the dead person's spirit.\n* [[Hitotsume-koz\u014d]] \u2013 A one-eyed child spirit.\n* [[Hitotsume-ny\u016bd\u014d]] \u2013 A one-eyed monk spirit.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Hiyorib\u014d]] \u2013 The spirit which stops rainfall.\n* [[Hoji (Japanese mythology)|Hoji]] \u2013 The wicked spirit of Tamamo-no-Mae.\n* [[Hone-onna]] \u2013 The [[Skeleton (undead)|skeleton]]-woman.\n* [[Fenghuang|H\u014d-\u014d]] \u2013 The legendary [[Fenghuang]] bird of China.\n* [[Kitsune#Hoshi no tama (\u307b\u3057\u306e\u305f\u307e)|Hoshi-no-Tama]] \u2013 A ball guarded by a Kitsune (fox) which can give the one who obtains it power to force the Kitsune to help them. It is said to hold some reserves of the Kitsune's power.\n* [[H\u014ds\u014dshi]] \u2013 A ritual exorcist.\n* [[Hotoke]] \u2013 A deceased person.\n* [[Hyakki Yak\u014d]] \u2013 The [[demon]]s' night parade.\n* [[Hy\u014dsube]] \u2013 A kind of hair-covered [[Kappa (folklore)|Kappa]].\n\n==I==\n* [[Ibaraki-doji]] \u2013 Offspring of an oni.\n* [[Tsukumogami#Types of tsukumogami|Ichiren-Bozu]] \u2013 Animated prayer beads.\n* [[Ikiry\u014d]] \u2013 Essentially a living [[ghost]], as it is a living person's soul outside of their body.\n* [[Ikuchi]] \u2013 A sea-serpent that travels over boats in an arc while dripping oil.\n* [[Inugami]] \u2013 A dog-spirit created, worshipped, and employed by a family via sorcery.\n* [[Inugami Gyoubu]] \u2013 A type of bake-danuki.\n* [[Isonade]] \u2013 A [[fish]]-like [[sea monster]] with a barb-covered tail.\n* [[Issie]] \u2013 A lake monster.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Itsumade]] \u2013 A fire-breathing birdlike monster.\n* [[Ittan-momen]] \u2013 A possessed roll of cotton that attempts to smother people by wrapping itself around their faces.\n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|Iyaya]] \u2013 A woman whose face is reflected as an old man.\n\n==J==\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Jami]] \u2013 A wicked mountain spirit.\n* [[Janjanbi]] \u2013 A soul in the form of a ball of fire, named for the sound it makes.\n* [[Jibakurei]] \u2013 A spirit that protects a specific place.\n* [[Jikininki]] \u2013 [[Ghost]]s that eat human corpses. \n* [[Jinmenju]] \u2013 A tree with human-faced fruits.\n* [[Jinmenken]] - A human-faced dog.\n* [[Namazu (Japanese mythology)|Jishin-namazu]] \u2013 The giant [[catfish]] that causes earthquakes and [[tsunami]]. It was blamed during the [[Ansei]] quake & tsunami.\n* [[Jor\u014dgumo]] \u2013 A [[spider]]-woman.\n* [[Tsukumogami#Types of tsukumogami|Jatai]] \u2013 Animated folding screen cloth.\n* [[Jubokko]] \u2013 A [[vampire|vampiric]] tree.\n\n==K==\n* {{Nihongo|[[Kahaku]]|\u6cb3\u4f2f}} \u2013 Another name for a [[Kappa (folklore)|Kappa]].\n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|Kakurezato]]\n* [[Kamaitachi]] \u2013 The slashing sickle-clawed [[weasel]] that haunts the mountains.\n* [[Kamikiri (haircutting)|Kamikiri]] - A yokai that secretly cut people's hair. \n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Kambariny\u016bd\u014d]] \u2013 A monk spirit that spies on people using the toilet.\n* Kameosa \u2013 A possessed sake jar.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Kanedama]] \u2013 A spirit that carries money.\n* [[Kappa (folklore)|Kappa]] \u2013 A famous water monster with a water-filled head and a love of cucumbers.\n* [[Tengu#Great and small demons|Karasu-tengu]] \u2013 Crow demon.\n* [[Karura]]  \u2013 Anthropomorphic eagle akin to the Hindu [[Garuda]].\n* [[Kasa-obake]] \u2013 A possessed paper umbrella monster.\n* [[Kasha folklore|Kasha]] \u2013 A cat-like demon that descends from the sky and carries away corpses.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Katawaguruma]] \u2013 A type of [[Wanyudo]], with an anguished woman instead of a monk's head in a burning wheel.\n* [[Otter#Japanese folklore|Kawauso]] \u2013 River otters.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Kawaakago]] \u2013 A river spirit that pretends to be a crying baby.\n* [[Kechibi]] \u2013 Fireballs with human faces inside.\n* [[Kene\u014d]] \u2013 An old man seated in the underworld who weighs the clothes given to him by [[Datsue-ba]].\n* [[Keukegen]] \u2013 A small dog-like creature covered entirely in long hair.\n* [[Kijimuna]] \u2013 A tree sprite from Okinawa.\n* [[Qilin|Kirin]] \u2013 The Japanese version of the Qilin of China, which is part [[dragon]] and part [[deer]] with antlers, fish scales and an ox's tail. Said to be a protective creature and the guardian of the metal element.\n* [[Kitsune]] \u2013 A [[fox]] spirit.\n* [[Kitsunebi]] \u2013 Flames created by the Kitsune.\n* [[Kitsune no yomeiri]] - Ghost lights\n* [[Kiyohime]] \u2013 A woman who transformed into a [[Snake|serpent]] [[demon]] out of the rage of unrequited love.\n* [[Kodama (spirit)|Kodama]] \u2013 A spirit that lives in a tree.\n* [[Ubume|Kokakuch\u014d]] \u2013 The ''Ubume'' bird.\n* [[Komainu]] \u2013 The pair of [[lion]]-dogs that guard the entrances of temples.\n* [[Konaki-jiji]] \u2013 This yokai disguises itself as an abandoned baby then cries until someone picks it up.\n* [[Tengu#Great and small demons|Konoha-tengu]] \u2013 A bird-like ''[[Tengu]]''.\n* [[Koromodako]] \u2013 An octopus-like Yokai that lives in the waters bordering Kyoto and Fukui.\n* [[Koro-pok-guru|Koropokkuru]] \u2013 A little person from [[Ainu people|Ainu]] folklore.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Kosenj\u014dbi]] \u2013 Fireballs that float over former battlefields.\n* [[Kosode-no-te]] \u2013 A possessed [[kosode]].\n* [[Kubikajiri]] \u2013 Female corpse-chewing graveyard spirit.\n* [[Kuchisake-onna]] \u2013 The slit-mouthed woman.\n* [[Kuda-gitsune]] \u2013 A small [[fox]]-like animal used in sorcery.\n* [[Kudan (y\u014dkai)|Kudan]] \u2013 A cow with a human face.\n* [[Kyonsh\u012b]] \u2013 The Japanese version of the Chinese hopping vampire, known as \"[[jiangshi]]\".\n* Kumo Y\u014dkai \u2013 A Japanese spider demon.\n* Kunekune - A tall, slender strip of paper sheet that wiggles on rice or barley fields during hot summer. \n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|Ky\u014dkotsu]] \u2013 A skeletal figure that emerges from a well.\n* [[Gazu Hyakki Tsurezure Bukuro#Second Volume|Ky\u014drinrin]] \u2013 Possessed scrolls or papers.\n\n==M==\n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi|Mekurabe]] \u2013 The multiplying skulls that menaced [[Taira no Kiyomori]] in his courtyard.\n* [[Menreiki]] - A spirit composed of Gigaku masks.\n* [[Miage-ny\u016bd\u014d]] \u2013 A spirit that grows as fast as you can look up at it.\n* [[Mikaribaba]] \u2013 A one-eyed old woman.\n* [[Mikoshi-ny\u016bd\u014d]] \u2013 A bald [[goblin]] with an extending neck. \n* [[Misaki]] \u2013 High-ranking divine spirits.\n* [[Mizuchi]] \u2013 A dangerous water [[dragon]].\n* [[Mokumokuren]] \u2013 A swarm of eyes that appear on a paper sliding door in an old building.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Momonj\u012b]] - AN old-man who is waiting for travelers at every fork in the road.\n* [[Y\u014dkai|Mononoke]] \u2013 Any mischievous and troublesome creature/entity of uncertain origin.\n* Morinji-no-kama \u2013 Another name for ''Bunbuku Chagama'', the ''[[bake-danuki]]'' teakettle.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|M\u014dry\u014d]] \u2013 A general term for various water demons that eat corpses.\n* [[Mujina]] \u2013 A shapeshifting [[badger]].\n* [[My\u014dbu#Legends connecting kitsune to the title my\u014dbu|My\u014dbu]] \u2013 A title sometimes given to a [[fox]].\n\n==N==\n* [[Namahage]] \u2013 A ritual-disciplinary [[demon]] from the [[Oga Peninsula]].\n* [[Namazu (Japanese mythology)|Namazu]] \u2013 A giant [[catfish]] that causes earthquakes.\n* [[Nekomata]] \u2013 A cat yokai. \n* [[Ningen (folklore)|Ningen]] - An enormous white sea creature with humanoid features. \n* [[Ningyo]] \u2013 A fish person or \"[[mermaid]]\".\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Nobusuma]] \u2013 A flying squirrel-like monster (possibly inspired by the [[Indian giant flying squirrel]]).\n* [[Gazu Hyakki Yagy\u014d|Noderab\u014d]] \u2013 Strange creatures that stand near a temple bell.\n* [[Noppera-b\u014d]] \u2013 A faceless [[ghost]].\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Nozuchi]] \u2013 A fat snake-like creature.\n* [[Yako (fox)|Nogitsune]] \u2013 A dangerous [[kitsune]].\n* [[Nue]] \u2013 A monster with the head of a [[monkey]], the body of a [[raccoon dog]], the legs of a [[tiger]], and a [[snake]]-headed tail. It plagued the emperor with nightmares in the ''[[The Tale of the Heike|Heike Monogatari]]''. \n* [[Nukekubi]] \u2013 A vicious humanlike monster whose head detaches from its body, often confused with the ''[[Rokurokubi]]''.\n* [[Nuppeppo]] \u2013 An animated lump of decaying human flesh.\n* [[Nure-onna]] \u2013 A female [[snake]]-like monster who appears on the shore.\n* [[Nuribotoke]] \u2013 An animated corpse with blackened flesh and dangling eyeballs.\n* [[Nurikabe (folklore)|Nurikabe]] \u2013 A ghostly wall that traps a traveler at night.\n* [[Nurarihyon]] \u2013 A strange character who sneaks into houses on busy evenings.\n* [[Ny\u016bd\u014d-b\u014dzu]] \u2013 A [[yokai]] that grows larger the further one looks up.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#First Volume|Ny\u016bnaisuzume]]- [[Old World sparrow|Sparrows]] that flew from the mouth of exiled poet Fujiwara-no Sanekata.\n\n==O==\n* [[Obake]] (or ''Bakemono'') \u2013 Shapeshifting spirits.\n* Obariyon \u2013 [[Y\u014dkai]] which rides piggyback on a human victim and becomes unbearably heavy.\n* [[Oboroguruma]] \u2013 An oxen cart with a face in its carriage.\n* [[Yotsuya Kaidan|Oiwa]] \u2013 The [[ghost]] of a woman with a distorted face who was murdered by her husband. One of the most famous [[onry\u014d]].\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|\u014ckaburo]] -  Cross-dressing [[y\u014dkai]]\n* [[Ehon Hyaku Monogatari|\u014cgama]] \u2013 A giant [[toad]] which breathes rainbow-like smoke and wields a giant spear against whoever attacks it.\n* [[Japanese wolf#Culture|\u014ckami]] \u2013 A powerful [[wolf]] spirit that either takes your life or protects it depending on the actions one does in his or her life.\n* [[Banch\u014d Sarayashiki|Okiku]] \u2013 The plate-counting [[ghost]] of a servant girl.\n* [[\u014ckubi]] \u2013 The huge face of a woman which appears in the sky.\n* [[Okuri-inu]] \u2013 A spectral [[dog]] which follows lone travelers, attacking them if they trip. Similar to the [[Black dog (ghost)|Black dog]] of English folklore.\n* [[\u014cmagatoki]] \u2013 Dusk.\n* [[\u014cmukade]] \u2013 A giant, human-eating [[centipede]] that lives in the mountains.\n* [[Oni (folklore)|Oni]] \u2013 The classic Japanese [[demon]]. It is an [[ogre]]-like creature which often has horns.\n** [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|Oni of Rashomon]]\n* [[Onibaba (folklore)|Onibaba]] \u2013 The [[demon]]ic [[hag]] of [[Adachigahara]].\n* [[Onibi]] \u2013 A demonic flame which can suck out life if people come too near.\n* [[Onihitokuchi]] \u2013 One-eyed [[oni]] that kills and eat humans.\n* [[Onikuma]] \u2013 Bear [[y\u014dkai]].\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Onmoraki]] \u2013 A [[bird]]-demon created from the spirits of freshly dead corpses.\n* [[\u014cny\u016bd\u014d]] \u2013 Wastebasket taxon for all 'priestly' demons.\n* [[Onry\u014d]] \u2013 A vengeful [[ghost]] formed from powerful feelings like [[Rage (emotion)|rage]] or [[Sorrow (emotion)|sorrow]].\n* [[Otoroshi]] \u2013 A hairy creature that perches on the torii gates to shrines and temples.\n* [[Onmyoji]] \u2013 A human who has powers like a [[y\u014dkai]]'s.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#First Volume|Osakabe]] \u2013 An old woman [[y\u014dkai]] which resides in [[Himeji Castle]] and who can read and manipulate hearts.\n\n==R==\n* [[Raijin]] \u2013 The God of Thunder.\n* [[Raij\u016b]] \u2013 A beast that falls to earth in a lightning bolt.\n* [[R\u014djinbi]] \u2013 A ghostly fire that appears with an old person.\n* [[Rokurokubi]] \u2013 A person, usually female, whose neck can stretch indefinitely.\n* [[Japanese dragon|Ryuu]] \u2013 The Japanese [[dragon]].\n\n==S==\n* [[Sha Wujing|Sa Goj\u014d]] \u2013 The water-monster Sha Wujing from ''[[Journey to the West]]'', often interpreted in Japan as a [[Kappa (folklore)|kappa]].\n*Sagari - Hanging horse head. \n* [[Samebito]] \u2013 A [[shark]]-man from the undersea [[Ry\u016bg\u016b-j\u014d|Dragon Palace]].\n* [[Sankai]] \u2013 An amorphous afterbirth spirit.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#First Volume|Sansei]] \u2013 A humanoid with a single leg twisted backwards.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Second Volume|Sarakazoe]] - A type of [[onibi]] that appears as a counting plate.\n* [[Satori (folklore)|Satori]] \u2013 An [[ape]]-like creature that can read one's thoughts.\n* [[Sazae-oni]] \u2013 A turban [[snail]] that turns into a woman.\n* [[Sessh\u014d-seki]] \u2013 The poisonous \"killing stones\" which Tamamo-no-Mae transformed into.\n* [[Azure Dragon|Seiry\u016b]] \u2013 Japanese version of the Chinese [[Azure Dragon]].\n* [[Shachihoko]] \u2013 A [[tiger]]-headed [[fish]] whose image is often used in architecture.\n* [[Shibaemon-tanuki]] \u2013 A [[bake-danuki]] from [[Awaji Island]].\n* [[Shichinin misaki]] \u2013 A group of seven ghosts who sicken the living.\n* [[Shidaidaka]] \u2013 A humanoid [[yokai]] that appears above roads.\n* [[Shikigami]] \u2013 A spirit summoned to do the bidding of an [[Onmy\u014dji]].\n* [[Shikome]] \u2013 Wild women sent by [[Izanami]] to harm [[Izanagi]].\n* [[Shinigami]] \u2013 The Japanese [[Death (personification)|Grim Reaper]].\n* [[Shiranui (Optical phenomenon)|Shiranui]] \u2013 A mysterious flame seen over the seas in [[Kumamoto Prefecture]].\n* [[Shirime]] (\u5c3b\u76ee) \u2013 An apparition in the shape of a man having an eye in the place of his anus.\n* [[Shir\u014dneri]] \u2013 Possessed [[mosquito]] nettings or dust clothes.\n* [[Shiry\u014d]] \u2013 The souls of the dead, the opposite of [[ikiryo]].\n* [[Shisa]] \u2013 The Okinawan version of the ''Shishi''.\n* [[Imperial guardian lion|Shishi]] \u2013 The paired [[lion]]-dogs that guard the entrances of temples.\n* [[Sh\u014dj\u014d]] \u2013 Red-haired sea [[Sprite (creature)|sprite]]s who love alcohol.\n* [[Gazu Hyakki Yagy\u014d|Sh\u014dkera]] \u2013 A creature which peeks in through the skylight of an old house.\n* [[S\u014dj\u014db\u014d]] \u2013 The famous ''Daitengu'' of [[Mount Kurama]].\n* Suiko \u2013 Another name for the [[Kappa (folklore)|kappa]].\n* [[Sun Wukong|Son Gok\u016b]] \u2013 The [[monkey]] king Sun Wukong from [[Journey to the West|''Journey to the West''.]]\n* Sunakake Baba \u2013 A witch who uses sand.\n* [[Sunekosuri]] \u2013 A dog-like [[yokai]] that rubs up against people's legs when it is raining.\n*Susanoo - the storm god, younger brother of the sun goddess Amaterasu.\n* [[Shuten-doji]] \u2013  [[Oni]]\n* [[Vermilion Bird|Suzaku]] \u2013 The Japanese version of the Chinese [[Vermilion Bird]].\n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|Suzuri-no-tamashii]] - Inkstone spirit.\n\n==T==\n*[[Takaonna|Taka-onna]] \u2013 A female monster that can stretch its waist to peer inside buildings.\n* [[Tamamo-no-Mae]] \u2013 A wicked nine-tailed [[fox]] who appeared as a courtesan.\n* [[Bake-danuki|Tanuki]] \u2013 A shape-shifting [[Japanese raccoon dog]].\n* [[Teke Teke]] \u2013 A vengeful spirit of a school girl, with a half upper torso body, who goes around killing people by slicing them in half with a scythe, mimicking her own disfigurement.\n* [[Ten (folklore)|Ten]] \u2013 A shapeshifting mischievous [[weasel]].  \n* [[Tengu]] \u2013 A wise [[demon]] with two variants: a red man with a long nose, or a bird-like [[demon]].\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#Third Volume|Tenj\u014dkudari]] - A female [[yokai]] that crawls on the ceiling. \n* [[Tenka (kaika)]] - Ghost lights\n* [[Tenko (fox)]] - Divine beast\n* [[Tennin]] \u2013 A heavenly being.\n* [[Tenome|Te-no-me]] \u2013 A ghost of a blind man with his eyes on his hands.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#First Volume|Teratsutsuki]] - The [[onry\u014d]] of a man who lived in the 6th century CE.\n* [[Gazu Hyakki Yagy\u014d|Tesso]] \u2013 A priest who was snubbed by the emperor and became a swarm of rats which laid waste to a rival temple.\n* [[T\u014dfu-koz\u014d]] \u2013 A yokai that appears as a young boy carrying a plate of tofu.\n* [[Tsuchigumo]] \u2013 A clan of spider-like [[yokai]].\n* [[Tsuchinoko]] \u2013 A legendary [[Snake|serpentine]] monster. It is now a cryptid resembling a fat [[snake]].\n* Tsukinowaguma \u2013 A legendary bear.<ref>Clarissa Pinkola Est\u00e9s, ''Women who Run with the Wolves'' (1996), Ch. 12.</ref>\n* [[Tsukuyomi]] \u2013 A moon god.\n* [[Tsukumogami]] \u2013 An animated [[tea caddy]] that [[Matsunaga Hisahide]] used to bargain a peace with [[Oda Nobunaga]]. It is now understood to mean any 100-year-old inanimate object that has come to life.\n* [[Tsurube-otoshi]] \u2013 A monster that drops out of the tops of trees.\n\n==U==\n* [[Ubume]] \u2013 The spirit of a woman who died in childbirth.\n* Uma-no-ashi \u2013 A horse's leg which dangles from a tree and kicks passersby.\n* [[Umib\u014dzu]] \u2013 A giant monster appearing on the surface of the sea.\n* Umi-ny\u014db\u014d \u2013 A female sea monster who steals fish.\n* [[Ungaiky\u014d]] \u2013 A possessed mirror.\n* [[Konjaku Gazu Zoku Hyakki#First Volume|Ushi-no-tokimairi]] \u2013 A curse done at the ox hour (between 1 and 3 in the morning) by a [[black magic]] user, with various effects.\n* [[Ushi-oni]] \u2013 A name given to an assortment of [[ox]]-headed monsters.\n* [[Kudan (y\u014dkai)#Ushi-onna|Ushi-onna]] \u2013 A kimono-clad woman with a cow head.\n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|Ushirogami]] - A one-eyed, footless spirit.\n* [[Uwan]] \u2013 A spirit named for the sound it shouts when surprising people.\n\n==W==\n* [[Gazu Hyakki Yagy\u014d|Waira]] \u2013 A large beast that lurks in the mountains, about which little is known.\n* [[Wani (dragon)|Wani]] \u2013 A water monster comparable to an [[alligator]] or [[crocodile]]. A related word has been applied to the [[saltwater crocodile]].\n* [[Wany\u016bd\u014d]] \u2013 A flaming wheel with a man's head in the center, that sucks out the soul of anyone who sees it.\n\n==Y==\n* [[Yad\u014dkai]] \u2013 Monks who have turned to mischief.\n* [[Yama-biko]] \u2013 Small creatures that create echoes.\n* [[Yamajijii]] \u2013 An old man with one eye and one leg.\n* [[Yamako]] \u2013 An [[ape]]like occasionally cannibalistic creature that can read minds. \n* [[Gazu Hyakki Tsurezure Bukuro|Yamaoroshi]] \u2013 A possessed vegetable [[grater]], almost porcupine-like in appearance.\n* [[Yamata no Orochi]] \u2013 The eight-headed dragon/[[snake|serpent]] monster slain by the god Susanoo.\n* [[wiktionary:\u5c71\u72ac|Yama-inu]] \u2013 A dog-like mountain spirit, that may appear to travelers on mountain roads; may be friendly, or may attack and kill the traveler, depending on the tale (also see the [[Japanese wolf]]).\n* [[Yama-uba]] \u2013 A [[crone]]-like y\u014dkai.\n* [[Yashima no Hage-tanuki]] \u2013 A [[bake-danuki]] that protects the [[Taira clan]].\n* [[Three-legged bird|Yatagarasu]] \u2013 The three-legged [[crow]] of Amaterasu.\n* [[Yato-no-kami]] \u2013 Deadly [[Snake]] gods which infested a field.\n* [[Yobuko]] \u2013 A mountain-dwelling spirit.\n* [[Y\u014dkai]]/Youkai \u2013 A class of supernatural monsters, spirits, and demons in Japanese folklore. They can also be called [[ayakashi (y\u014dkai)|ayakashi]] (\u5996?), [[mononoke]] (\u7269\u306e\u602a?), or mamono (\u9b54\u7269?).\n* [[Yomotsu-shikome]] \u2013 The [[hag]]s of the underworld.\n* [[Konjaku Hyakki Sh\u016bi#Third Volume \u2013 Rain|Yonakinoishi]]\n* [[Y\u014dsei]] \u2013 The Japanese word for \"[[fairy]]\".\n* [[Yosuzume]] \u2013 A mysterious bird that sings at night, sometimes indicating that the [[okuri-inu]] is near.\n* [[Yuki-onna]] \u2013 The snow woman.\n* [[Yurei]] \u2013 Ghosts in a more Western sense.\n\n==Z==\n* [[Zashiki-warashi]] \u2013 A protective childlike house spirit.\n* [[Zennyo Ry\u016b\u014d]] \u2013 A rain-making dragon.\n* [[Tsukumogami#Types of tsukumogami|Zorigami]] \u2013 An animated clock.\n* [[Zuijin]] \u2013 A tutelary spirit.\n* [[Zunbera-b\u014d]] \u2013 Another name for the [[Noppera-b\u014d]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Japanese mythology]]\n* [[Kwaidan|Kaidan]]\n{{Portal bar|Asia|Japan|Mythology|Religion}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.onmarkproductions.com/html/buddhism.shtml Photo Dictionary of Japanese Buddhist and Shinto Deities]\n* [https://hyakumonogatari.com \u767e\u7269\u8a9e\u602a\u8ac7\u4f1a Hyakumonogatari Kaidankai | Translated Japanese Ghost Stories and Tales of the Weird and the Strange], a blog by Mizuki Shigeru \n* [http://en.gigazine.net/news/20081230_youkai_bronze/ 133 Yokai Statues on Mizuki Shigeru Road]\n\n{{Japanese folklore long}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese legendary creatures| ]]\n[[Category:Y\u014dkai| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of legendary creatures|Japan]]\n[[Category:Mythological dogs|Japan]]\n[[Category:Japanese culture-related lists|Legendary creatures from Japan]]\n", "name_user": "Hudadni", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_legendary_creatures_from_Japan"}
